1. e4 c5
{ The Anti-Sicilians are a wide array of variations that offer various types of play to White - there are sharp attacks like in the Grand Prix Attack or calm play as in the Rossolimo. Some of these systems have developed a lot of theory on their own and are complex enough, sometimes on par with the lines in the open Sicilians.   The Anti-Sicilians can be very problematic, especially for the Najdorf players. The main reason lies in the move-orders that White can use to trick Black into an unfavourable transposition to an open Sicilian. In order to simplify things, and to make this repertoire suitable for other Sicilian players who play 2... d6, not only the Najdorf players, I decided to construct a repertoire that guarantees against transpositions to an open Sicilian  (the extremely rare cases where these are possible are clearly explained in the analyses)  .   As with my Najdorf repertoire, my guiding principles have been focused on understanding and less on memorisation  (so you will again find a lot of textual explanations)  and conciseness. I aimed to provide enough theoretical knowledge so that the student is confident enough, but also I tried to explain as precisely as possible the reasons behind the moves. I paid special attention to the middlegame plans and ideas so as to equip the student for the independent play after the theory ends.   I hope that after careful study of this course the students will feel confident to meet 1 e4 with 1... c5 and will look forward to anything the White player can throw at them.   Good luck ! }
*

