1. e4 c5 2. f4
{ White wants to play a reversed Dutch while at the same time preserving transpositional options to a Closed Sicilian.   2.c4  This is a move that aims to confuse Black and steer the game either into an English Opening  (you can argue this arose after 1 c4 c5 2 e4)  or into a Maroczy bind if White manages to push d4. Unless Black plays the Accelerated Fianchetto and is not against a transposition to the Maroczy, or he plays the Taimanov and can go ...e6 and ...Nc6 here, allowing d4, there isn't much leeway to avoid an unfavourable transposition, so be careful with the following variation.  Nc6  Black can also start with   2...Nf6  3.Nc3  Nc6  But please note that   2...d6  would be met by  3.Ne2  with d4 next, thus allowing White to obtain the Maroczy bind. If Black stops d4 by playing ...e5 himself, this would lead to a symmetrical position from the English Opening which gives White better chances because he would be a tempo up.  3.Ne2  If White tries to fianchetto the light-squared bishop then Black is in time to push ...d5 anyway. For example after   3.g3  Nf6  4.Bg2  e6  5.Nc3  d5 !  still works as after White takes on d5 Black will eventually recapture the pawn after ...Nb4, or in case a bishop lands on d5 then Black will have ample compensation after  6.exd5  exd5  7.Nxd5  Nxd5  8.Bxd5  Bf5  with excellent play.  3...Nf6  4.Nbc3  e6  Black will push ...d5 in order to prevent White's plan of d4.  5.d4  If   5.g3  then  d5  comes.  5...d5 !  Black has a valid alternative in   5...cxd4  6.Nxd4  Bb4  but this leads to a line of the Taimanov Variation. This line became popular lately, so I prefer to avoid it, especially as 5... d5 leads to good play for Black.  6.cxd5  exd5  7.Bg5  The only way to pose problems.  After   7.e5  Black has  Ng4  and White's centre collapses after  8.h3  cxd4 !  7...cxd4  Eliminating the possibility of dxc5 after ...Be7.  8.Nxd4  If   8.Nxd5  then  Qa5+  9.Bd2  Qd8  and White can take a repetition if he wants to, implying that Black is at least equal here.  8...Be7  Unpinning and preparing castling. Black manages to finish development quickly, which makes him well-prepared to deal with the tension in the centre.  9.Bb5  If   9.e5  then after  Nd7  White's pawn on e5 will need protection.  9...Bd7  Unpinning again.  10.Bxc6  If   10.e5  then  Ne4  is good.  After   10.exd5  Nxd5  is possible thanks to the fact that the bishop on g5 is attacked. A further  11.Nxd5  Bxg5  12.Qe2+  Kf8  is good for Black as he remains with the pair of bishops while the uncastled king doesn't cause problems in view of the idea of ...g6 and ...Kg7 later on.  10...bxc6  Keeping the pair of bishops.  11.O-O  If   11.exd5  then  Nxd5  12.Bxe7  Qxe7+  is with check, allowing time for ...Nc3, which would wreck White's structure. Hence White castles.  11...Nxe4  Taking the pawn and now White risks to remain without material. His best is to transpose to an equal endgame after the forced sequence  12.Bxe7  Qxe7  13.Re1  O-O  Getting away from the centre.  14.f3  Nxc3  Now everything is exchanged and at the end White will recuperate the pawn.  15.Rxe7  Nxd1  16.Rxd7  Nxb2  17.Nxc6  Now both a7 and d5 hang. The endgame is equal in many ways, one is the active  Rfe8  18.Rxd5  Rac8  19.Nxa7  Rc2  When after opening a luft by ...g6 Black will play ...Ree2.   2.b4 ?!  The Wing Gambit isn't very serious and Black's best reaction is to play in the centre after taking the pawn.  cxb4  3.a3  If   3.d4  then also  d5  3...d5  Following the rules - play in the centre is the best antidote to wing provocations.  4.exd5  Qxd5  5.Nf3  e5  Expanding in the centre and defending the pawn on b4.  6.axb4  After   6.Bb2  Nc6  7.axb4  Bxb4  8.c4  Qd6  Black has excellent play, as the 'combination'  9.Nxe5  doesn't work in more than one way. Here's the simplest:  Nxe5  10.Qe2  f6  11.f4  Bg4  12.fxe5  Bxe2  13.exd6  Bxf1  14.Kxf1  Bxd6  with a clear pawn up in the endgame.  6...Bxb4  7.Na3  The idea is to come to c4. White's play does look artificial, so it's not surprising that Black is already better.  Nf6  Continuing normal development and preparing castling. Black is a pawn up and has development advantage !  8.Nc4  Threatening both the pawn on e5 and Nb6, but these are easily parried by  e4  Though truth be told, Black could even sacrifice the exchange and play   8...Nc6  9.Nb6  axb6  10.Rxa8  O-O  with an almost winning position !  9.Ne3  Qh5  The simplest, forcing an exchange of queens and an endgame where Black will be a pawn up.  10.Nd4  Qxd1+  11.Nxd1  O-O  With a clear pawn up and absolutely no compensation for White.   2.b3  The fianchetto of the dark-squared bishop does not pretend to seek advantage, but White gets a playable position with a lot of pieces on the board. If White wants to play b3 it makes sense to do it immediately, as opposed to 2.Nf3 d6 3.b3 as with the knight on f3 there are no ideas based on f2-f4.  Nc6  Black will develop in Scheveningen style, with his pieces in the centre and ready to react to whatever White tries.  3.Bb2  d6  A multi-purpose move: if allowed Black would want to close the long diagonal by ...e5 and then develop by ...g6, ...Bg7, ...Nge7, ...O-O and then to push either ...f5 with kingside attack or ...d5 with central play; on the other hand, the move allows for ...Bd7 after White's next move, thus avoiding the doubling of the c-pawns if White takes on c6.  4.Bb5  Bd7  Of course, Black wants to take on c6 with a bishop.  5.f4  Preventing ...e5.  Nf6  Since ...e5 has been prevented, Black continues in Scheveningen style, with ...e6 and ...Be7 to come next.  6.Qe2  Taking on f6 would be great for Black, who would take with the e-pawn and remain with an unopposed dark-squared bishop that will be developed on g7 after ...g6 and later opened up by ...f5.  e6  7.Nf3  Be7  Black finished his development and the only thing that remains is the position of the king. But Black needn't hurry with this decision, as he has useful moves at his disposal, like ...a6 and possibly a queenside expansion by ...b5. To make it safer, Black would wait for White to castle kingside before he does the same. If White decides to castle queenside, then Black can even leave the king in the centre for a while and start queenside expansion by ...a6 and ...b5 as described above.  8.O-O  On any other move Black would play ...a6.  The push   8.e5  isn't dangerous in view of  Nd5  attacking the f4-pawn, and after  9.exd6  Bxd6  10.g3  Black can now safely castle  O-O  with the threat of ...Ndb4 while ...a6 is always on the cards.  8...O-O  With both kings on the kingside Black is perfectly safe.  9.d3  a6  Black wins the bishop pair and even though the position is rather closed this is good for his long-term prospects.  10.Bxc6  Bxc6  11.Nbd2  b5  Black has a very pleasant position. He expands on the queenside in typical Sicilian fashion while the potentially strong and unopposed bishop on c6 effectively prevents any central breaks like e5 and f5 as that would open the long diagonal  (in the latter case after ...ef)  . Other ideas for Black may include the ...d5 break with the idea to force e5 and then play ...d4, opening the long diagonal  (obviously, the knight from f6 would have to be moved first)  , or the exchange of the dark-squared bishops by ...Nd7 and ...Bf6, thus weakening the dark squares on the queenside.   2.a3  An odd move, as preparing b4 really shouldn't be on top of White's priorities.  g6  Since the long diagonal will be opened, it makes sense to put the bishop on it.  3.b4  Continuing with the idea started on move 2.  Changing tack with   3.d4  is harmless after  cxd4  4.Qxd4  Nf6  because  5.e5  is bad in view of  Nc6  and White has problems with e5-pawn in view of the ...Qa5 threat.  On the other hand,   3.Nc3  would likely transpose to something similar to the Grand Prix Attack after  Bg7  4.Bc4  Nc6  with White already committed to the move a3.  3...Bg7  4.Nc3  d6  Preparing the development of the knight on g8.  5.Rb1  Nf6  With ...O-O to follow and then depending on circumstances Black will finish development by ...Nc6 or ...Nbd7 and develop the bishop from c8 either on b7  (after ...b6)  or on the h3-c8 diagonal.   2.g3  Will transpose elsewhere after  Nc6  3.Bg2  g6  4.d3  Bg7  And now  5.f4  On the other hand   5.Nf3  d6  is analysed under 2. Nf3 d6 3. g3.  5...d6  is either analysed under the Closed Sicilian if White plays Nc3 at some point or under 2. f4 if he doesn't.   2.d3  Nc6  Doesn't have an independent value, as it will transpose elsewhere, for example  3.Nf3   3.f4  transposes to 2. f4.   3.g3  d6  4.Bg2  g6  5.Nc3  transposes to the Closed Sicilian.  while   5.f4  transposes to 2. f4.  3...d6  4.g3  g6  transposes to 2. Nf3 d6 3. g3.   2.Na3  This is not as silly as it appears. The move Na3 is typical for the Alapin Sicilian so White tries to steer the game towards those lines while at the same time keeping Rossolimo ideas like Bb5 and g3, Bg2 plans at his disposal.  d5  Just like in the Alapin, this seems simplest.  3.exd5  Giving check by   3.Bb5+  is met by  Nc6  and White cannot go along the positional lines after  4.Bxc6+  bxc6  5.d3  because after  e5  Black's full centre, bishop pair and the stranded knight on a3 all outweigh the doubled c-pawns.  3...Qxd5  4.Nf3  Nc6  Developing and controlling d4. If Black manages to prevent d4 then he will have a very comfortable position.  Ideally Black would want to play ...Bg4, but playing it now is met by   4...Bg4  5.Nb5 !  Threatening Nc7 and d4, and White forces a playable endgame after  Bxf3  6.Nc7+  Kd7  7.Nxd5  Bxd1  8.Kxd1  e6  9.Ne3  though this is certainly very playable for Black after  Nc6  when Black's central control compensates for White's bishop pair.  5.Bc4  Qd8  Going back to d8 avoids possible Nb5 ideas by White.  6.c3  White's only active plan is to try to push d4.  Nf6  7.d4  e6  In order to finish development Black temporarily closes the bishop on c8, but it will most likely be developed along the long diagonal after ...a6 and ...b5.  8.O-O  cxd4  This forces favourable simplifications.  9.Nb5  White cannot afford to make himself an IQP because Black will calmly finish development by ...Be7 and ...O-O and then will play either ...a6, ...b5 and ...Bb7 or ...b6 and ...Bb7 when all his pieces will be ideally placed, which cannot be said for White with his knight on a3.  a6  The useful move is played with a tempo.  10.Nbxd4  Nxd4  11.Nxd4  Bd6  With good play for Black who will continue with ...Qc7, ...O-O and then he will develop the bishop on c8 either by playing ...b5 and ...Bb7, ...Bd7-c6 or even ...e5, depending on circumstances.   2.Be2  Will transpose to the lines analysed under 2. f4 after  Nc6  3.f4  g6  4.Nf3  Bg7   2.Ne2  Similar to 2. c4 this move aims for a Maroczy structure after c4 and d4. Now unless Black plays the Accelerated Fianchetto and allows the Maroczy, in which case he can play 2... d6, allowing 3. c4 and then d4, or he plays the Taimanov and he plays 2... e6 allowing 3. c4 and then d4, he has only one acceptable move here and that one is  Nf6 !  Attacking the e4-pawn and forcing White's next move, thus preventing c4.  3.Nbc3  If   3.e5  then after  Ng4  White has to play  4.f4  in order to defend e5.   4.d4  cxd4  5.Qxd4  d6  is good for Black after  6.exd6  Nc6 !  7.Qd2  In order to have Nf4 against Qb6.  e5  with excellent play for Black.  4...d6  5.h3  Nh6  Black will take on e5 when the e5-pawn will need constant defence.  3...d5  The move   3...d6  would lead to a transposition to a fianchetto line of another open Sicilian after  4.g3  For example, after  g6  after   4...a6  5.Bg2  Nc6  6.d4  cxd4  7.Nxd4  we have a Scheveningen after  Bd7  followed by ...e6.  5.d4  cxd4  6.Nxd4  we have a Dragon. So if Black doesn't want to enter that territory he has little choice. Therefore the move to play is 3...d5.  On the other hand,   3...Nc6  is perfectly acceptable for Sveshnikov players.  4.exd5  The move   4.e5  is dubious as after  Ng4  5.f4  h5  followed by ...e6, ...Nh6-f5, ...Nc6 Black would have a fantastic position. He can then finish development by ...b6, ...Bb7, ...Be7, ...Qd7, castle long and start attack on the kingside by preparing ...f6 and ...g5.  4...Nxd5  5.Nxd5  Qxd5  6.d4  The alternative is   6.Nc3  when after  Qe5+  7.Be2  Bg4  8.O-O  Bxe2  9.Nxe2  Nc6  Black is comfortably equal. He will finish development by ...e6 and ...Be7  (or ...g6 and ...Bg7)  and will play on the d-file.  6...e5  Attacking the centre.  7.Nc3  Taking on e5 is harmless, as after   7.dxe5  Qxe5  8.c3  Be7  Black will castle with a good position.  7...Qxd4  8.Be3  White tries to prove that his lead in development and the active pieces compensate for the pawn.  In case of   8.Bd3  trying to avoid the exchange of queens, Black develops smoothly and castles queenside, when White won't have compensation for the pawn. After  Bg4 !  Provoking a weakening.  9.f3  Be6  10.Qe2  Nc6  11.Be3  Qb4  12.O-O-O  O-O-O  Black is a pawn up for practically nothing.  8...Bg4 !  Again, this disruptive move that forces further exchanges.  9.Bxd4  Bxd1  10.Bxe5  Bxc2  11.Kd2  Bf5  It is not very likely that White will return the pawn, so he must bank on his activity. This puts more pressure on White to play precise moves because if he fails to do so he will simply be a pawn down for nothing. After  12.Re1  Kd7  13.Kc1  Nc6  Black is fine as after  14.Rd1+  Ke8  The king intends to hide on g6 after ...f6 and ...Kf7.   2.Bc4  This looks amateurish, but it is again important for Black to be careful with the possible transpositions to an open Sicilian. The best plan here is to go for a quick ...d5, thus underlying the problematic nature of the early development of the bishop.  e6  Blunting the bishop immediately.  Dragon players can play   2...Nc6  3.Nf3  g6  and if  4.c3  then  Nf6  intending  5.d3   5.e5  d5  5...d6  with a transposition to the line with 3 Bc4.  3.Nf3  The move   3.Nc3  would likely transpose after  a6  3...a6  This move covers b5 so now when ... d5 is played White won't have the check from b5.  4.Nc3  This move prevents ...d5.  Bear in mind that after   4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  Nf6  After   5...Nc6  it's a Taimanov with an odd bishop on c4.   5...Qc7  is a great Kan for Black as it immediately hits the bishop on c4.  6.Nc3  d6  we have a transposition to the Sozin Variation in the Najdorf.  4...b5  5.Be2  Bb7  This prevents d4 as then after the exchange on d4 White will be forced to awkwardly recapture with the queen because taking with the knight would lose the e4-pawn after ...b4.  6.d3  Qc7  With a very good position for Black - he will develop with ...Nf6  (or ...Ne7-g6)  , ... Nc6 and has the option to play in the centre by ...d5 or even ...f5  (especially if the knight is on g6)  . White on the other hand wasted time with the light-squared bishop and is very passive. }
2... g6
{ It is important to start with this move.   2...Nc6  allows  3.Nf3  g6  4.Bb5 }
3. Nf3
{ The alternatives are harmless. For example, after   3.c3  d5  White has an inferior version of the Alapin, so he must continue  4.e5  but then after  4...Nc6  5.Nf3  Bg4  6.h3  Bxf3  7.Qxf3  e6  Black has an excellent French without the bad bishop. He will continue with ...h5, ...Nge7-f5, ...Qb6 with very comfortable play.  Another alternative is   3.d4  cxd4  4.Nf3  White is trying to transpose to the Classical Dragon. In case of   4.Qxd4  Nf6  5.e5  Nc6  6.Qd3  Nh5  followed by ...d6, and White's centre will collapse.  4...Bg7  5.Nxd4  d5  A nice move to avoid the transposition to the Dragon.  6.e5  Nc6  7.Nc3  Nh6  Black will follow up with ...0-0 and then ...Nf5 or even ...f6, and White will find it difficult to hold his centre. }
3... Bg7
{ Now White is on a crossroad - he should decide whether he wants to develop his light-squared bishop on g2 or e2. In both cases Black develops the same: ...Nc6, ...d6, ...e6 and ...Nge7. }
4. Be2
{ 4.d3  Nc6  Black continues development along the usual lines of ...d6, ...e6 and ...Nge7.  5.g3  d6  6.Bg2  e6  Black's set-up is very flexible. His general play is as follows: he intends to place the knight on e7, controlling the f5-square  (thus preventing a possible kingside attack after f5 by White)  , castle and then depending on circumstances to play ...b5-b4 with queenside attack or play in the centre by pushing ...d5 or ...f5.  7.O-O  Nge7  8.c3  Note that   8.Nc3  would transpose to the Closed Sicilian.  8...O-O  9.Be3  b5  Immediately starting queenside activity.  10.d4  White cannot really stop ...b4.  If he plays   10.a3  then  a5  followed by ...Bb7 or ...Ba6, when ...b4 will inevitably come.  10...cxd4  The pawn was attacked, so Black takes before continuing his queenside play.  11.cxd4  Taking with the knight and keeping the d-file open gives Black good play after   11.Nxd4  Nxd4  12.Bxd4  e5 !  13.Be3  Be6  with a good Sicilian position with typical queenside play after ...Qc7, ...Nc6 etc.  11...Na5  With the obvious idea to jump to c4, but also opening the long diagonal for the bishop.  12.b3  Bb7  Attacking e4. Black's play here is based on attacking and controlling the light squares in the centre.  13.Nbd2  f5 !  The key move, whose idea is to obtain control of the light squares in the centre like d5 and f5.  14.e5  If White keeps the tension then Black will play some preparatory moves like   14.Qb1  Nac6  and then at an appropriate moment will take on e4 and put the knights on f5 and d5.  14...Nd5  The knight is untouchable here.  15.Bf2  Rc8  With excellent play for Black. His centralised knight on d5 dominates the position and he will continue his play on the queenside by means of ...Nc6-b4 or ...b4, fixing the c3-square and later on perhaps advancing ...a5-a4. A good preparatory move would be ...Qd7, connecting the rooks and perhaps preparing for doubling on the c-file.  Note that   4.c3  is met by  d5  when after  5.e5  Nc6  6.d4  cxd4  7.cxd4  Bg4  White will have problems with the d4-pawn after moves like ...Qb6, ...e6, ...Nge7-f5 with ...h5 at some point in order to secure the knight on f5. }
4... Nc6 5. O-O d6
{ It is better to start with ...d6 as playing ...e6 first may invite e5 by White. }
6. d3
{ If White attempts to build a centre by   6.c3  an important move to play is  f5 !  It attacks the e4-pawn and prevents d4. Then after  7.d3  Nf6  Black has good play and he can quickly become the attacking side after  8.exf5  Bxf5  9.Nh4  Bd7  10.f5  This aggressive attempt by White backfires simply because Black can castle queenside.  Qc7  11.fxg6  O-O-O !  with initiative and attack on the kingside along the open g and h-files. }
6... e6
{ Black develops in the most flexible way. By putting the knight on e7 he controls the f5-pushes by White. He will then castle and start queenside activities by pushing ...b5-b4. He also has the move ...f5 at his disposal, whose aim is to fight for the light squares in the centre by either provoking the e4-pawn to move or by taking it  (this is particularly valid after White had played d4, but we will see that it's possible to play ...f5 even before White pushes d4)  . }
7. c3
{ Putting a knight on c3 makes no sense as the knight will just get in the way after ...b5-b4. }
7... Nge7 8. Be3
{ White's plan is to push d4 and obtain a full centre. Black combats this centre by flexible development.  The immediate   8.d4 ?!  is not good in view of  cxd4  9.cxd4  Qb6  when White cannot defend both d4 and b2. }
8... O-O 9. Nbd2
{ White has other options as well.  The immediate push   9.d4  is met by  f5  10.e5  Nd5  11.Qd2  a6  followed by ...b5. Black has a very good position thanks to his control over the light squares and will finish development by ...Bb7.  After   9.Na3  Black continues with  a6  with the idea of ...b5 and if  10.d4  then the already familiar  f5  fighting for the light squares.  or   10...cxd4  followed by ...b5. For a good example how this should be played please take a look at the model game Larsen-Fischer. }
9... f5
{ Black is almost developed so he doesn't need to wait for White's d4 in order to push ...f5 himself. This move creates a tension in the centre that favours Black because White cannot release that tension - taking on f5 is not really an option for White since it will allow Black to obtain a big central mass after ...gxf5 or a great square for the knight after ...Nxf5. The f5-push also stops White's central play connected with d4 since then Black would take on e4 and obtain excellent light-square control in the centre thanks to the control and access to the d5 and f5-squares. }
10. Bf2 { Getting away from possible attacks from f5 or d5. } 10... b6
{ Since now the main play is in the centre, Black won't play ...b5, but rather 10... b6, which lends extra support to the c5-pawn. His plan is to develop by ...Bb7 and ...Qd7 and then he will concentrate on the ...e5 push. He may also consider playing ...h6 and ...Kh7 which at some later stage may introduce ...g5 ideas. His piece coordination is better for this central confrontation because his fianchettoed bishops are controlling the centre and are not in the way on the central files which can be used by the rooks.   White's pieces, on the other hand, feel as if they are stepping on each other's toes and he has no active plans. The position offers Black excellent prospects in the ensuing middlegame. }
