[Black "2.c4 Variation 9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c4
{ This is a move that aims to confuse Black and steer the game either into an English Opening - you can argue this arose after 1.c4 c5 2.e4 - or into a Maroczy bind if White manages to push d4. Unless Black plays the Accelerated Fianchetto and is not against a transposition to the Maroczy, or he plays the Taimanov and can go ...e6 and ...Nc6 here, allowing d4, there isn't much leeway to avoid an unfavourable transposition, so be careful with the following variation. }
2... Nc6 3. Ne2 Nf6 4. Nbc3 e6
{ Black will push . ..d5 in order to prevent White's plan of d4. } 5. d4 d5 6.
cxd5 exd5 7. Bg5 { The only way to pose problems. } 7... cxd4
{ Eliminating the possibility of dxc5 after ... Be7. } 8. Nxd4 Be7
{ Unpinning and preparing castling. Black manages to finish development quickly, which makes him well-prepared to deal with the tension in the centre. }
9. Bb5 Bd7 { Unpinning again. } 10. Bxc6 bxc6 { Keeping the pair of bishops. }
11. O-O Nxe4
{ Taking the pawn and now White risks to remain without material. His best is to transpose to an equal endgame after the forced sequence }
12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. Re1 O-O { Getting away from the centre. } 14. f3 Nxc3
{ Now everything is exchanged and at the end White will recuperate the pawn. }
15. Rxe7 Nxd1 16. Rxd7 Nxb2 17. Nxc6
{ Now both a7 and d5 hang. The endgame is equal in many ways, one is the active }
17... Rfe8 18. Rxd5 Rac8 19. Nxa7 Rc2
{ When after opening a luft by ...g6 Black will play ...Ree2. } *

