1. e4 c5 2. Na3
{ This is not as silly as it appears. The move Na3 is typical for the Alapin Sicilian so White tries to steer the game towards those lines while at the same time keeping Rossolimo ideas like Bb5 and g3, Bg2 plans at his disposal. }
2... d5 { Just like in the Alapin, this seems simplest. } 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. Nf3
Nc6
{ Developing and controlling d4. If Black manages to prevent d4 then he will have a very comfortable position. }
5. Bc4 Qd8 { Going back to d8 avoids possible Nb5 ideas by White. } 6. c3
{ White's only active plan is to try to push d4. } 6... Nf6 7. d4 e6
{ In order to finish development Black temporarily closes the bishop on c8, but it will most likely be developed along the long diagonal after ...a6 and ...b5. }
8. O-O cxd4 { This forces favourable simplifications. } 9. Nb5
{ White cannot afford to make himself an IQP because Black will calmly finish development by ...Be7 and ...O-O and then will play either ...a6, ...b5 and ...Bb7 or ...b6 and ...Bb7 when all his pieces will be ideally placed, which cannot be said for White with his knight on a3. }
9... a6 { The useful move is played with a tempo. } 10. Nbxd4 Nxd4 11. Nxd4 Bd6
{ With good play for Black who will continue with ...Qc7, ...O-O and then he will develop the bishop on c8 either by playing ...b5 and ...Bb7, ... Bd7-c6 or even ...e5, depending on circumstances. }
*

