1. e4 c5 2. Bc4
{ This looks amateurish, but it is again important for Black to be careful with the possible transpositions to an open Sicilian. The best plan here is to go for a quick ... d5, thus underlying the problematic nature of the early development of the bishop. }
2... e6 { Blunting the bishop immediately. } 3. Nf3 a6
{ This move covers b5 so now when ... d5 is played White won't have the check from b5. }
4. Nc3 { This move prevents ...d5. } 4... b5 5. Be2 Bb7
{ This prevents d4 as then after the exchange on d4 White will be forced to awkwardly recapture with the queen because taking with the knight would lose the e4-pawn after ...b4. }
6. d3 Qc7
{ With a very good position for Black - he will develop with ...Nf6  (or ...Ne7-g6)  , ...Nc6 and has the option to play in the centre by ...d5 or even ...f5  (especially if the knight is on g6)  . White on the other hand wasted time with the light-squared bishop and is very passive. }
