1. e4 c5 2. f4
{ White wants to play a reversed Dutch while at the same time preserving transpositional options to a Closed Sicilian. }
2... g6 { It is important to start with this move. } 3. Nf3 Bg7
{ Now White is on a crossroad - he should decide whether he wants to develop his light-squared bishop on g2 or e2. In both cases Black develops the same: ...Nc6, ...d6, ...e6 and ...Nge7. }
4. d3 Nc6
{ Black continues development along the usual lines of ...d6, ...e6 and ...Nge7. }
5. g3 d6 6. Bg2 e6
{ Black's set-up is very flexible. His general play is as follows: he intends to place the knight on e7, controlling the f5-square  (thus preventing a possible kingside attack after f5 by White)  , castle and then depending on circumstances to play ...b5-b4 with queenside attack or play in the centre by pushing ...d5 or ...f5. }
7. O-O Nge7 8. c3 O-O 9. Be3 b5 { If he plays } 10. a3 { then } 10... a5
{ followed by ...Bb7 or ...Ba6, when ...b4 will inevitably come. } *

