{ White wants to play a reversed Dutch while at the same time preserving transpositional options to a Closed Sicilian. }
2... g6 { It is important to start with this move. } 3. Nf3 Bg7
{ Now White is on a crossroad - he should decide whether he wants to develop his light-squared bishop on g2 or e2. In both cases Black develops the same: ...Nc6, ...d6, ...e6 and ...Nge7. }
4. d3 Nc6
{ Black continues development along the usual lines of ...d6, ...e6 and ...Nge7. }
5. g3 d6 6. Bg2 e6
{ Black's set-up is very flexible. His general play is as follows: he intends to place the knight on e7, controlling the f5-square  (thus preventing a possible kingside attack after f5 by White)  , castle and then depending on circumstances to play ...b5-b4 with queenside attack or play in the centre by pushing ...d5 or ...f5. }
7. O-O Nge7 8. c3 O-O 9. Be3 b5 { Immediately starting queenside activity. }
10. d4 { White cannot really stop ...b4. } 10... cxd4
{ The pawn was attacked, so Black takes before continuing his queenside play. }
11. cxd4 Na5
{ With the obvious idea to jump to c4, but also opening the long diagonal for the bishop. }
12. b3 Bb7
{ Attacking e4. Black's play here is based on attacking and controlling the light squares in the centre. }
13. Nbd2 f5
{ The key move, whose idea is to obtain control of the light squares in the centre like d5 and f5. }
14. e5 Nd5 { The knight is untouchable here. } 15. Bf2 Rc8
{ With excellent play for Black. His centralised knight on d5 dominates the position and he will continue his play on the queenside by means of ...Nc6-b4 or ...b4, fixing the c3-square and later on perhaps advancing ...a5-a4. A good preparatory move would be ...Qd7, connecting the rooks and perhaps preparing for doubling on the c-file. }
