[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Various 2nd Moves"]
[Black "2.f4 Variation 13"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. f4
{ White wants to play a reversed Dutch while at the same time preserving transpositional options to a Closed Sicilian. }
2... g6 { It is important to start with this move. } 3. Nf3 Bg7
{ Now White is on a crossroad - he should decide whether he wants to develop his light-squared bishop on g2 or e2. In both cases Black develops the same: ...Nc6, ...d6, ...e6 and ...Nge7. }
4. Be2 Nc6 5. O-O d6
{ It is better to start with ...d6 as playing ...e6 first may invite e5 by White. }
6. d3 e6
{ Black develops in the most flexible way. By putting the knight on e7 he controls the f5-pushes by White. He will then castle and start queenside activities by pushing ...b5-b4. He also has the move ...f5 at his disposal, whose aim is to fight for the light squares in the centre by either provoking the e4-pawn to move or by taking it  (this is particularly valid after White had played d4, but we will see that it's possible to play ...f5 even before White pushes d4)  . }
7. c3
{ Putting a knight on c3 makes no sense as the knight will just get in the way after ...b5-b4. }
7... Nge7 8. Be3
{ White's plan is to push d4 and obtain a full centre. Black combats this centre by flexible development. }
8... O-O 9. Nbd2 { White has other options as well. } 9... f5
{ Black is almost developed so he doesn't need to wait for White's d4 in order to push ...f5 himself. This move creates a tension in the centre that favours Black because White cannot release that tension - taking on f5 is not really an option for White since it will allow Black to obtain a big central mass after ...gxf5 or a great square for the knight after ...Nxf5. The f5-push also stops White's central play connected with d4 since then Black would take on e4 and obtain excellent light-square control in the centre thanks to the control and access to the d5 and f5-squares. }
10. Bf2 { Getting away from possible attacks from f5 or d5. } 10... b6
{ Since now the main play is in the centre, Black won't play ...b5, but rather 10... b6, which lends extra support to the c5-pawn. His plan is to develop by ...Bb7 and ...Qd7 and then he will concentrate on the ...e5 push. He may also consider playing ...h6 and ...Kh7 which at some later stage may introduce ...g5 ideas. His piece coordination is better for this central confrontation because his fianchettoed bishops are controlling the centre and are not in the way on the central files which can be used by the rooks.   White's pieces, on the other hand, feel as if they are stepping on each other's toes and he has no active plans. The position offers Black excellent prospects in the ensuing middlegame. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Morra Gambit"]
[Black "The Morra Gambit Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. d4 cxd4 3. c3
{ The notorious Morra  (or Smith-Morra)  Gambit. The gambit is quite an exciting and very aggressive choice against the Sicilian and can be very dangerous. If accepted, White's play is automatic and easy, which is very important in a practical game. }
3... e5
{ A very rare line against the Morra whose idea is to turn the tables on the gambiteer. After this move White has two options, neither of which is in line with the aggressive intentions of the gambit. The first option is to go for an equal endgame and the second one is to accept a piece sacrifice but to allow to be attacked long-term. As you can see, this is not what a gambiteer is expecting when playing his favourite gambit ! }
4. Nf3
{ If White takes immediately on d4, then after   4.cxd4  exd4  5.Nf3  would transpose back to the main line after 5. cxd4. }
4... Nc6 5. Bc4
{ With this move White chooses the second option - to accept a sacrifice and subject himself to a long-term attack.   5.cxd4  Is the other option, going for an equal endgame.  exd4  6.Nxd4  Nf6  7.Nc3  Bb4  This resembles the Scotch Four Knights, only here without the c-pawns.  8.Nxc6  dxc6  Connecting the pawns and forcing the exchange of queens.  9.Qxd8+  Avoiding the exchange by   9.Bd3  isn't dangerous as after  O-O  10.O-O  Qa5  followed by ...Be6 and ...Rad8 Black has smooth play.  9...Kxd8  10.f3  Be6  The endgame is comfortable for Black. He will continue with ...Ke7 to connect the rooks and then according to circumstance, ...Nd7-e5   c5  or ...Bc5, one rook will come to the d-file. An idea in the future may be the ...f5 push, to eliminate the e4-pawn that gives White space advantage in the centre. }
5... Nf6 { Now the game resembles the Two Knights Defence. } 6. Ng5
{ Note that   6.Qb3 ?  is bad in view of  Na5  and White cannot take on f7 as after  7.Bxf7+  Ke7  the queen cannot maintain the defence of the bishop.  The move   6.cxd4  is also harmless, in view of  Bb4+  7.Nc3  Covering with the bishop   7.Bd2  is met by  Bxd2+  8.Nbxd2  exd4  9.e5  Ng4  followed by ...O-O which is also fine for Black.  7...Nxe4  8.O-O  Bxc3  9.dxe5  Nxe5  10.Bd5  Nf6  11.bxc3  d6  and the maximum White can hope for is to exchange his bishop pair in order to take the d6-pawn which would result in an equal position where Black will still have the better structure in view of the c3-pawn. }
6... d5 { The only way to defend f7. } 7. exd5 Na5
{ The moves are the same as in the Two Knights. } 8. Bb5+ Bd7 9. Qe2
{ 9.Qa4  This is an alternative that implicitly admits Black's powerful compensation in the main line.  9...Be7  Black will quickly finish development by castling next and is at least equal in the ensuing positions.  10.cxd4  This is critical as White again goes after material.  Against other moves Black is fine, for example   10.O-O  O-O  11.Bxd7  Nxd7  12.Ne4  Rc8  with the threat of ...Rc4 in case White takes on d4.  10...exd4  11.Bxd7+  Qxd7 !  This piece sacrifice is very strong. The idea is based on the surprisingly awkward position of the queen on a5.  12.Qxa5  Nxd5  The threat is ...Bb4, trapping the queen.  13.a3  Bxg5  Eliminating the knight and allowing for the next check.  14.Bxg5  Qe6+  15.Kf1  O-O  With excellent compensation for Black who has easy play along the open files and against White's king stuck in the centre. }
9... Bd6
{ Defending the pawn on e5 and preparing castling. Black sacrifices the knight on a5, which doesn't have a square to go to, in order to finish his development and push back White's pieces. }
10. b4
{ If   10.cxd4  then after  O-O  Black is almost winning thanks to his development advantage and White's awkward pieces. }
10... h6 { First the knight is pushed back. } 11. Nf3
{ Going to e4 is bad, as after   11.Ne4  Nxe4  12.Bxd7+  Qxd7  13.Qxe4  Nc4  Black has an overwhelming position without the need to sacrifice anything - White still needs to finish development and has the worse structure. }
11... O-O
{ Black is fully developed, but the price to pay was the knight on a5. Still, after }
12. bxa5 d3
{ Is a nice move to make, as White cannot take on d3 in view of the fork after ...e4. }
13. Qb2 e4
{ Defending the advanced pawn on d3 and gaining more time to develop the initiative. }
14. Nd4 Be5
{ A nice move, creating the threat to take on d4 and take on a5, thus winning the bishop on b5. }
15. O-O Nxd5
{ Taking the pawn and centralising the knight. Black has only one pawn for the piece, but the pawns on d3 and e4 make his position easy to play while White cannot easily finish development. If allowed, he will play ...Rc8, ...f5 with a terrific bind. Even with White aiming for simplifications after }
16. Bxd7 Qxd7 17. Qb5 { Doesn't help White because after } 17... Qxb5 18. Nxb5
f5
{ The pressure on c3 makes Black's play very easy by piling up on the c-file while White finds it impossible to develop his queenside without shedding more pawns. }
