1. e4 c5 2. d4 cxd4 3. c3
{ The notorious Morra  (or Smith-Morra)  Gambit. The gambit is quite an exciting and very aggressive choice against the Sicilian and can be very dangerous. If accepted, White's play is automatic and easy, which is very important in a practical game. }
3... e5
{ A very rare line against the Morra whose idea is to turn the tables on the gambiteer. After this move White has two options, neither of which is in line with the aggressive intentions of the gambit. The first option is to go for an equal endgame and the second one is to accept a piece sacrifice but to allow to be attacked long-term. As you can see, this is not what a gambiteer is expecting when playing his favourite gambit! }
4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Bc4
{ With this move White chooses the second option - to accept a sacrifice and subject himself to a long-term attack. }
5... Nf6 { Now the game resembles the Two Knights Defence. } 6. Ng5 d5
{ The only way to defend f7. } 7. exd5 Na5
{ The moves are the same as in the Two Knights. } 8. Bb5+ Bd7 9. Qa4
{ Is an alternative that implicitly admits Black's powerful compensation in the main line. }
9... Be7
{ Black will quickly finish development by castling next and is at least equal in the ensuing positions. }
10. cxd4 { This is critical as White again goes after material. } 10... exd4
11. Bxd7+ Qxd7
{ This piece sacrifice is very strong. The idea is based on the surprisingly awkward position of the queen on a5. }
12. Qxa5 Nxd5 { The threat is ...Bb4, trapping the queen. } 13. a3 Bxg5
{ Eliminating the knight and allowing for the next check. } 14. Bxg5 Qe6+ 15.
Kf1 O-O
{ With excellent compensation for Black who has easy play along the open files and against White's king stuck in the centre. }
