[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Alapin Variation"]
[Black "The Alapin Variation Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ The Alapin Variation is a very popular option against the Sicilian because it is relatively easy to play with White. }
2... d5
{ The central push is one of the main lines and gives Black free play. } 3.
exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nc6
{ Black develops the queenside first. This will be useful in the lines where White takes on c5 so that a quick ...O-O-O is possible. }
5. Nf3
{ 5.dxc5  Leads to a sharp endgame where Black has the initiative.  Qxd1+  6.Kxd1  e5  Taking central space. Black sacrificed the c5-pawn for two factors: development advantage and the awkward position of the king on d1, stuck in the centre that hinders White's coordination.  7.b4  In case of   7.Be3  Nf6  (with the idea of ...Nd5)  8.f3  (liberating f2 for the bishop)  Nd7  9.b4  a5  10.Bb5  Nf6  is a move to remember, Black wants to return to d5 now that the b4-pawn can be attacked. If White defends it after  11.a3  Nd5  12.Bd2  Be7  followed by ...O-O, ...Rd8 and ...Be6 Black has excellent compensation. White's knight on b1 and rook on a1 cannot easily join the game while Black can further improve his position by ...f5, ...Bf6.  7...a5  Attacking White's queenside.  8.Bb5  The only way to keep the extra pawn.  Nge7  The knight aims for d5. From there it attacks the b4-pawn but it can also go to f4.  9.Nf3  f6  Securely defending the e5-pawn.  10.a3  Again the only way for White to defend the b4-pawn.  Nd5  11.Bb2  Defending the rook on a1, but this leaves the f4-square without control.  Nf4  Now White has problems with the g2-pawn.  12.Ne1  The move   12.g3  allows  Bg4  and after  13.Nbd2  O-O-O  Black has great play against White's king in the centre.  12...Bf5  Black develops, takes control of the d3 and c2-squares and wants to castle long to join the rook in the attack. An illustrative line of Black's potential is  13.g3  O-O-O+  14.Nd2  Nh3  15.Rf1  g6 !  with the idea of ...Bh6 with a very strong attack.   5.Be3  This move is rarely played and it gives Black easy play after  cxd4  6.cxd4  e5  Black is better prepared for the central confrontation.  7.Nc3  Bb4  Black develops quickly.  8.Nf3  exd4  White threatened to take on e5 so Black had to take on d4.  9.Nxd4  Nge7  White is already under pressure here. If  10.Qa4  then after  He cannot play   10.Rc1  in view of  Qxa2  10...Bxc3+  11.bxc3  O-O  the queen on d5 hinders the development of White's light-squared bishop because of the attack on g2. }
5... Bg4
{ Black plays for quick queenside development. Now White is at a crossroad. He can take on c5 and go for an endgame allowing strong initiative, similar to the line 5.dxc5, or he can allow the formation of an isolated pawn on d4 with Black having already developed the light-squared bishop  (in IQP positions this bishop is usually passive on c8)  . }
6. Be2
{ With this move White goes for the IQP position.   6.dxc5  This wins the pawn on c5, but as in the line with 5. dxc5, after the exchange of queens the king will be stuck in the centre and Black's quick development will give him excellent compensation.  Qxd1+  Taking on c5 is too dangerous:   6...Qxc5  allows White to take over the initiative after  7.Be3  attacking the queen.  7.Kxd1  e6 !  Unlike the line with 5. dxc5, here the move   7...e5  isn't very good as after  8.b4  a5  9.b5  Nd8  10.c6  bxc6  11.h3 !  White returns the pawn but wins the bishop pair   the bishop cannot retreat along the h3-c8 diagonal because the e5-pawn is hanging - this is the difference with the  5.dxc5  line - with the white knight already developed on  f3  the pawn on  e5  hangs  and he will have some advantage in the endgame.  8.b4  The alternative way to defend the pawn by   8.Be3  is met by the maneuver of the knight to d5, just like in the 5. dxc5 line. So,  Nf6  9.Nbd2  (White tries to defend the c5-pawn by pieces)  Nd5  10.Nb3  O-O-O  11.Ke1  e5  Black is almost fully developed and can now advance in the centre. His further plan is to push the kingside pawns, for example  12.h3  Bh5  13.Bb5  f6  and then to move the bishop from h5 and go ...h5, ...g5-g4. White's extra pawn on the queenside is not felt as the play happens on the other side of the board and White always has to have at least one piece defending the advanced c5-pawn.  8...a5  The typical move to disrupt and attack White's queenside.  9.Bb5  Nge7  The same maneuver as in the 5 dc line - the knight can go to d5 from where it exerts strong pressure on the pawns on c3 and b4, but it can also go to f5 or g6, depending on circumstances.  10.a3  axb4  It is good to insert this because of a small tactical detail that can be seen after Black castles long on the next move.  11.cxb4  O-O-O+  12.Nbd2  The point of taking on b4 is seen in the fact that White cannot go   12.Kc2 ?  here in view of  Bxf3  13.gxf3  Nd4+  winning the bishop on b5 - that is why it was important to remove the pawn from c3 with the exchange on b4.  12...Bxf3+  Black takes the opportunity to double White's f-pawns.  13.gxf3  Nd4  Black has tremendous initiative here and White needs to be very careful.  14.Bd3  The attempt to defend f3 backfires:   14.Be2 ?!  Nd5 !  threatening ...Nc3 gives Black a big advantage. After  15.Bb2  the game can end in a cute mate after  Nxe2  16.Kxe2  Nf4+  17.Ke3  g5  18.Bxh8  Rd3+  19.Ke4  f5+  20.Ke5  Be7  followed by 21... Rd5#.  14...Ng6 !  With this knight move Black takes control over f4 and now threatens to take on f3.  Taking on f3 would be in White's favour - after   14...Nxf3  15.Nxf3  Rxd3+  16.Ke2  White managed to untangle.  15.Bb2  White finally develops, but now Black returns the pawn and maintains the activity after  Nxf3  16.Nxf3  Rxd3+  17.Nd2  Now we see the point of 14... Ng6 - after   17.Ke2  Black has  Nf4+  17...Be7  And with ...Rhd8 to come Black has a great position. }
6... cxd4 { Immediately creating the IQP. } 7. cxd4 e6
{ Black will now develop the kingside and will obtain a comfortable position with play against the IQP. }
8. Nc3
{ White attacks the exposed queen.  If   8.O-O  then Black has time to take control over the d5-square by  Nf6  and after  9.Nc3  Qa5  with ...Be7 and ...O-O to follow. He can meet  10.Qb3  by  Qb4  with equal play. }
8... Bb4 { Black develops with tempo.   8...Qa5  allows  9.d5 } 9. O-O Qa5
{ The queen moves to a safe square and puts pressure on the knight on c3. } 10.
h3
{ This forces the exchange of the bishop.  The immediate   10.d5  is harmless as after  exd5  11.Nxd5  Rd8  Black has the time to develop the knight from g8 and castle after  12.Bb5  Nge7  as  13.Qd4  can simply be met by  Rxd5  14.Bxc6+  bxc6  15.Qxg4  O-O  with Black's activity compensating for the pawn on c6. }
10... Bxf3
{ Black must not lose time. He takes on f3 in order to gain tempo to develop the knight from g8. }
11. Bxf3 Nge7
{ This is the position Black has been aiming for. He has comfortable development and after castling he will start the play against the IQP. The knight is developed on e7 rather than on f6 because from e7 it can go to f5 to increase the pressure on the d4-pawn. }
12. Be3
{ Defending the pawn on d4 in advance as Black would attack it anyway by putting a rook on d8 later on.  Sacrificing the pawn temporarily by   12.a3  Bxc3  13.bxc3  Qxc3  allows Black to return it after  14.Rb1  O-O  15.Rxb7  but this leads to unclear play after  Qa5  followed by ...Rad8. }
12... O-O { Completing the development. } 13. Qb3 Nf5
{ Black's activity and play against the IQP more than compensate for White's bishop pair. Even more so, Black can now take on e3 at any moment if he deems it appropriate. }
14. a3
{ After this Black can also retreat to d6, but taking on c3 also gives him good play. }
14... Bxc3 15. bxc3 Qc7
{ It was possible to take on e3 as well, but this move emphasises Black's strategy to play with knights against bishops as long as he has good squares for the knights - this is particularly valid for the c4-square. The knight on f5 is very useful in preventing the c4-push by attacking the d4-pawn. Black will play ...Na5 next and likely ...Nc4 with great play. }
*

