1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ The Alapin Variation is a very popular option against the Sicilian because it is relatively easy to play with White. }
2... d5
{ The central push is one of the main lines and gives Black free play. } 3.
exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nc6
{ Black develops the queenside first. This will be useful in the lines where White takes on c5 so that a quick ...O-O-O is possible. }
5. dxc5 { Leads to a sharp endgame where Black has the initiative. } 5... Qxd1+
6. Kxd1 e5 { In case of } 7. Be3 Nf6 { with the idea of ...Nd5 } 8. f3
{ liberating f2 for the bishop } 8... Nd7 9. b4 a5 10. Bb5 Nf6
{ is a move to remember, Black wants to return to d5 now that the b4-pawn can be attacked. If White defends it after }
11. a3 Nd5 12. Bd2 Be7
{ followed by ...O-O, ...Rd8 and ...Be6 Black has excellent compensation. White's knight on b1 and rook on a1 cannot easily join the game while Black can further improve his position by ...f5, ...Bf6. }
