1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ The Alapin Variation is a very popular option against the Sicilian because it is relatively easy to play with White. }
2... d5
{ The central push is one of the main lines and gives Black free play. } 3.
exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nc6
{ Black develops the queenside first. This will be useful in the lines where White takes on c5 so that a quick ...O-O-O is possible. }
5. dxc5 { Leads to a sharp endgame where Black has the initiative. } 5... Qxd1+
6. Kxd1 e5
{ Taking central space. Black sacrificed the c5-pawn for two factors: development advantage and the awkward position of the king on d1, stuck in the centre that hinders White's coordination. }
7. b4 a5 { Attacking White's queenside. } 8. Bb5
{ The only way to keep the extra pawn. } 8... Ne7
{ The knight aims for d5. From there it attacks the b4-pawn but it can also go to f4. }
9. Nf3 f6 { Securely defending the e5-pawn. } 10. a3
{ Again the only way for White to defend the b4-pawn. } 10... Nd5 11. Bb2
{ Defending the rook on a1, but this leaves the f4-square without control. }
11... Nf4 { The move } 12. g3 { allows } 12... Bg4 { and after } 13. Nd2 O-O-O
{ Black has great play against White's king in the centre. } *

