[Black "The Alapin Variation 6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ The Alapin Variation is a very popular option against the Sicilian because it is relatively easy to play with White. }
2... d5
{ The central push is one of the main lines and gives Black free play. } 3.
exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nc6
{ Black develops the queenside first. This will be useful in the lines where White takes on c5 so that a quick ...O-O-O is possible. }
5. Nf3 Bg4
{ Black plays for quick queenside development. Now White is at a crossroad. He can take on c5 and go for an endgame allowing strong initiative, similar to the line 5.dxc5, or he can allow the formation of an isolated pawn on d4 with Black having already developed the light-squared bishop  (in IQP positions this bishop is usually passive on c8)  . }
6. dxc5
{ This wins the pawn on c5, but as in the line with 5. dxc5, after the exchange of queens the king will be stuck in the centre and Black's quick development will give him excellent compensation. }
6... Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 e6 { The alternative way to defend the pawn by } 8. Be3
{ is met by the maneuver of the knight to d5, just like in the 5. dxc5 line. So, }
8... Nf6 9. Nd2 { White tries to defend the c5-pawn by pieces } 9... Nd5 10.
Nb3 O-O-O 11. Ke1 e5
{ Black is almost fully developed and can now advance in the centre. His further plan is to push the kingside pawns, for example }
12. h3 Bh5 13. Bb5 f6
{ and then to move the bishop from h5 and go ...h5, ...g5-g4. White's extra pawn on the queenside is not felt as the play happens on the other side of the board and White always has to have at least one piece defending the advanced c5-pawn. }
*

