1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ The Alapin Variation is a very popular option against the Sicilian because it is relatively easy to play with White. }
2... d5
{ The central push is one of the main lines and gives Black free play. } 3.
exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nc6
{ Black develops the queenside first. This will be useful in the lines where White takes on c5 so that a quick ...O-O-O is possible. }
5. Nf3 Bg4
{ Black plays for quick queenside development. Now White is at a crossroad. He can take on c5 and go for an endgame allowing strong initiative, similar to the line 5.dxc5, or he can allow the formation of an isolated pawn on d4 with Black having already developed the light-squared bishop  (in IQP positions this bishop is usually passive on c8)  . }
6. Be2 { With this move White goes for the IQP position. } 6... cxd4
{ Immediately creating the IQP. } 7. cxd4 e6
{ Black will now develop the kingside and will obtain a comfortable position with play against the IQP. }
8. Nc3 { White attacks the exposed queen. } 8... Bb4
{ Black develops with tempo. } 9. O-O Qa5
{ The queen moves to a safe square and puts pressure on the knight on c3. } 10.
h3 { This forces the exchange of the bishop. } 10... Bxf3
{ Black must not lose time. He takes on f3 in order to gain tempo to develop the knight from g8. }
11. Bxf3 Nge7
{ This is the position Black has been aiming for. He has comfortable development and after castling he will start the play against the IQP. The knight is developed on e7 rather than on f6 because from e7 it can go to f5 to increase the pressure on the d4-pawn. }
12. Be3
{ Defending the pawn on d4 in advance as Black would attack it anyway by putting a rook on d8 later on. }
12... O-O { Completing the development. } 13. Qb3 Nf5
{ Black's activity and play against the IQP more than compensate for White's bishop pair. Even more so, Black can now take on e3 at any moment if he deems it appropriate. }
14. a3
{ After this Black can also retreat to d6, but taking on c3 also gives him good play. }
14... Bxc3 15. bxc3 Qc7
{ It was possible to take on e3 as well, but this move emphasises Black's strategy to play with knights against bishops as long as he has good squares for the knights - this is particularly valid for the c4-square. The knight on f5 is very useful in preventing the c4-push by attacking the d4-pawn. Black will play ...Na5 next and likely ...Nc4 with great play. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Closed Sicilian"]
[Black "The Closed Sicilian Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3
{ The Closed Sicilian leads to relatively calm play, though Black must be a bit careful about a possible f5-push in the middlegame. }
3... g6
{ The kingside fianchetto is the best reaction to the Closed Sicilian. The bishop from g7 controls the central squares d4 and e5 and helps the queenside attack. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6
{ The most flexible move, defending c5 first. Now White has two main options at his disposal. }
6. Be3
{ 6.f4  This is the other main move in this position.  e6  Black develops in the flexible manner - the knight from e7 will control the f5-square.  7.Nf3  Nge7  8.O-O  O-O  9.Be3  This is an important moment. With his last move White is threatening to push d4, so Black must stop this. Here I would like to describe the scenario according to which Black plays in the Closed Sicilian. He needs to know what he should do on the kingside and the queenside. On the kingside, he must be careful about a possible f5-push. When that push becomes an option for White, let's say after a g4-push, then Black should meet this by playing ...f5 himself. Then he should follow the rule of thumb: if White takes with the g-pawn   gxf5  he recaptures with the e-pawn   exf5  ; if White takes with the e-pawn   exf5  he recaptures with the g-pawn   gxf5  . In other words, always recapturing with the other pawn. The ultimate goal is to end up with a piece on the f5-square, which likely means keeping the knight on e7 so that it can land on f5 after all the exchanges. On the queenside Black's plan is as follows: he plays ...Rb8 and pushes ...b5-b4. Then, when White removes the c3-knight and plays c3 Black will take ...bxc3 and then continue with ...Ba6 and ...Qa5. This is the ideal set-up for Black on the queenside, against which White will find it almost impossible to defend. For an illustration of these ideas please check the model games Turovsky-Dvoretsky and Bronstein-Dvoretsky.  9...Nd4 !  The only way to stop d4. Note that the knight should jump to d4 only when d4 is threatened.  10.e5  This is the most concrete attempt. The others are more in spirit of the Closed Sicilian, but do not pose real problems.  For example   10.Qd2  can be met by  Rb8  and then ...b5-b4.  The move   10.Bf2  threatens to take on d4 with the knight, so a good idea is to play  Nxf3+  11.Bxf3  Nc6  keeping control of the d4-square.  The move   10.g4  is analysed in the model game Bronstein-Dvoretsky.  10...Bd7  The idea is to come with the bishop on c6, once the long diagonal has been opened.  11.Ne4  Targeting d6.  Taking on d4 twice isn't very good in view of   11.Nxd4  cxd4  12.Bxd4  Nf5  13.Bf2  dxe5  14.fxe5  Bxe5  and Black regains the pawn with better play as his pieces are better placed.  Similarly,   11.exd6  Nef5  12.Bf2  Bc6  activates Black's pieces.  11...Nef5  Attacking the bishop and keeping control over d6.  12.Bf2  Nxf3+  Since both knights want to be on d4 this makes the knight on f5 superfluous  (this concept is from Dvoretsky's books !)  so the solution is to exchange the knight already on the desired square so that the other one can land there. Hence the logic of Black's move.  13.Qxf3  Taking with the bishop is met by   13.Bxf3  Bc6  14.c3  (taking away d4 from the knight)  h5  stabilising the knight. Then if White takes  15.exd6  Black first defends the c5-pawn by  b6  before taking on d6. The loss of the light-squared bishop after  16.Nf6+  Bxf6  17.Bxc6  Rc8  isn't very important because Black's pawns on the light squares limit White's light-squared bishop and the long diagonal is empty.  13...Bc6  The square where the bishop was headed to.  14.c3  Rc8  Defending the bishop before playing ...b6.  15.d4  Defending the e5-pawn and building a centre, but Black is harmoniously developed and can deal with it.  Note that the move   15.g4  doesn't really attack the knight on f5 because after White takes gxf5 Black can recapture ...exf5 and the knight on e4 is pinned. So Black can simply reply with  dxe5  15...cxd4  Opening the c-file first.  16.cxd4  h5  Stabilising the knight and controling more light squares.  17.Rfd1  Black will play similarly against other moves as well.  Qa5  18.Qe2  Bd5  The bishop is very comfortable on d5 and Black will follow up with ...Rc6 and ...Rfc8 with excellent play.  The other moves   6.Nge2  and   6.Nh3  do not change Black's play. He continues along the same lines of  e6  followed by 7... Nge7 and then probably castling and queenside expansion by ...Rb8, ...b5-b4. }
6... Rb8
{ Since with his last move White prepared the move Qd2, aiming to exchange the fianchettoed bishop on g7 in case Black plays ...e6 and ...Nge7, Black first postpones this development of the kingside and starts his own typical queenside expansion. }
7. Qd2 b5 8. f4
{ The alternative is the move   8.Nge2  (threatening d4)  to which Black first attacks the c3-knight by  b4  9.Nd1  and only now jumps to d4:  Nd4  After  10.O-O  he continues with the usual development of  e6  followed by 11... Ne7. I would like to note here how Black should react if White manages to play Bh6 and exchange the dark-squared bishops. Once these bishops are exchanged, Black's flexible pawn structure moves on dark squares in order to cover them, leave space for his own light-squared bishop, and at the same time fix White's pawns on light squares which limit White's light-squared bishop. This means the move ...e5 is played, often supported by ...f6 and the bishop comes to e6. This set-up harmoniously covers both the dark squares  (the pawns cover them)  and the light squares  (the bishop on e6 and the knight on e7 cover them)  . }
8... b4
{ Expanding on the queenside and forcing the knight to go to d1 to defend the b2-pawn. }
9. Nd1 e6
{ Black achieved the maximum on the queenside for the time being so now he finishes the development of the kingside. With the pawn on f4 there is no threat to exchange the dark-squared bishops. }
10. Nf3
{ The threat is to play d4, so Black prevents it by putting his knight on d4. }
10... Nd4 { Preventing d4 in a typical fashion. } 11. O-O Ne7
{ Black almost finished development, all remains is to castle and then continue with his queenside play. }
12. Nh4
{ White tries to push f5 at all costs.  In case of   12.c3  Black would first open the b-file with  bxc3  13.bxc3  and then would not waste time and take on f3:  Nxf3+  14.Bxf3  and now would play the typical move  Ba6  which he will follow up with ...Qa5  (probably after castling first)  . }
12... f5
{ A typical reaction again - when White threatens f5 then Black should prevent it by playing that move himself. }
13. c3 bxc3 14. bxc3 Ndc6
{ Black will follow up with castling short and then probably play ...Qa5 with the intention to pursue his queenside play. The position is complex but Black has every reason to be optimistic here as he has a very good and harmonious position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Closed Sicilian"]
[Black "The Closed Sicilian 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3
{ The Closed Sicilian leads to relatively calm play, though Black must be a bit careful about a possible f5-push in the middlegame. }
3... g6
{ The kingside fianchetto is the best reaction to the Closed Sicilian. The bishop from g7 controls the central squares d4 and e5 and helps the queenside attack. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6
{ The most flexible move, defending c5 first. Now White has two main options at his disposal. }
6. f4 { This is the other main move in this position. } 6... e6
{ Black develops in the flexible manner - the knight from e7 will control the f5-square. }
7. Nf3 Nge7 8. O-O O-O 9. Be3
{ This is an important moment. With his last move White is threatening to push d4, so Black must stop this. Here I would like to describe the scenario according to which Black plays in the Closed Sicilian. He needs to know what he should do on the kingside and the queenside.  On the kingside, he must be careful about a possible f5-push. When that push becomes an option for White, let's say after a g4-push, then Black should meet this by playing ...f5 himself. Then he should follow the rule of thumb: if White takes with the g-pawn   gxf5  he recaptures with the e-pawn   exf5  ; if White takes with the e-pawn   exf5  he recaptures with the g-pawn   gxf5  . In other words, always recapturing with the other pawn. The ultimate goal is to end up with a piece on the f5-square, which likely means keeping the knight on e7 so that it can land on f5 after all the exchanges.   On the queenside Black's plan is as follows: he plays ...Rb8 and pushes ...b5-b4. Then, when White removes the c3-knight and plays c3 Black will take ..bxc3 and then continue with ...Ba6 and ...Qa5. This is the ideal set-up for Black on the queenside, against which White will find it almost impossible to defend.   For an illustration of these ideas please check the model games Turovsky-Dvoretsky and Bronstein-Dvoretsky. }
9... Nd4 { For example } 10. Qd2 { can be met by } 10... Rb8
{ and then ...b5-b4. } *

