{ followed by 11... Ne7. I would like to note here how Black should react if White manages to play Bh6 and exchange the dark-squared bishops. Once these bishops are exchanged, Black's flexible pawn structure moves on dark squares in order to cover them, leave space for his own light-squared bishop, and at the same time fix White's pawns on light squares which limit White's light-squared bishop. This means the move ...e5 is played, often supported by ...f6 and the bishop comes to e6. This set-up harmoniously covers both the dark squares  (the pawns cover them)  and the light squares  (the bishop on e6 and the knight on e7 cover them)  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Closed Sicilian"]
[Black "The Closed Sicilian 9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3
{ The Closed Sicilian leads to relatively calm play, though Black must be a bit careful about a possible f5-push in the middlegame. }
3... g6
{ The kingside fianchetto is the best reaction to the Closed Sicilian. The bishop from g7 controls the central squares d4 and e5 and helps the queenside attack. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6
{ The most flexible move, defending c5 first. Now White has two main options at his disposal. }
6. Be3 Rb8
{ Since with his last move White prepared the move Qd2, aiming to exchange the fianchettoed bishop on g7 in case Black plays ...e6 and ...Nge7, Black first postpones this development of the kingside and starts his own typical queenside expansion. }
7. Qd2 b5 8. f4 b4
{ Expanding on the queenside and forcing the knight to go to d1 to defend the b2-pawn. }
9. Nd1 e6
{ Black achieved the maximum on the queenside for the time being so now he finishes the development of the kingside. With the pawn on f4 there is no threat to exchange the dark-squared bishops. }
10. Nf3
{ The threat is to play d4, so Black prevents it by putting his knight on d4. }
10... Nd4 { Preventing d4 in a typical fashion. } 11. O-O Ne7 { In case of }
12. c3 { Black would first open the b-file with } 12... bxc3 13. bxc3
{ and then would not waste time and take on f3: } 13... Nxf3+ 14. Bxf3
{ and now would play the typical move } 14... Ba6
{ which he will follow up with ...Qa5  (probably after castling first)  . } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Closed Sicilian"]
[Black "The Closed Sicilian 10"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3
{ The Closed Sicilian leads to relatively calm play, though Black must be a bit careful about a possible f5-push in the middlegame. }
3... g6
{ The kingside fianchetto is the best reaction to the Closed Sicilian. The bishop from g7 controls the central squares d4 and e5 and helps the queenside attack. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6
{ The most flexible move, defending c5 first. Now White has two main options at his disposal. }
6. Be3 Rb8
{ Since with his last move White prepared the move Qd2, aiming to exchange the fianchettoed bishop on g7 in case Black plays ...e6 and ...Nge7, Black first postpones this development of the kingside and starts his own typical queenside expansion. }
7. Qd2 b5 8. f4 b4
{ Expanding on the queenside and forcing the knight to go to d1 to defend the b2-pawn. }
9. Nd1 e6
{ Black achieved the maximum on the queenside for the time being so now he finishes the development of the kingside. With the pawn on f4 there is no threat to exchange the dark-squared bishops. }
10. Nf3
{ The threat is to play d4, so Black prevents it by putting his knight on d4. }
10... Nd4 { Preventing d4 in a typical fashion. } 11. O-O Ne7
{ Black almost finished development, all remains is to castle and then continue with his queenside play. }
12. Nh4 { White tries to push f5 at all costs. } 12... f5
{ A typical reaction again - when White threatens f5 then Black should prevent it by playing that move himself. }
13. c3 bxc3 14. bxc3 Ndc6
{ Black will follow up with castling short and then probably play ...Qa5 with the intention to pursue his queenside play. The position is complex but Black has every reason to be optimistic here as he has a very good and harmonious position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Grand Prix Attack"]
[Black "The Grand Prix Attack Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3
{ This is the trickiest move to meet only for the Najdorf player. The reason lies in the fact that White doesn't want to play a Najdorf, but at the same time he keeps the option to transpose to an open Sicilian by d2-d4 at a certain point. This is further made more problematic for the Najdorf player due to the very few Najdorf moves that Black has at his disposal: ...d6, ...Nf6 and ...a6 while White has more 'waiting' moves: Nge2, g3, Bg2, O-O or f4, Nf3 and then d4. What this means is that White can easily force Black into another open Sicilian if Black attempts to remain flexible and play the Najdorf-allowing moves mentioned above. }
2... Nc6
{ All these considerations led me to my suggestion of the move 2... Nc6. With this move and his subsequent play Black will prevent any transposition to an open Sicilian. The advantage of this move is that the Grand Prix Attack doesn't work so well anymore for White  (since Black can play directly ...e6 and ...d5 for example, without wasting time on ...d6)  and that the positions that arise are calmer and do not allow White attacking chances. In fact, as we will see in some of the lines, even Black gets to attack, as shown by the World Champion himself in several of his games. }
3. f4
{ The starting point of the Grand Prix Attack, but as already mentioned, this doesn't work so well for White with the pawn still on d7. White has two more alternatives to 3. f4 and these are 3. Nf3 and 3. Bb5.   3.Nf3  e5  Again preventing d4 with a transposition to an open Sicilian.  4.Bc4  Be7  It is important to keep the g5-square under control in order to prevent Ng5.  5.d3  d6  Now White has a choice of two possible plans: a more direct one, connected with a quick O-O and f4, or a more positional one, connected with the knight maneuver to e3  (Nd2-f1-e3)  .  6.Nd2  This is the more positional approach. White wants to put the knight on the ideal e3-square, from where it will control d5 and f5.   6.O-O  With this move White will attempt to push f4 quickly enough. This line requires more theoretical knowledge and some memorisation as the lines are rather long.  Nf6  Finishing the development of the kingside.  7.Ng5  This liberates the path for the f-pawn.  For a different treatment of the position in a more positional way, starting with the not very ambitious move   7.h3  take a look at the model game Aronian-Carlsen.  7...O-O  8.f4  Bg4  An important move. It finishes development and wins a tempo by attacking the queen. In some lines the bishop can drop back to h5 and g6, defending f7.  9.Qe1  The queen intends to go to g3.  The move   9.Nf3  is met by  exf4  10.Bxf4  Nd4  and the pin is unpleasant for White. Black will continue with ...Qd7 and either take ...Nxf3 and play ...Be6 or will push ...b5 and eliminate the b3-bishop.  9...exf4  Eliminating the threat of f5.  10.Bxf4  Taking with the rook is met by   10.Rxf4  Ne5  followed by ...h6.  10...Nd4  Centralising the knight and attacking c2.  11.Qd2  After the alternative   11.Qf2  play would follow the same lines and would transpose after  h6  12.Nf3  Nxf3+  13.gxf3  Be6  14.Qg2  Kh7  11...h6  12.Nf3  Nxf3+  Black now exchanges a pair of light pieces.  13.gxf3  Be6  The bishop on c4 is strong so Black seeks to exchange it.  14.Qg2  If   14.Kh1  then again  Kh7  After an exchange on e6 when Black follows up with ...fxe6 it is important to have the g6 and h6 squares protected by the king.  14...Kh7  Covering g6 and h6.  15.Bxe6  Black was already threatening ...d5, for example,   15.Kh1  d5 !  15...fxe6  16.Bd2  Liberating the path for the f-pawn.  Qd7  The beginning of an excellent defensive regrouping, discovered by Lc0 !  17.f4  If   17.Kh1  then  Ng8  first, with the same idea as in the main line.  17...Rf7 !  A multi-purpose move, the first step of the defensive regrouping. It defends g7 and wants to double the rooks on the f-file.  18.Kh1  Ng8 !  The star move ! This move liberates the f6-square for the bishop, who in turn will liberate the e7-square for the knight, from where it will cover the g6-square. Once this regrouping is finished Black's position will be very harmonious.  19.Rg1  Bf6  Following the plan. The bishop can also go to d4 to make White's control over the g-file more problematic by controlling the g1-square. With the moves ... Raf8 and ...Ne7 Black will secure his kingside and will have a very solid position. After ...Bd4 he will open the f-file and keep an eye on the f4-pawn and the standard queenside expansion by ...b5-b4 is still on the cards.  Note that the direct   6.Ng5 ?  is bad as after  Bxg5  7.Qh5  Be7  White only has three checks to show for the missing piece:  8.Qxf7+  Kd7  9.Be6+  Kc7  10.Nd5+  Kb8  and Black is a piece up for nothing.  The move   6.Nd5  is met by  Nf6  as Black doesn't mind the exchange of his dark-squared bishop as it is limited by its own pawn structure.  6...Nf6  Black continues his development.  7.Nf1  Nd7 !  This maneuver was brought into the limelight by Magnus Carlsen. The idea is to continue the fight for the d5-square from b6, rather than f6, thus not blocking the path of the f-pawn, which will allow for a counterplay-seeking ...f5 later on.  8.Ne3  White continues with his plan. Against other moves Black's play is relatively straight-forward: he will play ...Nb6, ...O-O and then depending on circumstances ...Kh8 and ...f5 and/or ...Bg5, aiming to exchange the dark-squared bishops as the pawn structure makes Black's dark-squared bishop rather limited. For an illustration of these alternatives, namely 8.Nd5 and 8.a3, which aims to preserve the light-squared bishop, please take a look at the model games Svidler-Carlsen and Karjakin-Carlsen respectively.  8...Nb6  Finishing the knight maneuver.  9.O-O  If White jumps to d5 with either knight then after an exchange there and castling by both sides the position will transpose to the main line.  So,   9.Ned5  Nxd5  10.Nxd5  O-O  11.O-O  and we have a transposition.  or   9.Ncd5  9...O-O  10.Ncd5  Nxd5  11.Nxd5  Be6  A natural move, finishing development and keeping control of the d5-square.  12.f4  This is the more direct approach.  The alternative is   12.c3  but that allows Black to start activities first after  Na5  13.Bb5  a6  14.Ba4  f5  with active play on both sides of the board.  12...exf4  The threat was f5, so Black must take the pawn.  13.Bxf4  Nb4 !  Now we see the other idea behind 11... Be6 - Black instigates simplifications by attacking the knight on d5.  14.Nxe7+  Mass exchanges after taking on b4 and e6 are harmless for Black:   14.Nxb4  cxb4  15.Bxe6  fxe6  16.Qg4  Qd7  and everything is protected while the b4-pawn pins down the c2-pawn as Black would want to attack it by putting a rook on the c-file.  14...Qxe7  15.c3  Nc6  16.Bb5  The only way to preserve the bishop. White has the bishop pair here but Black's position is very solid.  Rad8  Not only giving more protection to the d6-pawn, but also preparing for ...d5 and the opening of the d-file.  17.d4  This doesn't bring much.  But the alternative   17.Qe1  isn't better as it shows the solidity of Black's position after  f6  18.Qg3  Ne5  with an excellent position.  17...cxd4  18.cxd4  Qc7  A fine move, intending ...Qb6 with an attack on White's fragile centre, the loose bishop on b5 and pawn on b2. Black has good counterplay here.   3.Bb5  This is similar to the Rossolimo, having the same idea to take on c6 and double Black's c-pawns. However, unlike the Rossolimo, here the d4-square isn't controlled by the knight, so Black uses that fact to remove the knight from c6 at the same time attacking the bishop on b5.  Nd4  It is better not to allow White to take on c6.  4.Bc4  This is the most commonly played move, but while the alternatives are equally possible they tend to transpose to the main line.  For example:   4.Nf3  a6  5.Bc4  Nf6  6.O-O  e6  and we have a transposition.   4.Nge2  a6  5.Bc4  Nf6  6.O-O  e6  and again we have a transposition, this time to the comment to White's 5th move where the move 5. Nge2 is discussed.  Even the move   4.Ba4  will transpose after  a6  5.Bb3  b5  6.d3  e6  7.Nf3  Nf6  The move   4.a4  will also transpose after  a6  5.Bc4  Nf6  6.Nf3  e6  7.O-O  d5  which is discussed in the comments to White's 7th move.  4...e6  Blunting the bishop. Black will now aim to either push ...d5 or ...a6 and ... b5, going after the bishop.  5.Nf3  The alternative   5.Nge2  is valid, though it changes little in how Black plays:  Nf6  6.O-O  The move   6.e5  is always met by  d5  which is a typical reaction.  6...a6  7.d3  If   7.a4  then  d5  7...b5  8.Bb3  Nxb3  9.axb3  Bb7  with a similar position to the main line, the only difference being the knight on e2 rather than on f3 as in the main line. If White uses this fact to quickly push the f-pawn by  10.f4  Black is ready and can open the long diagonal for the bishop by  d5  11.e5  d4 !  12.exf6  dxc3  13.fxg7  Bxg7  14.bxc3  Rg8  with excellent play.  5...Nf6  Continuing development.  6.O-O  Not fearing   6.e5  in view of  d5  6...a6  This move is needed to cover b5 against a possible check and also as means to prepare ... b5.  7.d3  The move   7.a4  is met by  d5  and after  8.exd5  exd5  9.Ba2  The sacrifice   9.Nxd5 ?  Nxd5  10.Nxd4  cxd4  11.Qh5  Be6  12.Re1  is incorrect in view of  Nf4  and Black remains material up.  9...Bg4  Black has excellent play. White must try to untangle by  10.Qe1+  Be7  11.Nxd4  cxd4  12.Ne2  but after  d3  13.cxd3  O-O  followed by ...Re8 White's awful structure and buried bishop give Black ample compensation.  7...b5  Forcing the exchange of the knight on d4 for the light-squared bishop, thus winning the bishop pair.  8.Bb3  Nxb3  Black obtains the bishop pair and keeps a very solid position.  9.axb3  Bb7  The bishop will be excellent on the long diagonal. At the same time this move defends the b5-pawn against Nxb5 by defending the rook on a8.  10.e5  The only way to try to justify the knight on f3 and the slight lead in development.  b4  Fighting for the light-squares in the centre by attacking the knight that covers them.  11.Nb1  Taking on f6 would be good for Black as then the position would open for the bishops:   11.exf6  bxc3  12.fxg7  Bxg7  13.bxc3  Bxc3  with excellent play on the g-file after ...Rg8. White will find it difficult to defend against the potent combination of a rook on g8 and the monster bishop on b7.  Putting the knight on a4 would leave the knight stranded and after   11.Na4  Nd5  Black would develop and push ...f6, opening the f-file and eliminating the pawn on e5.  11...Nd5  12.Nbd2  Be7  Black wants to finish development by castling and then to push ...f6. This aims to exchange the pawn on e5 that gives White some space advantage, open the f-file for the rook and obtain pawn majority in the centre. The rook on the f-file in combination with the bishop on b7 gives Black excellent dynamic possibilities.  The move   3.Nge2  doesn't have an independent value because after  e5  (Black prevents d4)  .  4.Nd5  d6  5.Nec3  Nge7  6.Bc4  Nxd5  7.Nxd5  Be7  8.O-O  O-O  9.d3  we have a transposition to the line 3. Nf3 e5 4. Bc4 Be7 5. d3 d6 6. Nd2 Nf6 7. Nf1 Nd7 8. Ne3 Nb6 9. Ned5 O-O 10. O-O Nd5 11. Nd5. }
3... g6
{ The kingside fianchetto is the best plan against the Grand Prix Attack. } 4.
Nf3 Bg7 5. Bb5
{ As in the line with 3. Bb5, the idea is to take on c6 and double the c-pawns. In the same way, Black avoids it by jumping to d4. }
5... Nd4 6. O-O
{ Taking on d4 is dubious, as after   6.Nxd4  cxd4  7.Ne2  Black has the following idea:  Qb6 !  8.Bd3  if   8.Bc4  then again  d5 !  and whichever way White takes Black follows up with 9... Nf6 getting back the pawn.  8...d5  9.e5   9.exd5  is again met by  Nf6  9...f6 !  attacking the centre. After  10.exf6  Nxf6  Black will castle and play ...Nd7-c5 with a better position as the bishop on d3 prevents White from finishing development.  Also not very good is returning to c4:   6.Bc4  e6  gives Black a full extra tempo   Nd4  compared to the lines with 5. Bc4 and he will continue in the same manner with ...Ne7 next.  Another option for White which is not very good is   6.Bd3  because after  d6  (with the threat of ... Bg4)  White must take on d4,  7.Nxd4  cxd4  8.Ne2  but here after  Nf6  9.O-O   9.Nxd4  is met by  Nxe4  9...O-O  10.Qe1  Black has the maneuver  Nd7  with the threat of ...Nc5, which gives him easy play. }
6... Nxb5 { Taking this bishop always feels good. } 7. Nxb5 d5
{ Striking in the centre and changing the structure. Now White doesn't have the easy play typical for the Grand Prix Attack with d3, Qe1-h4, f5 etc. }
8. e5
{ The only way to try for something.  In case of   8.exd5  a6  9.Nc3  Nf6  Black will recapture on d5 with very good play. }
8... a6
{ Chasing away the knight. Black will now play for a better structure. } 9. Nc3
Bg4
{ Black's plan is to exchange the light-squared bishop and play ...e6, thus making sure he has the better bishop  (not restricted by his own pawns)  . }
10. d4
{ If White doesn't push d4 then Black will finish development by ...e6 and ...Ne7 and then will advance on the queenside, while at the same time he can think about ...h5 and ...Nf5. }
10... cxd4 11. Qxd4 Bxf3
{ Before the knight could move Black is eliminating it. } 12. Rxf3 e6
{ This is the structure Black is aiming for - it is the same structure that can arise from the French or the Sicilian after Black had pushed ...d5 and White had played e5. Here Black has the better bishop - this will become apparent once it is transferred via f8 and his knight also has good prospects going to either f5 or c6. His structure is also better, as once he finishes development he can try to use the c-file to his advantage. }
13. Qb4
{ Trying to disrupt the normal flow of events, but Black is prepared for this. }
13... b5
{ Gaining space on the queenside and planning to chase away the queen by ...Bf8. Now the attempt }
14. a4 { Doesn't work in view of } 14... Bf8 15. Qb3 Bc5+
{ Activating the bishop first. } 16. Kh1 b4 { Pushing away the knight. } 17.
Ne2 Ne7
{ With a better position for Black who will continue with ...Nc6 or ...Nf5 and ...O-O with excellent play on the queenside along the c- and b-files. }
*

