1. e4 c5 2. Nc3
{ This is the trickiest move to meet only for the Najdorf player. The reason lies in the fact that White doesn't want to play a Najdorf, but at the same time he keeps the option to transpose to an open Sicilian by d2-d4 at a certain point. This is further made more problematic for the Najdorf player due to the very few Najdorf moves that Black has at his disposal: ...d6, ...Nf6 and ...a6 while White has more 'waiting' moves: Nge2, g3, Bg2, O-O or f4, Nf3 and then d4. What this means is that White can easily force Black into another open Sicilian if Black attempts to remain flexible and play the Najdorf-allowing moves mentioned above. }
2... Nc6
{ All these considerations led me to my suggestion of the move 2... Nc6. With this move and his subsequent play Black will prevent any transposition to an open Sicilian. The advantage of this move is that the Grand Prix Attack doesn't work so well anymore for White  (since Black can play directly ...e6 and ...d5 for example, without wasting time on ...d6)  and that the positions that arise are calmer and do not allow White attacking chances. In fact, as we will see in some of the lines, even Black gets to attack, as shown by the World Champion himself in several of his games. }
3. Nf3 e5 { Again preventing d4 with a transposition to an open Sicilian. } 4.
Bc4 Be7
{ It is important to keep the g5-square under control in order to prevent Ng5. }
5. d3 d6
{ Now White has a choice of two possible plans: a more direct one, connected with a quick O-O and f4, or a more positional one, connected with the knight maneuver to e3  (Nd2-f1-e3)  . }
6. O-O
{ With this move White will attempt to push f4 quickly enough. This line requires more theoretical knowledge and some memorisation as the lines are rather long. }
6... Nf6 { Finishing the development of the kingside. } 7. Ng5
{ This liberates the path for the f-pawn. } 7... O-O 8. f4 Bg4
{ An important move. It finishes development and wins a tempo by attacking the queen. In some lines the bishop can drop back to h5 and g6, defending f7. }
9. Qe1 { The queen intends to go to g3. } 9... exf4
{ Eliminating the threat of f5. } 10. Bxf4 Nd4
{ Centralising the knight and attacking c2. } 11. Qd2 h6 12. Nf3 Nxf3+
{ Black now exchanges a pair of light pieces. } 13. gxf3 Be6
{ The bishop on c4 is strong so Black seeks to exchange it. } 14. Qg2 Kh7
{ Covering g6 and h6. } 15. Bxe6 fxe6 16. Bd2
{ Liberating the path for the f-pawn. } 16... Qd7
{ The beginning of an excellent defensive regrouping, discovered by Lc0 ! } 17.
f4 Rf7
{ A multi-purpose move, the first step of the defensive regrouping. It defends g7 and wants to double the rooks on the f-file. }
18. Kh1 Ng8
{ The star move ! This move liberates the f6-square for the bishop, who in turn will liberate the e7-square for the knight, from where it will cover the g6-square. Once this regrouping is finished Black's position will be very harmonious. }
19. Rg1 Bf6
{ Following the plan. The bishop can also go to d4 to make White's control over the g-file more problematic by controlling the g1-square. With the moves ...Raf8 and ...Ne7 Black will secure his kingside and will have a very solid position. After ...Bd4 he will open the f-file and keep an eye on the f4-pawn and the standard queenside expansion by ...b5-b4 is still on the cards. }
