2... Nc6
{ All these considerations led me to my suggestion of the move 2... Nc6. With this move and his subsequent play Black will prevent any transposition to an open Sicilian. The advantage of this move is that the Grand Prix Attack doesn't work so well anymore for White  (since Black can play directly ...e6 and ...d5 for example, without wasting time on ...d6)  and that the positions that arise are calmer and do not allow White attacking chances. In fact, as we will see in some of the lines, even Black gets to attack, as shown by the World Champion himself in several of his games. }
3. Nf3 e5 { Again preventing d4 with a transposition to an open Sicilian. } 4.
Bc4 Be7
{ It is important to keep the g5-square under control in order to prevent Ng5. }
5. d3 d6
{ Now White has a choice of two possible plans: a more direct one, connected with a quick O-O and f4, or a more positional one, connected with the knight maneuver to e3  (Nd2-f1-e3)  . }
6. Nd2
{ This is the more positional approach. White wants to put the knight on the ideal e3-square, from where it will control d5 and f5. }
6... Nf6 { Black continues his development. } 7. Nf1 Nd7
{ This maneuver was brought into the limelight by Magnus Carlsen. The idea is to continue the fight for the d5-square from b6, rather than f6, thus not blocking the path of the f-pawn, which will allow for a counterplay-seeking ...f5 later on. }
8. Ne3
{ White continues with his plan. Against other moves Black's play is relatively straight-forward: he will play ...Nb6, ...O-O and then depending on circumstances ...Kh8 and ...f5 and/or ...Bg5, aiming to exchange the dark-squared bishops as the pawn structure makes Black's dark-squared bishop rather limited. For an illustration of these alternatives, namely 8. Nd5 and 8. a3  (which aims to preserve the light-squared bishop)  please take a look at the model games Svidler-Carlsen and Karjakin-Carlsen respectively. }
8... Nb6 { Finishing the knight maneuver. } 9. O-O
{ If White jumps to d5 with either knight then after an exchange there and castling by both sides the position will transpose to the main line. }
9... O-O 10. Ncd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Be6
{ A natural move, finishing development and keeping control of the d5-square. }
12. f4 { This is the more direct approach. } 12... exf4
{ The threat was f5, so Black must take the pawn. } 13. Bxf4 Nb4
{ Mass exchanges after taking on b4 and e6 are harmless for Black: } 14. Nxb4
cxb4 15. Bxe6 fxe6 16. Qg4 Qd7
{ and everything is protected while the b4-pawn pins down the c2-pawn as Black would want to attack it by putting a rook on the c-file. }
