[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Grand Prix Attack"]
[Black "The Grand Prix Attack 20"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3
{ This is the trickiest move to meet only for the Najdorf player. The reason lies in the fact that White doesn't want to play a Najdorf, but at the same time he keeps the option to transpose to an open Sicilian by d2-d4 at a certain point. This is further made more problematic for the Najdorf player due to the very few Najdorf moves that Black has at his disposal: ...d6, ...Nf6 and ...a6 while White has more 'waiting' moves: Nge2, g3, Bg2, O-O or f4, Nf3 and then d4. What this means is that White can easily force Black into another open Sicilian if Black attempts to remain flexible and play the Najdorf-allowing moves mentioned above. }
2... Nc6
{ All these considerations led me to my suggestion of the move 2... Nc6. With this move and his subsequent play Black will prevent any transposition to an open Sicilian. The advantage of this move is that the Grand Prix Attack doesn't work so well anymore for White  (since Black can play directly ...e6 and ...d5 for example, without wasting time on ...d6)  and that the positions that arise are calmer and do not allow White attacking chances. In fact, as we will see in some of the lines, even Black gets to attack, as shown by the World Champion himself in several of his games. }
3. Bb5
{ This is similar to the Rossolimo, having the same idea to take on c6 and double Black's c-pawns. However, unlike the Rossolimo, here the d4-square isn't controlled by the knight, so Black uses that fact to remove the knight from c6 at the same time attacking the bishop on b5. }
3... Nd4 { It is better not to allow White to take on c6. } 4. Bc4
{ This is the most commonly played move, but while the alternatives are equally possible they tend to transpose to the main line. }
4... e6
{ Blunting the bishop. Black will now aim to either push ...d5 or ...a6 and ... b5, going after the bishop. }
5. Nf3 Nf6 { Continuing development. } 6. O-O a6
{ This move is needed to cover b5 against a possible check and also as means to prepare ... b5. }
7. d3 b5
{ Forcing the exchange of the knight on d4 for the light-squared bishop, thus winning the bishop pair. }
8. Bb3 Nxb3 { Black obtains the bishop pair and keeps a very solid position. }
9. axb3 Bb7
{ The bishop will be excellent on the long diagonal. At the same time this move defends the b5-pawn against Nxb5 by defending the rook on a8. }
10. e5
{ The only way to try to justify the knight on f3 and the slight lead in development. }
10... b4
{ Taking on f6 would be good for Black as then the position would open for the bishops: }
11. exf6 bxc3 12. fxg7 Bxg7 13. bxc3 Bxc3
{ with excellent play on the g-file after ...Rg8. White will find it difficult to defend against the potent combination of a rook on g8 and the monster bishop on b7. }
*

