[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3
{ This is the trickiest move to meet only for the Najdorf player. The reason lies in the fact that White doesn't want to play a Najdorf, but at the same time he keeps the option to transpose to an open Sicilian by d2-d4 at a certain point. This is further made more problematic for the Najdorf player due to the very few Najdorf moves that Black has at his disposal: ...d6, ...Nf6 and ...a6 while White has more 'waiting' moves: Nge2, g3, Bg2, O-O or f4, Nf3 and then d4. What this means is that White can easily force Black into another open Sicilian if Black attempts to remain flexible and play the Najdorf-allowing moves mentioned above. }
2... Nc6
{ All these considerations led me to my suggestion of the move 2... Nc6. With this move and his subsequent play Black will prevent any transposition to an open Sicilian. The advantage of this move is that the Grand Prix Attack doesn't work so well anymore for White  (since Black can play directly ...e6 and ...d5 for example, without wasting time on ...d6)  and that the positions that arise are calmer and do not allow White attacking chances. In fact, as we will see in some of the lines, even Black gets to attack, as shown by the World Champion himself in several of his games. }
3. f4
{ The starting point of the Grand Prix Attack, but as already mentioned, this doesn't work so well for White with the pawn still on d7. White has two more alternatives to 3. f4 and these are 3. Nf3 and 3. Bb5. }
3... g6
{ The kingside fianchetto is the best plan against the Grand Prix Attack. } 4.
Nf3 Bg7 5. Bc4 { Is less effective because after } 5... e6
{ A logical move that blunts the bishop, Black is ready for ...Nge7 and ...d5. }
6. O-O Nge7 7. d3 O-O 8. Qe1 d5 { Black expands in the centre. } 9. Bb3 Na5
{ If } 10. f5 { then after } 10... Nxb3 11. axb3 exf5 { White has nothing as }
12. Bg5 { is met by } 12... f6
{ this is possible only because White's light-squared bishop has been eliminated, so the weakening of the a2-g8 diagonal is not important }
*

