1. e4 c5 2. Nc3
{ This is the trickiest move to meet only for the Najdorf player. The reason lies in the fact that White doesn't want to play a Najdorf, but at the same time he keeps the option to transpose to an open Sicilian by d2-d4 at a certain point. This is further made more problematic for the Najdorf player due to the very few Najdorf moves that Black has at his disposal: ...d6, ...Nf6 and ...a6 while White has more 'waiting' moves: Nge2, g3, Bg2, O-O or f4, Nf3 and then d4. What this means is that White can easily force Black into another open Sicilian if Black attempts to remain flexible and play the Najdorf-allowing moves mentioned above. }
2... Nc6
{ All these considerations led me to my suggestion of the move 2... Nc6. With this move and his subsequent play Black will prevent any transposition to an open Sicilian. The advantage of this move is that the Grand Prix Attack doesn't work so well anymore for White  (since Black can play directly ...e6 and ...d5 for example, without wasting time on ...d6)  and that the positions that arise are calmer and do not allow White attacking chances. In fact, as we will see in some of the lines, even Black gets to attack, as shown by the World Champion himself in several of his games. }
3. f4
{ The starting point of the Grand Prix Attack, but as already mentioned, this doesn't work so well for White with the pawn still on d7. White has two more alternatives to 3. f4 and these are 3. Nf3 and 3. Bb5. }
3... g6
{ The kingside fianchetto is the best plan against the Grand Prix Attack. } 4.
Nf3 Bg7 5. Bb5
{ As in the line with 3. Bb5, the idea is to take on c6 and double the c-pawns. In the same way, Black avoids it by jumping to d4. }
5... Nd4 6. O-O Nxb5 { Taking this bishop always feels good. } 7. Nxb5 d5
{ Striking in the centre and changing the structure. Now White doesn't have the easy play typical for the Grand Prix Attack with d3, Qe1-h4, f5 etc. }
8. e5 { The only way to try for something. } 8... a6
{ Chasing away the knight. Black will now play for a better structure. } 9. Nc3
Bg4
{ Black's plan is to exchange the light-squared bishop and play ...e6, thus making sure he has the better bishop  (not restricted by his own pawns)  . }
10. d4
{ If White doesn't push d4 then Black will finish development by ...e6 and ...Ne7 and then will advance on the queenside, while at the same time he can think about ...h5 and ...Nf5. }
10... cxd4 11. Qxd4 Bxf3
{ Before the knight could move Black is eliminating it. } 12. Rxf3 e6
{ This is the structure Black is aiming for - it is the same structure that can arise from the French or the Sicilian after Black had pushed ...d5 and White had played e5. Here Black has the better bishop - this will become apparent once it is transferred via f8 and his knight also has good prospects going to either f5 or c6. His structure is also better, as once he finishes development he can try to use the c-file to his advantage. }
13. Qb4
{ Trying to disrupt the normal flow of events, but Black is prepared for this. }
13... b5
{ Gaining space on the queenside and planning to chase away the queen by ...Bf8. Now the attempt }
14. a4 { Doesn't work in view of } 14... Bf8 15. Qb3 Bc5+
{ Activating the bishop first. } 16. Kh1 b4 { Pushing away the knight. } 17.
Ne2 Ne7
{ With a better position for Black who will continue with ...Nc6 or ...Nf5 and ...O-O with excellent play on the queenside along the c- and b-files. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Various 3rd Moves"]
[Black "Various 3rd Moves Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. c3
{ Apart from the Moscow Variation, White has many other options on his 3rd move. The most theoretically important is the move 3. c3. In this variation Black has two general plans at his disposal: the fianchetto of the dark-squared bishop and the ...Bg4 pin followed by ...e6. The general rule of thumb is that if the pin is allowed, Black plays it, if it isn't - or it is not a pin anymore, as in the 4. Be2 line - then Black plays the fianchetto.   3.Bc4  This move had a period of popularity quite some time ago. Its aim is to obtain a Spanish-like position after c3, d3 followed by the typical maneuver Nbd2-f1-g3. White will also try to push d4 and obtain a full centre if possible.  Nf6  By attacking the e4-pawn Black forces White to defend it by d3, thus preventing possible ideas with quick c3 and d4.  4.d3  In case of   4.c3  please see this variation via the move-order 3. c3 Nf6 4. Bc4.  4...Nc6  Black develops normally, controlling the centre.  5.c3  White also follows his plan of play as in the Spanish.  The move   5.Nc3  is at odds with that plan, though it is sometimes played. Black should continue in the same manner with  g6  followed by ...Bg7, ...O-O and then he will have two possible plans at his disposal: either to play on the queenside by ...Rb8 and ...b5-b4, or on the kingside by ...e5, ...h6, ...Kh7  (the last two are necessary in order to remove the king from the a2-g8 diagonal)  , ...Nh5  (or ...Ne8)  and ...f5.  5...g6  The fianchetto will enable the bishop to exert pressure on the centre.  6.O-O  Bg7  7.Bb3  O-O  8.Re1  White prepares for the Nbd2-f1-g3 maneuver, but Black is ahead in development and starts his own queenside play first.  b5  Threatening ...b4. Black's play is similar to the Closed Sicilian, as he expands on the queenside and attempts to create weaknesses there.  9.a3  White prevents ...b4 as against the other moves Black would play it.  Note that White cannot advance in the centre by   9.d4  because after  cxd4  10.cxd4  Bg4  Black already is very active and threatens to take on f3, thus ruining White's structure as the queen is overburdened to defend both pawn on d4 and knight on f3. After  11.Be3  Black can continue his active play by  Na5  attacking the light-squared bishop and when it retreats  12.Bc2  Nc4  now attacking the dark-squared bishop and the pawn on b2. When that bishop also retreats  13.Bc1  Black can continue the attack in the centre by  Nd7  and White cannot hold the centre.  9...a5  Since ...b4 isn't possible in view of the pin on the a-file after axb4, Black now advances with the a-pawn to a4 in order to fix the light-squared weaknesses  (in particular the b3-square)  left by White's last move.  10.h3  White prevents possible ...Bg4 ideas.  The immediate   10.d4  again doesn't work in view of  cxd4  11.cxd4  Bg4  and White's centre is under attack.  10...Nd7  A fine maneuver. The knight is aiming for b6, anticipating a possible d4, which would weaken the c4-square. The control over c4 can further be increased after ...a4 and ...Na5.  11.Be3  White refrains from playing d4.   11.d4  a4  12.Bc2  e5  and White's centre hasn't brought him anything in view of Black's active pieces, but this is only a moral victory for Black, who managed to prevent White's main idea in the opening.  11...a4  Black continues with his plan to get a grip on the light squares on the queenside.  12.Bc2  Nb6  The knight arrived at its destination and now controls the c4-square.  13.Nbd2  White also fights for the control of the light squares and now threatens d4.  e5 !  An important move - Black finally prevents d4 and can now concentrate on the queenside with moves like ...Be6  (probably prepared by ...h6 in order to prevent Ng5)  and ...Na5. For continuation of Black's subtle strategy please take a look at the model game Timofeev-Kasparov.   3.Nc3  This move doesn't have an independent value as after  e5  We have a transposition to the line 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nf3 e5 4. Bc4 Be7 5. d3 d6.   3.b3  This makes less sense than 2. b3 as here the f2-pawn is blocked by the knight on f3, making the f4 move impossible. Black can use this fact to set-up a pawn centre by playing ...e5, rendering the bishop on b2 passive.  Nc6  4.Bb2  e5  Blocking the long diagonal. Now Black's plan is to play ...g6, ...Bg7, ...Nge7, ...O-O and then start an attack on the kingside by ...f5. Here we examine what happens if White tries to prevent that plan by preparing and pushing d4.  5.Bc4  g6  6.O-O  Bg7  7.c3  White prepares d4, but it is Black who is better prepared for this opening of the centre.  Nge7  Black continues with his original plan. This move also has the benefit of not closing the long diagonal and the bishop on g7.  8.d4  White managed to push d4, but after  exd4  It is important to take with the e-pawn since when White recaptures the d4-pawn will be pinned in view of the undefended bishop on b2.  9.cxd4  O-O  Black finishes development and now threatens ...Bg4 in order to put more pressure on d4.  10.h3  d5  Destroying White's centre.  11.exd5  Nxd5  White has problems with the pressure on d4 so in order to resolve it he will have to relinquish the bishop pair.  12.Bxd5  Qxd5  13.Nc3  Qh5  Here the queen is out of the way and also puts some pressure on White's kingside  (in particular she ties down the white queen to defend the knight on f3, otherwise Black could take ...Bxh3)  .  14.d5  Nb4  Black continues to attack the d-pawn - now he again threatens to take it  (the bishop on b2 is undefended when White takes Nxd5)  and has additional option to further attack it by ...Rd8. Black has excellent play and it is White who needs to be careful here.   3.b4  This version of the Wing Gambit has the benefit of Black having already played ...d6, so playing ...d5 would make less sense. Still, Black can use the fact that the d6-pawn secures the knight on f6 to quickly finish his kingside development while at the same time remaining a pawn up.  cxb4  A free pawn should be taken, especially when no visible compensation is apparent.  4.d4  White will enjoy a full centre, but Black will be a pawn up with a very solid and weakness-free position.  Nf6  5.Bd3  g6  The fianchetto ensures against problems on the kingside.  6.a3  Sooner or later this will be forced as the pawn on b4 controls the c3-square, which White would like to use to put his c-pawn there, to bolster the centre.  bxa3  7.Nxa3  Bg7  8.O-O  O-O  Black finished development and is a pawn up with no problems. His plan is to continue with ...Nc6 and push ...e5, trying to either force exchanges or the d5-push, when he will obtain the c5-square for a knight and also attacking possibilities on the kingside in King's Indian fashion: ... Nh5  (or ...Ne8/... Nd7)  and ...f5. At the same time, he still remains a clear pawn up, this pawn being a passed pawn  (the one on a7)  .   3.g3  With this move White usually wants to develop in a King's Indian Attack manner, but at the same time keeping the option to play c3 and d4 in the centre. Note that he can also start with 3. d3.  Nf6  Black will develop with a kingside fianchetto, but first he must take care to prevent the c3, d4 expansion in the centre. This move forces White to defend the e4-pawn, which also prevents a transposition to an open Sicilian.  Note that the immediate   3...Nc6  may invite  4.d4  4.d3  Nc6  Now the other knight can be developed.  5.Bg2  g6  The kingside fianchetto is often the most effective development against the majority of White's slow systems in the Anti-Sicilians.  6.O-O  Bg7  7.Re1  With this move White shows his intention to play c3 and d4. It is the most flexible move as it keeps the option to develop the b1-knight to a3 or d2.  O-O  Black finishes development of the kingside and now will have to decide how to continue.  8.c3  Rb8  Black prepares for the typical counterplay with ...b5-b4 but first removes the rook from the long diagonal. The rook will be useful on the b-file later on when that file opens.  9.a4  It is useful for White to insert this move because after axb5 the a-file will be opened for his rook.   9.d4 ?!  cxd4  10.cxd4  Bg4  puts White's centre under pressure after a subsequent ...Qb6.  As an illustration, if he plays   9.h3  immediately  (to prevent Bg4)  ,  b5  10.d4  White can still open the a-file after   10.a3  when the game will transpose to the main line after  a5  11.Be3  b4  12.axb4  axb4  10...Nd7  11.Be3  b4  12.Nbd2  Now thanks to the a-file being closed Black has the useful move  Ba6  activating the bishop with comfortable play.  9...a6  Black wants to push ...b5 so this is the only way to prepare it.  10.h3  This is an important move to prepare d4, which if played immediately would be met by taking on d4 and ... Bg4, putting pressure on the centre, especially after ...Qb6, which would attack not only the d4-pawn but also the b2-pawn. Against any other move Black would simply continue with ...b5-b4. For an illustration of an ideal scenario for Black please take a look at the model game Laird-Azmaiparashvili, played via a different move-order but one that is perfect for understanding Black's ideas.  b5  Black continues with his queenside expansion.  11.axb5  axb5  White opened the a-file so his rook is already developed. If compared to the comment to White's 9th move you can see that down the line Black won't have the ...Ba6 in this variation.  12.d4  Nd7  An important move. White finally managed to push d4 and Black reacts by withdrawing the f6-knight in a typical reaction that not only opens the g7-bishop to put pressure on the d4-pawn and the long diagonal, but also to neutralise the threats of e5  (now that square is controlled too many times)  and d5, which would be comfortably met by ... Nce5. This is an important reaction to remember as it renders White's centre exposed and takes away the sting from any advances.  13.Be3  White bolsters the d4-pawn and continues with his development.  b4  Black puts maximum pressure on the queenside.  14.Nbd2  Bb7  Black finished development and is ready for the middlegame. He has a solid and harmonious position with active play on the queenside. The move d5 is not scary because there is always ... Nce5. Ideas for Black in this position are exchanging on c3 and d4 in order to obtain the b4-square for the knight, playing ...Qc7 and ...Rfc8, the move ... e6 can be useful for extra control over d5 and Black can also contest the a-file by playing ...Ra8. Against h4 Black can play ...h6, not weakening the g5-square by ...h5.   3.d3  This move doesn't have an independent value because after  Nc6  4.g3  g6  5.Bg2  Bg7  6.O-O  Nf6  We have a transposition to the variation after 3. g3.   3.h3  A rare move, but it has been tried by some strong players like Nakamura and Karjakin, though only in blitz games   note that the move-order in those games was  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.h3  . The idea is again to keep the option to a transposition to an open Sicilian, while at the same time making a noncommittal move that may support the g4-push.  3...Nf6  This is useful, to force 4. Nc3 and avoid ideas based on c3 and d4.  4.Nc3  e5  This forces a transposition to the line 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nf3 e5 after  The move   4...a6  will not force White into a Najdorf, as he can first play  5.g3  and only when Black commits with the e- or b-pawn can decide to enter an open Sicilian.  5.Bc4  Be7  The threat was Ng5, so Black needs to have the option to castle in order to defend against it.  6.d3  Nc6  7.O-O  O-O  Where White has played the non-ambitious move h3 instead of the more aggressive 7. Ng5. For the details see the model game Aronian-Carlsen.   3.c4  White tries to establish the Maroczy bind after d4.  Bg4  Black fights for the d4-square by attacking the piece that controls it.  4.d4  If White doesn't play this then Black will comfortably develop in Closed Sicilian style by ...Nc6, ...g6, ...Bg7, ...e6 and ...Nge7, keeping firm control over the dark squares in the centre.  cxd4  5.Qxd4  Bxf3  Black naturally takes the knight to double White's f-pawns.  6.gxf3  Nc6  Forcing the queen to move away from the centralised position. White managed to establish the bind, but the price he had to pay was the worsening of his structure and a lack of safe haven for his king. Black has a smooth development now with ...g6, ...Bg7, ...Nf6 and ...O-O.  7.Qd3  g6  8.Nc3  Bg7  9.f4  White tries to make use of the doubled pawns to control the e5-square.  Nf6  10.Bg2  O-O  Black finished development and is now ready for the middlegame. His play in this position is based on the dark squares and the set-up he is aiming for is characteristic for some lines in the Grunfeld Defence. Black's plan is to play ...Bh6, ...Nh5 and ultimately ...e5, aiming to take control of the f4 and d4-squares. If allowed the queen will come to h4  (this may happen after a move like ...e6 as well)  . This concentration of pieces on the kingside can lead to a strong kingside attack. Note that the exchange of the dark-squared bishops is in Black's favour and it's an exchange Black should actively pursue as that would leave White without a piece to control the dark squares. }
3... Nf6
{ This move doesn't attack the pawn on e4 for the time being  (in view of the double attack Qa4+ which would pick up the knight on e4)  but it serves to prevent d4  (because the fourth rank would be covered by the d4-pawn and Black can take on e4)  . }
4. Be2
{ The most popular move in the position, but the others are just as likely to be played. White's general plan in the 3. c3 line is to obtain a full centre after castling and defending the e4-pawn or to get into a Spanish-like position after d3.   4.Bd3  White wants to put the bishop on c2 and push d4, this time trying to make do without the h3 move.  Nc6  Black develops normally to control the centre.  5.Bc2  The move   5.h3  will transpose after  g6  6.Bc2  e5 !  7.O-O  Bg7  to the variation with 4. h3.  5...Bg4  Black uses the fact that White omitted h3 and pins the knight, thus indirectly fighting against d4.  6.d3  Since pushing 6 d4 brings nothing to White, he resorts to slower play.   6.d4  cxd4  7.cxd4  e6  followed by ...d5.  6...e6  The bishop from c8 is out and Black can now develop the dark-squared bishop on e7. Additionally, the move ...e6 helps the central thrust ...d5.  7.Nbd2  Be7  8.h3  Bh5  9.Nf1  White is regrouping but this is slow and allows Black to strike in the centre first.  Castling short allows Black to become ambitious after   9.O-O  d5  10.Re1  Qc7  11.Nf1  O-O-O  with excellent chances thanks to his very harmonious development and central control.  9...d5  This is the point of Black's opening play - he controls the centre well and strikes first.  10.Qe2   10.Ng3  Bg6  If White keeps the tension in the centre, Black can develop the queen on c7 and then decide on which side to castle.  10...c4 !  This is an important move to remember. Black destroys White's central structure.  11.dxc4 ?!  White accepts the pawn sacrifice but ends up in a worse position.  Objectively it is better to keep it simple by   11.exd5  cxd3  12.Bxd3  Qxd5  where Black is at least equal.  11...dxe4  12.Bxe4  Nxe4  13.Qxe4  Bg6  Black has the bishop pair  (the light-squared bishop is particularly strong)  and his lead in development as excellent compensation for the pawn.  14.Qe3  O-O  Black is much better here - he will prevent White from castling by putting a queen or bishop on d3 and may start pushing his central pawns by ...e5, ...f5 etc. White has problems finishing development and finding a shelter for his king. Even an exchange of queens doesn't solve White's problems, for example:  15.N1d2  Qd3 !  Preventing castling. Putting the bishop on d3 is less effective in view of Nd4.  16.Qxd3  Bxd3  And White is paralysed - the knight on d2 is tied down to the defence of the c4-pawn. Defending it by  17.b3  Weakens the c3-pawn that Black can immediately attack by  Bf6  18.Bb2  Nb4 !  Using the pin on the long diagonal and threatening ... Nc2.  19.Kd1  Rfd8  With strong initiative.   4.h3  This move prevents the pinning ...Bg4.  g6  The fianchetto is the only way for Black to develop the dark squared bishop without closing the bishop on c8 by playing ...e6.  5.Bd3  White now wants to play Bc2, O-O and d4. However, Black is in time to develop and counter this plan.  Bg7  6.Bc2  e5 !  An important move, the only way to continue the fight for the d4-square.  7.O-O  O-O  8.d3  Now the play resembles the Spanish, but in a favourable version for Black since he has already fianchettoed his bishop  (in the Spanish he often goes ...Be7 first and then after castling goes ...Re8, ...Bf8, ...g6 and ...Bg7)  . The fianchettoed bishop also allows for aggressive plans on the kingside by pushing ...f5.  The move   8.d4  while possible, is not good for White because after  exd4  9.cxd4  cxd4  10.Nxd4  Nc6  Black is better developed and is putting White's centre under pressure. His next move will be ...d5 with at least equal play for Black.  8...Nc6  Before deciding on his plan Black must first finish his development.  9.Re1  White prepares the typical Spanish maneuver Nbd2-f1-g3/e3.  9...b5  Another aspect that is in Black's favour compared to the Spanish - he can start queenside expansion immediately, without sidelining the knight by ...Na5.  10.Nbd2  a5  Continuing the queenside expansion.  11.a4  White tries to obtain the c4-square for the knight as from there it can also go to e3.  b4  Creating tension on the queenside that White cannot relieve because it would leave the d4-square weak.  12.Nc4  h6  Now that the position has stabilised on the queenside, with Black grabbing space and creating tension only he can release, it is time to improve the position on the kingside. With ...h6 and ... Kh7 Black removes the king from the a2-g8 diagonal and prepares for ...f5 in the long term.  13.Bb3  Kh7  Continuing with the idea to prepare for kingside play based on ...f5.  14.Be3  Ba6  Black is in no hurry to start kingside play - after all it is only him that can play there. He finishes development with the bishop on a6 limiting the movement of the knight on c4 - if the knight moves the pawn on d3 becomes vulnerable. Black can then put the rook on b8, to be ready for a possible opening of the b-file and will then see whether to continue playing on the queenside  (with possible doubling on the b-file)  or on the kingside by preparing ...f5. This possiblity to play on both wings is a clear indicator of the better prospects of Black's position.   4.Bc4  This could have also arisen via 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. c3.  Nc6  While it is possible to take on e4:   4...Nxe4  5.Qa4+  Nc6  6.Bxf7+  Kxf7  7.Qxe4  d5  I think it's better to continue with development along the same lines as in the 4. Bd3 line.  5.Qe2   5.d3  would lead to the line 3. Bc4.  5...Bg4  The pin is again unpleasant for White. Black continues development and discourages d4.  6.h3  Bh5  7.d3  e6  Black develops normally. This time, compared to the 4. Bd3 line, the central thrust ...d5 will have more effect as it will attack the bishop on c4.  8.g4  White tries to break the pin, but weakens the kingside.  Bg6  9.g5  If White develops by   9.Nbd2  then Black can also develop  Be7  so when the knight moves, for example  10.Nf1  Black can strike  d5  attacking the e4-pawn. After  11.exd5  exd5  Black has an excellent position as he will castle and use the e-file to his advantage.  9...d5 !  A strong move that shows Black's potential. It was possible to move the knight or play 9... Bh5, but this is stronger.  10.Bb5  In case of   10.exd5  Nxd5  Black is better as White has exposed his kingside for nothing.  10...dxe4  The exchanges work in Black's favour as White's weaknesses will remain.  11.gxf6  exf3  12.Qxf3  Qd5  Going for the endgame is the simplest. After  13.Qxd5  exd5  Black is better as he has a lead in development, a better structure  (the d3-pawn is particularly tender)  and a space advantage.   4.d3  This move leads to a transposition to the line after 3. g3 after the moves  Nc6  5.g3  g6  6.Bg2  Bg7  7.O-O  O-O  And we have reached the same position from the line 3. g3. }
4... g6
{ Of the two possible plans in all the 3. c3 lines - the fianchetto and the ...Bg4 Black chooses the fianchetto because here 4... Bg4 would not be a pin. }
5. O-O Bg7 6. Bb5+
{ This check gave some rise to the popularity of the line at the end of the 20th century. It allows White to defend the pawn on e4 without a loss of tempo and push d4.   6.Re1  This is the slower alternative, after which it will be difficult for White to push d4 to his advantage.  O-O  Now that there is no check on a4 Black threatens to take on e4, so White defends it with his next move.  7.Bf1  Nc6  Black continues development and controls the d4-square as White still cannot play d4.  8.h3  A necessary final preparation.  The immediate   8.d4  is met by the typical  cxd4  9.cxd4  Bg4  when White has problems defending his centre.  8...e5 !  White was ready to push d4, but Black prevents it.  9.d3  White switches to the Spanish structure.   9.d4  isn't very good because after all the exchanges on d4:  exd4  10.cxd4  cxd4  11.Nxd4  Nxd4  12.Qxd4  Black plays  Re8  threatening ...Ne4 or ...Bf5 after which he has free play in the centre while White is still undeveloped.  9...h6  This useful move to guard against Ng5 has to be played sooner rather than later as it allows the bishop to come out to e6 without fearing attacks.  10.a3  White has one active plan in this position and that is the b4-push. If he doesn't prepare b4 Black will play ...Be6 and push ...d5 with an advantageous position.  Be6  Black doesn't prevent b4 by playing ...a5 as that would give away the light squares on the queenside after White plays a4. Then he could place his knight on c4 from where it cannot be chased away.  11.b4  a6  Not only preventing b5, but also preparing to play ...b5 himself. In view of his superior central control Black is better prepared for the queenside confrontation.  12.Bb2  White develops and threatens to push d4.  Nd7  Opening the fianchettoed bishop in order to control d4. This move is also part of the plan to push ...b5 and put the knight on b6, increasing Black's presence on the queenside.  13.d4  White must act quickly because if he plays   13.Nbd2  Black will respond with  b5  and after ...Nb6 Black will simply be better as his queenside presence is becoming threatening - he has active ideas like ...Na4, ...c4, ...cxb4 and ...d5.  13...exd4  Black should take with the e-pawn as after White recaptures the d4-pawn will be pinned.  14.cxd4  Rc8  Black prepares for the mass simplifications that would lead to the opening of the c-file.  15.Qd2  Defending the bishop and threatening d5.  cxd4  Now everything is exchanged on d4 and the endgame that arises is very pleasant for Black.  16.Nxd4  Nxd4  17.Bxd4  Bxd4  18.Qxd4  Qf6  Making sure the queens are exchanged as well.  19.Qxf6  Nxf6  White is still undeveloped and after he plays  20.Nd2  He allows  Rc3  With at least an equal endgame for Black - White has to be a bit careful defending the pawns on a3 and e4. }
6... Bd7
{ Covering with the bishop like in the Moscow Variation in order to speed up the development. }
7. Bxd7+ Nbxd7
{ Black recaptures like in the Moscow Variation. In fact, he is a tempo up compared to the Moscow Variation since here White played Be2 before giving the check on b5. And while in the Moscow Variation Black reacts with ...e6 and not with ...g6, the extra tempo makes up for this difference and gives Black pleasant play. }
8. Re1
{ White defends e4 and prepares d4.  In case of   8.Qe2  with the same idea Black would play exactly the same:  O-O  9.d4  e6 }
8... O-O { Black finished development and his pieces are well-placed. } 9. d4
e6
{ A useful move, preventing the e5-e6 idea. Black's plan now is to open the c-file by taking on d4 and then put a rook on c8. }
10. Bf4 Qb6 { Defending d6 and exerting pressure on d4 and b2. } 11. Nbd2 cxd4
{ White is threatening Nc4, so Black first opens the c-file before controling that square with ...Rc8. }
12. cxd4 Rfc8
{ Black has a very comfortable position. White's centre is not felt as Black creates play on the queenside, circumventing it. He has active ideas like doubling on the c-file, pushing the a-pawn  (like ...a5-a4 and then perhaps ...Qa6, ...Nb6-c4 etc.)  , while the d6-pawn can be covered by ...Bf8 if the queen needs to leave the sixth rank. }
