1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bc4
{ This move had a period of popularity quite some time ago. Its aim is to obtain a Spanish-like position after c3, d3 followed by the typical maneuver Nbd2-f1-g3. White will also try to push d4 and obtain a full centre if possible. }
3... Nf6
{ By attacking the e4-pawn Black forces White to defend it by d3, thus preventing possible ideas with quick c3 and d4. }
4. d3 Nc6 { Black develops normally, controlling the centre. } 5. c3
{ White also follows his plan of play as in the Spanish. } 5... g6
{ The fianchetto will enable the bishop to exert pressure in the centre. } 6.
O-O Bg7 7. Bb3 O-O 8. Re1
{ White prepares for the Nbd2-f1-g3 maneuver, but Black is ahead in development and starts his own queenside play first. }
8... b5
{ Threatening ...b4. Black's play is similar to the Closed Sicilian, as he expands on the queenside and attempts to create weaknesses there. }
9. a3 { White prevents ...b4 as against the other moves Black would play it. }
9... a5
{ Since ...b4 isn't possible in view of the pin on the a-file after axb4, Black now advances with the a-pawn to a4 in order to fix the light-squared weaknesses  (in particular the b3-square)  left by White's last move. }
10. h3 { White prevents possible ...Bg4 ideas. } 10... Nd7
{ A fine maneuver. The knight is aiming for b6, anticipating a possible d4, which would weaken the c4-square. The control over c4 can further be increased after ...a4 and ...Na5. }
11. d4 a4 12. Bc2 e5
{ and White's centre hasn't brought him anything in view of Black's active pieces, but this is only a moral victory for Black, who managed to prevent White's main idea in the opening. }
