[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Various 3rd Moves"]
[Black "3.b3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. b3
{ This makes less sense than 2. b3 as here the f2-pawn is blocked by the knight on f3, making the f4 move impossible. Black can use this fact to set-up a pawn centre by playing ...e5, rendering the bishop on b2 passive. }
3... Nc6 4. Bb2 e5
{ Blocking the long diagonal. Now Black's plan is to play ...g6, ...Bg7, ...Nge7, ...O-O and then start an attack on the kingside by ...f5. Here we examine what happens if White tries to prevent that plan by preparing and pushing d4. }
5. Bc4 g6 6. O-O Bg7 7. c3
{ White prepares d4, but it is Black who is better prepared for this opening of the centre. }
7... Nge7
{ Black continues with his original plan. This move also has the benfit of not closing the long diagonal and the bishop on g7. }
8. d4 { White managed to push d4, but after } 8... exd4
{ It is important to take with the e-pawn since when White recaptures the d4-pawn will be pinned in view of the undefended bishop on b2. }
9. cxd4 O-O
{ Black finishes development and now threatens ...Bg4 in order to put more pressure on d4. }
10. h3 d5 { Destroying White's centre. } 11. exd5 Nxd5
{ White has problems with the pressure on d4 so in order to resolve it he will have to relinquish the bishop pair. }
12. Bxd5 Qxd5 13. Nc3 Qh5
{ Here the queen is out of the way and also puts some pressure on White's kingside  (in particular she ties down the white queen to defend the knight on f3, otherwise Black could take ...Bxh3)  . }
14. d5 Nb4
{ Black continues to attack the d-pawn - now he again threatens to take it  (the bishop on b2 is undefended when White takes Nxd5)  and has additional option to further attack it by ...Rd8. Black has excellent play and it is White who needs to be careful here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Various 3rd Moves"]
[Black "3.b4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. b4
{ This version of the Wing Gambit has the benefit of Black having already played ...d6, so playing ...d5 would make less sense. Still, Black can use the fact that the d6-pawn secures the knight on f6 to quickly finish his kingside development while at the same time remaining a pawn up. }
3... cxb4
{ A free pawn should be taken, especially when no visible compensation is apparent. }
4. d4
{ White will enjoy a full centre, but Black will be a pawn up with a very solid and weakness-free position. }
4... Nf6 5. Bd3 g6 { The fianchetto ensures against problems on the kingside. }
6. a3
{ Sooner or later this will be forced as the pawn on b4 controls the c3-square, which White would like to use to put his c-pawn there, to bolster the centre. }
6... bxa3 7. Nxa3 Bg7 8. O-O O-O
{ Black finished development and is a pawn up with no problems. His plan is to continue with ...Nc6 and push ...e5, trying to either force exchanges or the d5-push, when he will obtain the c5-square for a knight and also attacking possibilities on the kingside in King's Indian fashion: ...Nh5  (or ...Ne8/...Nd7)  and ...f5. At the same time, he still remains a clear pawn up, this pawn being a passed pawn  (the one on a7)  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Various 3rd Moves"]
[Black "3.g3 Variation 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. g3
{ With this move White usually wants to develop in an King's Indian Attack manner, but at the same time keeping the option to play c3 and d4 in the centre. Note that he can also start with 3. d3. }
3... Nf6
{ Black will develop with a kingside fianchetto, but first he must take care to prevent the c3, d4 expansion in the centre. This move forces White to defend the e4-pawn, which also prevents a transposition to an open Sicilian. }
4. d3 Nc6 { Now the other knight can be developed. } 5. Bg2 g6
{ The kingside fianchetto is often the most effective development against the majority of White's slow systems in the Anti-Sicilians. }
6. O-O Bg7 7. Re1
{ With this move White shows his intention to play c3 and d4. It is the most flexible move as it keeps the option to develop the b1-knight to a3 or d2. }
7... O-O
{ Black finishes development of the kingside and now will have to decide how to continue. }
8. c3 Rb8
{ Black prepares for the typical counterplay with ...b5-b4 but first removes the room from the long diagonal. The rook will be useful on the b-file later on when that file opens. }
9. d4 cxd4 10. cxd4 Bg4
{ puts White's centre under pressure after a subsequent ...Qb6. } *

