[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Various 3rd Moves"]
[Black "3.g3 Variation 3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. g3
{ With this move White usually wants to develop in an King's Indian Attack manner, but at the same time keeping the option to play c3 and d4 in the centre. Note that he can also start with 3. d3. }
3... Nf6
{ Black will develop with a kingside fianchetto, but first he must take care to prevent the c3, d4 expansion in the centre. This move forces White to defend the e4-pawn, which also prevents a transposition to an open Sicilian. }
4. d3 Nc6 { Now the other knight can be developed. } 5. Bg2 g6
{ The kingside fianchetto is often the most effective development against the majority of White's slow systems in the Anti-Sicilians. }
6. O-O Bg7 7. Re1
{ With this move White shows his intention to play c3 and d4. It is the most flexible move as it keeps the option to develop the b1-knight to a3 or d2. }
7... O-O
{ Black finishes development of the kingside and now will have to decide how to continue. }
8. c3 Rb8
{ Black prepares for the typical counterplay with ...b5-b4 but first removes the room from the long diagonal. The rook will be useful on the b-file later on when that file opens. }
9. a4
{ It is useful for White to insert this move because after axb5 the a-file will be opened for his rook. }
9... a6 { Black wants to push ...b5 so this is the only way to prepare it. }
10. h3
{ This is an important move to prepare d4, which if played immediately would be met by taking on d4 and ... Bg4, putting pressure on the centre, especially after ...Qb6, which would attack not only the d4-pawn but also the b2-pawn. Against any other move Black would simply continue with ...b5-b4. For an illustration of an ideal scenario for Black please take a look at the model game Laird-Azmaiparashvili, played via a different move-order but one that is perfect for understanding Black's ideas. }
10... b5 { Black continues with his queenside expansion. } 11. axb5 axb5
{ White opened the a-file so his rook is already developed. If compared to the comment to White's 9th move you can see that down the line Black won't have the ...Ba6 in this variation. }
12. d4 Nd7
{ An important move. White finally managed to push d4 and Black reacts by withdrawing the f6-knight in a typical reaction that not only opens the g7-bishop to put pressure on the d4-pawn and the long diagonal, but also to neutralise the threats of e5  (now that square is controlled too many times)  and d5, which would be comfortably met by ... Nce5. This is an important reaction to remember as it renders White's centre exposed and takes away the sting from any advances. }
13. Be3 { White bolsters the d4-pawn and continues with his development. }
13... b4 { Black puts maximum pressure on the queenside. } 14. Nbd2 Bb7
{ Black finished development and is ready for the middlegame. He has a solid and harmonious position with active play on the queenside. The move d5 is not scary because there is always ... Nce5. Ideas for Black in this position are exhanging on c3 and d4 in order to obtain the b4-square for the knight, playing ...Qc7 and ...Rfc8, the move ...e6 can be useful for extra control over d5 and Black can also contest the a-file by playing ...Ra8. Against h4 Black can play ...h6, not weakening the g5-square by ...h5. }
