1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. h3
{ A rare move, but it has been tried by some strong players like Nakamura and Karjakin, though only in blitz games   note that the move-order in those games was  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.h3  . The idea is again to keep the option to a transposition to an open Sicilian, while at the same time making a noncommittal move that may support the g4-push. }
3... Nf6
{ This is useful, to force 4. Nc3 and avoid ideas based on c3 and d4. } 4. Nc3
e5 { This forces a transposition to the line 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nf3 e5 after } 5.
Bc4 Be7
{ The threat was Ng5, so Black needs to have the option to castle in order to defend against it. }
6. d3 Nc6 7. O-O O-O
{ Where White has played the non-ambitious move h3 instead of the more aggressive 7. Ng5. For the details see the model game Aronian-Carlsen. }
