[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Various 3rd Moves"]
[Black "3.c4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. c4
{ White tries to establish the Maroczy bind after d4. } 3... Bg4
{ Black fights for the d4-square by attacking the piece that controls it. } 4.
d4
{ If White doesn't play this then Black will comfortably develop in Closed Sicilian style by ...Nc6, ...g6, ...Bg7, ...e6 and ...Nge7, keeping firm control over the dark squares in the centre. }
4... cxd4 5. Qxd4 Bxf3
{ Black naturally takes the knight to double White's f-pawns. } 6. gxf3 Nc6
{ Forcing the queen to move away from the centralised position. White managed to establish the bind, but the price he had to pay was the worsening of his structure and a lack of safe haven for his king. Black has a smooth development now with ...g6, ...Bg7, ...Nf6 and ...O-O. }
7. Qd3 g6 8. Nc3 Bg7 9. f4
{ White tries to make use of the doubled pawns to control the e5-square. } 9...
Nf6 10. Bg2 O-O
{ Black finished development and is now ready for the middlegame. His play in this position is based on the dark squares and the set-up he is aiming for is characteristic for some lines in the Grunfeld Defence. Black's plan is to play ...Bh6, ...Nh5 and ultimately ...e5, aiming to take control of the f4 and d4-squares. If allowed the queen will come to h4  (this may happen after a move like ...e6 as well)  . This concentration of pieces on the kingside can lead to a strong kingside attack. Note that the exchange of the dark-squared bishops is in Black's favour and it's an exchange Black should actively pursue as that would leave White without a piece to control the dark squares. }
