1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. c3
{ Apart from the Moscow Variation, White has many other options on his 3rd move. The most theoretically important is the move 3. c3. In this variation Black has two general plans at his disposal: the fianchetto of the dark-squared bishop and the ...Bg4 pin followed by ...e6. The general rule of thumb is that if the pin is allowed, Black plays it, if it isn't   or it is not a pin anymore , as in the  4.Be2  line  then Black plays the fianchetto. }
3... Nf6
{ This move doesn't attack the pawn on e4 for the time being  (in view of the double attack Qa4+ which would pick up the knight on e4)  but it serves to prevent d4  (because the fourth rank would be covered by the d4-pawn and Black can take on e4)  . }
