[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. c3
{ Apart from the Moscow Variation, White has many other options on his 3rd move. The most theoretically important is the move 3. c3. In this variation Black has two general plans at his disposal: the fianchetto of the dark-squared bishop and the ...Bg4 pin followed by ...e6. The general rule of thumb is that if the pin is allowed, Black plays it, if it isn't   or it is not a pin anymore , as in the  4.Be2  line  then Black plays the fianchetto. }
3... Nf6
{ This move doesn't attack the pawn on e4 for the time being  (in view of the double attack Qa4+ which would pick up the knight on e4)  but it serves to prevent d4  (because the fourth rank would be covered by the d4-pawn and Black can take on e4)  . }
4. Bd3
{ White wants to put the bishop on c2 and push d4, this time trying to make do without the h3 move. }
4... Nc6 { Black develops normally to control the centre. } 5. Bc2 Bg4
{ Black uses the fact that White omitted h3 and pins the knight, thus indirectly fighting against d4. }
6. d3
{ Since pushing 6 d4 brings nothing to White, he resorts to slower play. } 6...
e6
{ The bishop from c8 is out and Black can now develop the dark-squared bishop on e7. Additionally, the move ...e6 helps the central thrust ...d5. }
7. Nbd2 Be7 8. h3 Bh5 9. Nf1
{ White is regrouping but this is slow and allows Black to strike in the centre first. }
9... d5
{ This is the point of Black's opening play - he controls the centre well and strikes first. }
10. Qe2 c4
{ This is an important move to remember. Black destroys White's central structure. }
11. dxc4 { White accepts the pawn sacrifice but ends up in a worse position. }
11... dxe4 12. Bxe4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 Bg6
{ Black has the bishop pair  (the light-squared bishop is particularly strong)  and his lead in development as excellent compensation for the pawn. }
14. Qe3 O-O
{ Black is much better here - he will prevent White from castling by putting a queen or bishop on d3 and may start pushing his central pawns by ...e5, ...f5 etc. White has problems finishing development and finding a shelter for his king. Even an exchange of queens doesn't solve White's problems, for example: }
15. N1d2 Qd3
{ Preventing castling. Putting the bishop on d3 is less effective in view of Nd4. }
16. Qxd3 Bxd3
{ And White is paralysed - the knight on d2 is tied down to the defence of the c4-pawn. Defending it by }
17. b3 { Weakens the c3-pawn that Black can immediately attack by } 17... Bf6
18. Bb2 Nb4 { Using the pin on the long diagonal and threatening ...Nc2. } 19.
Kd1 Rfd8 { With strong initiative. } *

