[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Various 3rd Moves"]
[Black "3.c3 Variation 8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. c3
{ Apart from the Moscow Variation, White has many other options on his 3rd move. The most theoretically important is the move 3. c3. In this variation Black has two general plans at his disposal: the fianchetto of the dark-squared bishop and the ...Bg4 pin followed by ...e6. The general rule of thumb is that if the pin is allowed, Black plays it, if it isn't   or it is not a pin anymore , as in the  4.Be2  line  then Black plays the fianchetto. }
3... Nf6
{ This move doesn't attack the pawn on e4 for the time being  (in view of the double attack Qa4+ which would pick up the knight on e4)  but it serves to prevent d4  (because the fourth rank would be covered by the d4-pawn and Black can take on e4)  . }
4. h3 { This move prevents the pinning ...Bg4. } 4... g6
{ The fianchetto is the only way for Black to develop the dark squared bishop without closing the bishop on c8 by playing ...e6. }
5. Bd3
{ White now wants to play Bc2, O-O and d4. However, Black is in time to develop and counter this plan. }
5... Bg7 6. Bc2 e5
{ An important move, the only way to continue the fight for the d4-square. } 7.
O-O O-O 8. d3
{ After 8 d3 play resembles the Spanish, but in a favourable version for Black since he has already fianchettoed his bishop  (in the Spanish he often goes ...Be7 first and then after castling goes ...Re8, ...Bf8, ...g6 and ...Bg7)  . The fianchettoed bishop also allows for aggressive plans on the kingside by pushing ...f5. }
8... Nc6
{ Before deciding on his plan Black must first finish his development. } 9. Re1
{ White prepares the typical Spanish maneuver Nbd2-f1-g3   e3  . } 9... b5
{ Another aspect that is in Black's favour compared to the Spanish - he can start queenside expansion immediately, without sidelining the knight by ...Na5. }
10. Nbd2 a5 { Continuing the queenside expansion. } 11. a4
{ White tries to obtain the c4-square for the knight as from there it can also go to e3. }
11... b4
{ Creating tension on the queenside that White cannot relieve because it would leave the d4-square weak. }
12. Nc4 h6
{ Now that the position has stabilised on the queenside, with Black grabbing space and creating tension only he can release, it is time to improve the position on the kingside. With ...h6 and ...Kh7 Black removes the king from the a2-g8 diagonal and prepares for ...f5 in the long term. }
13. Bb3 Kh7
{ Continuing with the idea to prepare for kingside play based on ...f5. } 14.
Be3 Ba6
{ Black is in no hurry to start kingside play - after all it is only him that can play there. He finishes development with the bishop on a6 limiting the movement of the knight on c4 - if the knight moves the pawn on d3 becomes vulnerable. Black can then put the rook on b8, to be ready for a possible opening of the b-file and will then see whether to continue playing on the queenside  (with possible doubling on the b-file)  or on the kingside by preparing ...f5. This possiblity to play on both wings is a clear indicator of the better prospects of Black's position. }
*

