1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. c3
{ Apart from the Moscow Variation, White has many other options on his 3rd move. The most theoretically important is the move 3. c3. In this variation Black has two general plans at his disposal: the fianchetto of the dark-squared bishop and the ...Bg4 pin followed by ...e6. The general rule of thumb is that if the pin is allowed, Black plays it, if it isn't   or it is not a pin anymore , as in the  4.Be2  line  then Black plays the fianchetto. }
3... Nf6
{ This move doesn't attack the pawn on e4 for the time being  (in view of the double attack Qa4+ which would pick up the knight on e4)  but it serves to prevent d4  (because the fourth rank would be covered by the d4-pawn and Black can take on e4)  . }
4. Be2
{ The most popular move in the position, but the others are just as likely to be played. White's general plan in the 3 c3 line is to obtain a full centre after castling and defending the e4-pawn or to get into a Spanish-like position after d3. }
4... g6
{ Of the two possible plans in all the 3. c3 lines - the fianchetto and the ... Bg4 Black chooses the fianchetto because here 4... Bg4 would not be a pin. }
5. O-O Bg7 6. Re1
{ This is the slower alternative, after which it will be difficult for White to push d4 to his advantage. }
6... O-O
{ Now that there is no check on a4 Black threatens to take on e4, so White defends it with his next move. }
7. Bf1 Nc6
{ Black continues development and controls the d4-square as White still cannot play d4. }
8. h3 { A necessary final preparation. } 8... e5
{ White was ready to push d4, but Black prevents it. } 9. d3
{ White switches to the Spanish structure. } 9... h6
{ This useful move to guard against Ng5 has to be played sooner rather than later as it allows the bishop to come out to e6 without fearing attacks. }
10. a3
{ White has one active plan in this position and that is the b4-push. If he doesn't prepare b4 Black will play ...Be6 and push ...d5 with an advantageous position. }
10... Be6
{ Black doesn't prevent b4 by playing ...a5 as that would give away the light squares on the queenside after White plays a4. Then he could place his knight on c4 from where it cannot be chased away. }
11. b4 a6
{ Not only preventing b5, but also preparing to play ...b5 himself. In view of his superior central control Black is better prepared for the queenside confrontation. }
12. Bb2 { White develops and threatens to push d4. } 12... Nd7
{ White must act quickly because if he plays } 13. Nbd2
{ Black will respond with } 13... b5
{ and after ...Nb6, Black will simply be better as his queenside presence is becoming threatening - he has active ideas like ...Na4, ...c4, ...cxb4 and ...d5. }
