{ The most popular move in the position, but the others are just as likely to be played. White's general plan in the 3 c3 line is to obtain a full centre after castling and defending the e4-pawn or to get into a Spanish-like position after d3. }
4... g6
{ Of the two possible plans in all the 3. c3 lines - the fianchetto and the ... Bg4 Black chooses the fianchetto because here 4... Bg4 would not be a pin. }
5. O-O Bg7 6. Bb5+
{ This check gave some rise to the popularity of the line at the end of the 20th century. It allows White to defend the pawn on e4 without a loss of tempo and push d4. }
6... Bd7
{ Covering with the bishop like in the Moscow Variation in order to speed up the development. }
7. Bxd7+ Nbxd7
{ Black recaptures like in the Moscow Variation. In fact, he is a tempo up compared to the Moscow Variation since here White played Be2 before giving the check on b5. And while in the Moscow Variation Black reacts with ...e6 and not with ...g6, the extra tempo makes up for this difference and gives Black pleasant play. }
8. Re1 { White defends e4 and prepares d4. } 8... O-O
{ Black finished development and his pieces are well-placed. } 9. d4 e6
{ A useful move, preventing the e5-e6 idea. Black's plan now is to open the c-file by taking on d4 and then put a rook on c8. }
10. Bf4 Qb6 { Defending d6 and exerting pressure on d4 and b2. } 11. Nbd2 cxd4
{ White is threatening Nc4, so Black first opens the c-file before controling that square with ...Rc8. }
12. cxd4 Rfc8
{ Black has a very comfortable position. White's centre is not felt as Black creates play on the queenside, circumventing it. He has active ideas like doubling on the c-file, pushing the a-pawn  (like ...a5-a4 and then perhaps ...Qa6, ...Nb6-c4 etc.)  , while the d6-pawn can be covered by ...Bf8 if the queen needs to leave the sixth rank. }
