[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Moscow Variation"]
[Black "The Moscow Variation Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+
{ The Moscow Variation is practically as equally popular as the main lines of the open Sicilian. It conveniently allows White to avoid the forcing lines of the open Sicilians while at the same time giving him a playable middlegame position. }
3... Bd7
{ Of the three possible moves this one is the simplest. After the exchange of the bishops Black's position will be easier to play as the exchanges favour the side with less space. }
4. Bxd7+
{ The main move. The alternatives are less ambitious.   4.c4  With this move White plays to establish a Maroczy bind, but with precise play Black manages to either prevent it or to obtain a favourable version of it.  Nf6  Developing with tempo by attacking the e4-pawn.  5.Nc3  a6  Forcing the exchange on d7.  6.Bxd7+  Nbxd7  As in the main line with 4. Bxd7+ Black recaptures with the knight. The idea is to liberate the eighth rank for the rook so that it can quickly come to c8, hitting the pawn on c4.  7.O-O  In case of the immediate   7.d4  Black uses the weakness of the c4-pawn in order to push ...b5. This is done after  cxd4  8.Nxd4  Rc8  9.Qe2  Qc7  10.b3  b5 !  with excellent play for Black.  7...Rc8  Black uses the access to the c8-square to hinder d4. For an alternative and extremely interesting treatment of the position please take a look at the model game Nguyen-Anton.  8.b3  e6  With the queenside developed Black needs to finish his kingside development now.  9.d4  cxd4  10.Qxd4  White would like to take with the knight, but that is impossible as it allows 10 Nd4 b5.  Be7  Black will finish development with his next move that will be castling.  11.Bb2  O-O  12.Rfd1  Qc7  Black has an excellent version of the hedgehog because White's queen doesn't belong on d4. This makes it difficult for White to harmonise his position while Black is well positioned and can continue with normal play. His next moves can be ...Rfd8 and/or ...Ne5  (not fearing Nxe5 dxe5 because then he will gain access to the c5 and d4-squares)  . As usual in the hedgehog formations his ultimate goal is to push . ..b5 or ...d5.   4.a4  With this move White indicates that he just wants to get a playable position without theory. This means that Black will obtain a good position in more or less any way.  Nf6  Attacking the e4-pawn. With the a-pawn already on a4 the hedgehog formation and an attempt to play with d4 are out of place, so White normally plays d3 and then develops slowly.  5.d3  a6  Immediately forcing White to exchange bishops as going back to c4 would be a loss of tempo.  6.Bxd7+  Qxd7  Since White is not going to play directly in the centre and his only idea to do something in the position is to play a5 and try to fix Black's queenside, Black can develop the knight on c6 and move the queen to c7, keeping an eye on the a5-pawn.  7.a5  If White doesn't play this immediately Black can stop it by playing ...Nc6 and ... Qc7.  Nc6  8.Nbd2  The knight rushes to c4 to defend the a5-pawn.  Qc7  Attacking the pawn and moving the queen from d7, thus avoiding a knight fork on b6 later on.  9.Nc4  e6  10.O-O  d5  Black plays ...d5 before White can prevent it by Bf4.  In case Black is fine with a possible repetition, Black can play   10...Be7  11.Bf4  Nh5  12.Be3  Nf6  13.Bf4  Nh5  11.exd5  Nxd5  Now with the e-file open  (there is no bishop on e7)  Black must recapture with the knight.  12.Re1  Be7  With castling to come next and then probably ...Bf6, ... Rad8 Black has an excellent position. }
4... Nxd7
{ With this recapture Black aims for quick development after ...Ngf6, ... e6, ... Be7 and ...O-O. This move also allows for a quick ...Rc8, an important move for Black in the hedgehog structures that will often arise. The resulting hedgehog positions are comfortable for Black as with his quick and smooth development he can concentrate on the upcoming middlegame where his main plans are the ...b5 and ...d5 thrusts. In case these are not viable, he will maneuver with moves like ...Qa5  (-h5)  (or ...Qc7-b8, in order to support ...b5)  , ...Rfe8   d8  , ...Bf8  (or sometimes the maneuver ...Bd8-b6)  , ...Ne5  (-g6)  . There is always something to play for in the hedgehog so Black won't run out of ideas. Additionally, the resulting positions are calm and Black can rely on his positional understanding more than on exact memorisation, though there are a few lines where precise move-orders offer Black the best the position can offer. }
5. O-O Ngf6
{ Attacking the e4-pawn and asking White to determine his intentions. Speaking of White's plans, he has two main ones at his disposal:   1. To go for the hedgehog formation with c4 and d4, or   2. To play for a full centre with c3 and d4. Both these plans can be executed with a queen on e2 or a rook on e1, which means we have 4 possible set-ups for White.   Of the lesser plans the idea to play like in an open Sicilian by pushing d4 and after ... cxd4 taking Nxd4 and playing Nc3 is harmless as Black has quick development and easy queenside play in that case. }
6. Qe2
{ The hedgehog plan with a queen on e2 is considered the most promising for White.   6.Re1  Here we will explore both plans: the hedgehog and going for c3 and d4, with a rook on e1.  e6  As usual, Black develops in the most natural way with ...e6, ...Be7 and ...O-O.  7.c3  White wants to establish a full centre by pushing d4.   7.c4  The hedgehog with a rook on e1 is considered less optimal than with a queen on e2 because in the latter case the rook goes to d1, immediately to the open d-file. Still, sometimes White plays like this so it is worth knowing how to play, especially as here we will encounter a typical maneuver by Black.  Be7  Black continues development and White establishes the central bind.  8.Nc3  O-O  9.d4  cxd4  10.Nxd4  Rc8  The c-file has been opened so Black attacks the c4-pawn immediately.  11.b3  a6  The b5-square is very important in these structures - Black has to control it in order to prevent a possible Nb5 which would attack the d6-pawn and also to support his own ...b5 push. The immediate threat is to push ...b5 now as the knight on c3 is not protected.  12.Bb2  White protects the knight and prevents ...b5.  Qa5  Another typical move. The queen is active on the fifth rank - it can go to h5 or g5, and it also supports the ...b5 push.  13.Qd2  Bd8 !  An instructive maneuver ! The bishop is activated and goes to b6. What is important to know is that the d6-pawn is defended tactically. After  14.Rad1  Bb6  15.Nde2  The pawn doesn't really hang as after  Rfd8  White cannot take it in view of  16.Qxd6 ?  Ng4  Or 16... Ne5 and then ...Nd3.  17.Rf1  Bc7  With taking on h2 and ...Qh5 to come, with a winning position.  7...Be7  Black continues his normal development.  8.d4  O-O  In these positions when White has the full centre Black can simply ignore it because he has smooth development and any pawn advance can easily be absorbed. If the pawns stay on d4 and e4 Black will create counterplay on the c-file by taking on d4 and playing ...Rc8. He can also consider the ...d5 push, which would force e5 by White  (allowing an IQP is not really an option for White - without the light-squared bishop he doesn't have enough dynamic potential to compensate for the IQP)  in which case the resulting French structure is in Black's favour as he has the better bishop.  9.e5  This push puts immediate pressure, but the line shows how Black absorbs this pressure.  Ne8  The knight retreats, but it can easily arrive on d5 via c7.  10.exd6  This resolves the tension in the centre.  In case of   10.Qe2  cxd4  11.cxd4  dxe5  12.dxe5  Nc7  13.Nc3  Nb6  and ...Nd5.  10...Bxd6  Both recaptures are possible, but with the e5-pawn gone the knight from e8 can return to f6.  11.Na3  White also needs to develop.  In case of   11.d5  exd5  12.Qxd5  Qc7  Black will unravel by ...Nef6.  11...cxd4  This capture wins the c5-square for the bishop in case it is attacked by  12.Nc4  Bc5  13.Nxd4  Nef6  Black has an excellent position. He has no weaknesses and has smooth play with his pieces. He can further consider pushing ...a6 and ...b5, a typical Sicilian queenside play. In the long term he will want to expand in the centre and kingside where his pawn majority lies.  Another plan for White is to initiatilly play in a slow manner with 6. d3, with the idea to go Ng5 and allow for f4. Still, with Black's king in the centre this won't lead to an attack because Black can easily castle queenside. Here is a sample line:   6.d3  e6  7.Nc3  Be7  8.Ng5  Nb8  A nice move, re-routing the knight to c6 from where it will have more control over the centre.  9.f4  Nc6  10.f5  This may start to look threatening, but Black will castle queenside !  Qd7  11.Bd2  h6  12.Nh3  O-O-O  and Black has a great position as White only over-extended himself. }
6... e6 { Continuing with the usual development. } 7. b3
{ This is considered the most precise way to prepare for the hedgehog formation. The point is to have the c4-pawn already protected once it lands there.   7.c4  This is another way to establish the bind, but it has the drawback that now White is forced to develop the bishop on e3 rather than on b2.  Rc8  Immediately preparing for the opening of the c-file.  8.Nc3  Be7  Now Black continues with the usual development.  9.d4  Insisting on the immediate d4.  White could still change his mind and play   9.b3  with Bb2 to follow, which would transpose back to the main line that starts with 7. b3.  9...cxd4  10.Nxd4  O-O  11.Be3  The point of Black's play is seen after   11.b3  d5 !  as it takes advantage of the pin on the c-file in view of the undefended knight on c3. Then  12.e5  Ne8  isn't dangerous and after  13.Rd1  dxc4  14.bxc4  Qa5  Black can look forward to playing against the weak c4-pawn.  11...a6  The usual move. Now Black is ready for the middlegame. With the white bishop on e3 White has some issues with the c4-pawn and the knight on c3: if the pawn is attacked then playing b3 leaves the knight undefended and Black can use this by playing ... b5.  12.Rac1  Defending the knight in advance.  More aggressive plans like   12.Rad1  Qa5  13.f4  are well-met with  Qb4  creating counterplay against the c4-pawn and after  14.Rc1  the maneuver  Bd8  removes the bishop from the undefended e7-square and threatens the capture on c4  (otherwise White had the discovered attack Nd5)  . Then  15.b3  can be met by  b5  12...Qa5  Activating the queen on a5 rather than on c7 in this case, as the rook is already on the c-file, thus avoiding to put the queen on the same file as the opponent's rook.  13.b3  White secures his queenside.  Rfe8  A good move - in the hedgehog  (and not only here !)  it always makes sense to put the rook on the same file as the opponent's queen.  14.Rfd1  d5 !  Generally speaking, if Black manages to push ...d5 he equalises at least. Here it all works in his favour as the simplifications lead to equality after  15.exd5  exd5  16.Nxd5  White cannot take with the c-pawn as the knight on c3 is hanging.  Nxd5  17.cxd5  Rxc1  18.Rxc1  Qxd5  With an equal position.   7.c3  Building a full centre with the queen on e2 is met in the same manner as with the rook on e1 instead.  Be7  8.d4  O-O  Just as in the line with 6 Re1 Black ignores White's centre.  9.e5  The difference with the 6 Re1 line is that here the rook can be placed more actively on the d-file, so White tries to open the game. In case of other moves Black can follow the same recipe by taking on d4 and playing ...Rc8, ... Nb6 etc.  Ne8  Black's reaction is the same. The only difference is that after  10.Rd1  cxd4  11.cxd4  Now instead of taking on e5 Black plays  Nc7 !  Black sensibly refrains from opening the d-file while at the same time employing the same idea to put a knight on d5. White cannot stop this as  12.Nc3  Is met by  Nb6  And on the next move the knight will land on d5.  The immediate   7.d4  is rather hasty because after  cxd4  8.Nxd4  Be7  9.c4  Black has  Qa5 !  preventing b3 and Bb2. This forces White to change to the alternative development of the bishop on e3, so after  10.Nc3  Rc8  11.Be3  O-O  we have a transposition to the line starting with 7. c4. }
7... Be7 { Black continues with the usual development. } 8. Bb2 O-O 9. c4 Rc8
{ The rook is very useful on the c-file as we have seen on more than one occasion. }
10. Nc3
{ This is more precise as the immediate   10.d4  can be met by  d5 !  and after  11.e5  Ne4  Black has a very good position thanks to the active knight. The exchanges of the pawns in the centre will increase the activity of Black's pieces. }
10... Re8
{ An important move ! While it follows the already-mentioned rule of thumb for the hedgehog to put the rook on the same file as the queen, it also allows Black to postpone the capture on d4. }
11. d4 Bf8
{ Another important move. Thanks to the rook on e8 Black can postpone the capture on d4 and make useful moves while at the same time not allowing White to establish a knight on d4. }
12. Rad1
{ The point is that pushing   12.d5  is not very good as after  exd5  13.cxd5  g6  Black has a very good version of the Benoni - the queen on e2 is out of place and White is not aggressively-enough positioned for the typical e5-push while Black is well-placed to start his usual queenside counterplay by ...a6 and ...b5. If White stops this by a4 then the idea of ...c4 is possible, after which b4 is not good in view of ...a5, obtaining the c5-square for the knight. This inability to resolve the central tension will lead White to lose a tempo with the queen and move it from the e-file and this is the point of Black's play.  Also note that   12.e5 ?  is met by  cxd4  when Black is a pawn up after  13.exf6  dxc3  14.Bxc3  Nxf6 }
12... Qa5
{ Black plays all the useful moves before taking on d4. With the queen on e2 White is reluctant to push d5, so he should remove the queen from the e-file. }
13. Qd2 cxd4 { Now finally Black takes on d4. } 14. Nxd4 a6
{ Eventually we ended up in a typical hedgehog position, but White was forced to lose a tempo by moving the queen. }
15. Rfe1
{ It is difficult to find a plan for White.  If he tries   15.f4  then Black can play  e5  16.Nf5  b5  obtaining excellent counterplay, since taking on d6 doesn't bring much to White after  17.Nxd6  Qb6+  18.Qf2  Qxf2+  19.Rxf2  Bxd6  20.Rxd6  bxc4  and the endgame is sharp but good for Black.  A move like   15.Kh1  can be met by  Qh5  and then if  16.f3  h6  when White doesn't have a constructive plan while Black is on the lookout for a counterplay based on ... b5 or ...d5 and also ideas like ...Qg5   h4  , ...Nh5-f4. }
15... Red8
{ Again putting the rook on the same file as the opponent's queen. The middlegame is complex and Black's mindset here should be one comprised of patience and based on search for counter-attack at the first opportunity. He is looking to push ...b5 or ...d5 if possible, and if these are not possible he should maneuver without making weaknesses and concessions.   Typical ideas are ...Qh5  (b4, c5)  , ...g6 and ...Bg7  (but careful with the d6-pawn)  , ...Nc5  (e5-g6)  in order to provoke a pawn movement. Sometimes with the knight on g6 Black can try ...h5-h4 in order to take control of the dark squares on the kingside, especially the f4-square. White's pieces are well-placed but he lacks an active plan against Black's well-entrenched position. Objectively the position is equal but Black should be happy about the outcome of the opening. }
