5. O-O Ngf6
{ Attacking the e4-pawn and asking White to determine his intentions. Speaking of White's plans, he has two main ones at his disposal:   1. To go for the hedgehog formation with c4 and d4, or   2. To play for a full centre with c3 and d4. Both these plans can be executed with a queen on e2 or a rook on e1, which means we have 4 possible set-ups for White.   Of the lesser plans the idea to play like in an open Sicilian by pushing d4 and after ... cxd4 taking Nxd4 and playing Nc3 is harmless as Black has quick development and easy queenside play in that case. }
6. Re1
{ Here we will explore both plans  (the hedgehog and going for c3 and d4)  with a rook on e1. }
6... e6
{ As usual, Black develops in the most natural way with ...e6, ...Be7 and .. .O-O. }
7. c4
{ The hedgehog with a rook on e1 is considered less optimal than with a queen on e2 because in the latter case the rook goes to d1, immediately to the open d-file. Still, sometimes White plays like this so it is worth knowing how to play, especially as here we will encounter a typical maneuver by Black. }
7... Be7
{ Black continues development and White establishes the central bind. } 8. Nc3
O-O 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Rc8
{ The c-file has been opened so Black attacks the c4-pawn immediately. } 11. b3
a6
{ The b5-square is very important in these structures - Black has to control it in order to prevent a possible Nb5 which would attack the d6-pawn and also to support his own ...b5 push. The immediate threat is to push ...b5 now as the knight on c3 is not protected. }
12. Bb2 { White protects the knight and prevents ...b5. } 12... Qa5
{ Another typical move. The queen is active on the fifth rank - it can go to h5 or g5, and it also supports the ...b5 push. }
13. Qd2 Bd8
{ An instructive maneuver ! The bishop is activated and goes to b6. What is important to know is that the d6-pawn is defended tactically. After }
14. Rad1 Bb6 15. Nde2 { The pawn doesn't really hang as after } 15... Rfd8
{ White cannot take it in view of } 16. Qxd6 Ng4
{ Or 16... Ne5 and then ...Nd3. } 17. Rf1 Bc7
{ With taking on h2 and ...Qh5 to come, with a winning position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Moscow Variation"]
[Black "The Moscow Variation 6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+
{ The Moscow Variation is practically as equally popular as the main lines of the open Sicilian. It conveniently allows White to avoid the forcing lines of the open Sicilians while at the same time giving him a playable middlegame position. }
3... Bd7
{ Of the three possible moves this one is the simplest. After the exchange of the bishops Black's position will be easier to play as the exchanges favour the side with less space. }
4. Bxd7+ { The main move. The alternatives are less ambitious. } 4... Nxd7
{ With this recapture Black aims for quick development after ...Ngf6, ... e6, ... Be7 and ...O-O. This move also allows for a quick ...Rc8, an important move for Black in the hedgehog structures that will often arise. The resulting hedgehog positions are comfortable for Black as with his quick and smooth development he can concentrate on the upcoming middlegame where his main plans are the ...b5 and ...d5 thrusts. In case these are not viable, he will maneuver with moves like ...Qa5  (-h5)  (or ...Qc7-b8, in order to support ...b5)  , ...Rfe8   d8  , ...Bf8  (or sometimes the maneuver ...Bd8-b6)  , ...Ne5  (-g6)  . There is always something to play for in the hedgehog so Black won't run out of ideas. Additionally, the resulting positions are calm and Black can rely on his positional understanding more than on exact memorisation, though there are a few lines where precise move-orders offer Black the best the position can offer. }
5. O-O Ngf6
{ Attacking the e4-pawn and asking White to determine his intentions. Speaking of White's plans, he has two main ones at his disposal:   1. To go for the hedgehog formation with c4 and d4, or   2. To play for a full centre with c3 and d4. Both these plans can be executed with a queen on e2 or a rook on e1, which means we have 4 possible set-ups for White.   Of the lesser plans the idea to play like in an open Sicilian by pushing d4 and after ... cxd4 taking Nxd4 and playing Nc3 is harmless as Black has quick development and easy queenside play in that case. }
6. Re1
{ Here we will explore both plans  (the hedgehog and going for c3 and d4)  with a rook on e1. }
6... e6
{ As usual, Black develops in the most natural way with . ..e6, ...Be7 and .. .O-O. }
7. c3 { White wants to establish a full centre by pushing d4. } 7... Be7
{ Black continues his normal development. } 8. d4 O-O
{ In these positions when White has the full centre Black can simply ignore it because he has smooth development and any pawn advance can easily be absorbed. If the pawns stay on d4 and e4 Black will create counterplay on the c-file by taking on d4 and playing ...Rc8. He can also consider the ...d5 push, which would force e5 by White  (allowing an IQP is not really an option for White - without the light-squared bishop he doesn't have enough dynamic potential to compensate for the IQP)  in which case the resulting French structure is in Black's favour as he has the better bishop. }
9. e5
{ This push puts immediate pressure, but the line shows how Black absorbs this pressure. }
9... Ne8 { In case of } 10. Qe2 cxd4 11. cxd4 dxe5 12. dxe5 Nc7 13. Nc3 Nb6
{ and ...Nd5. } *

