{ Black continues his normal development. } 8. d4 O-O
{ In these positions when White has the full centre Black can simply ignore it because he has smooth development and any pawn advance can easily be absorbed. If the pawns stay on d4 and e4 Black will create counterplay on the c-file by taking on d4 and playing ...Rc8. He can also consider the ...d5 push, which would force e5 by White  (allowing an IQP is not really an option for White - without the light-squared bishop he doesn't have enough dynamic potential to compensate for the IQP)  in which case the resulting French structure is in Black's favour as he has the better bishop. }
