{ This push puts immediate pressure, but the line shows how Black absorbs this pressure. }
9... Ne8 { The knight retreats, but it can easily arrive on d5 via c7. } 10.
exd6 { This resolves the tension in the centre. } 10... Bxd6
{ Both recaptures are possible, but with the e5-pawn gone the knight from e8 can return to f6. }
11. Na3 { White also needs to develop. } 11... cxd4
{ This capture wins the c5-square for the bishop in case it is attacked by }
12. Nc4 Bc5 13. Nxd4 Nef6
{ Black has an excellent position. He has no weaknesses and has smooth play with his pieces. He can further consider pushing ...a6 and ...b5, a typical Sicilian queenside play. In the long term he will want to expand in the centre and kingside where his pawn majority lies. }
