{ Attacking the e4-pawn and asking White to determine his intentions. Speaking of White's plans, he has two main ones at his disposal:   1. To go for the hedgehog formation with c4 and d4, or   2. To play for a full centre with c3 and d4. Both these plans can be executed with a queen on e2 or a rook on e1, which means we have 4 possible set-ups for White.   Of the lesser plans the idea to play like in an open Sicilian by pushing d4 and after ... cxd4 taking Nxd4 and playing Nc3 is harmless as Black has quick development and easy queenside play in that case. }
6. Qe2
{ The hedgehog plan with a queen on e2 is considered the most promising for White. }
6... e6 { The immediate } 7. d4 { is rather hasty because after } 7... cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Be7 9. c4 { Black has } 9... Qa5
{ preventing b3 and Bb2. This forces White to change to the alternative development of the bishop on e3, so after }
10. Nc3 Rc8 11. Be3 O-O
{ we have a transposition to the line starting with 7. c4. } *

