{ With this recapture Black aims for quick development after ...Ngf6, ... e6, ... Be7 and ...O-O. This move also allows for a quick ...Rc8, an important move for Black in the hedgehog structures that will often arise. The resulting hedgehog positions are comfortable for Black as with his quick and smooth development he can concentrate on the upcoming middlegame where his main plans are the ...b5 and ...d5 thrusts. In case these are not viable, he will maneuver with moves like ...Qa5  (-h5)  (or ...Qc7-b8, in order to support ...b5)  , ...Rfe8   d8  , ...Bf8  (or sometimes the maneuver ...Bd8-b6)  , ...Ne5  (-g6)  . There is always something to play for in the hedgehog so Black won't run out of ideas. Additionally, the resulting positions are calm and Black can rely on his positional understanding more than on exact memorisation, though there are a few lines where precise move-orders offer Black the best the position can offer. }
5. O-O Ngf6
{ Attacking the e4-pawn and asking White to determine his intentions. Speaking of White's plans, he has two main ones at his disposal:   1. To go for the hedgehog formation with c4 and d4, or   2. To play for a full centre with c3 and d4. Both these plans can be executed with a queen on e2 or a rook on e1, which means we have 4 possible set-ups for White.   Of the lesser plans the idea to play like in an open Sicilian by pushing d4 and after ... cxd4 taking Nxd4 and playing Nc3 is harmless as Black has quick development and easy queenside play in that case. }
