[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.Qxd4"]
[Black "4.Qxd4 Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ With this recapture White has two ideas, depending on Black's response - either to obtain a Maroczy bind by playing c4, or to obtain quick development by Nc3, Bg5 and O-O-O, aiming for a kingside attack. Obviously the drawback of the line is the exposed position of the queen, who often cannot find a comfortable spot, thus making White lose time. }
4... Nc6 { The most direct move, immediately attacking the queen. } 5. Bb5
{ This move is considered the main one, but the alternative is also decent and has gained some traction recently.   5.Qe3  With this move White aims for the Maroczy bind but without exchanging the light-squared bishop. His plan is to play c4, Nc3, Be2, O-O, Rd1, b3, Bb2 in various move-orders. Still, the queen on e3 is far from ideally placed in these structures and this gives Black good play.  Bg4  With this move Black will aim for a hedgehog position, but with the bishop actively placed on g4.  6.Be2  Nf6  Black develops normally and reaches the desired set-up without problems.  7.O-O  e6  8.Rd1  Be7  9.c4  Qc7  The threat was c5, so the queen is removed from the d-file.  10.Nc3  a6  The threat was Nb5, so the b5-square had to be controlled.  11.b3  O-O  Finishing development.  12.Bb2  If   12.Ba3  then  Rad8  safely defending the pawn. The other rook can go to e8, similarly as in the Moscow Variation placing the rook on the same file as the opponent's queen.  12...Ne5  A move that seeks an exchange of pieces. It is important to know that the exchange on e5 favours Black because after ...dxe5 he will obtain access to c5 for the bishop and eternal control over the weak d4-square that he can use for a light piece or a rook.  13.Rac1  Rac8  Black is in no need to resolve the tension in the centre. It is a general rule that if one side cannot resolve a tension  (in this case White)  then the other side should keep it as long as possible in order to pose practical problems - the opponent has to think on every move whether the tension will be resolved or not.  14.h3  White now forces Black to take on f3 as retreating with the bishop invites g4 and the bishop will be passive on g6.  Bxf3  15.Bxf3  Taking   15.gxf3  is double-edged. After  Ng6  (immediately going to the weakened f4-square)  16.f4  e5  17.f5  Nf4  Black has good counterplay thanks to the strong knight o f4. A constructive idea for Black in this position is ...Bd8-b6  (after moving the queen first)  in order to activate the bishop.  15...Nxf3+  Eliminating the bishop so as not to allow White to keep the bishop pair.  16.Qxf3  Rfd8  Black is without problems here and the position is equal. As in a usual hedgehog Black will seek the liberating moves ...b5 or ...d5. An interesting idea is the ... Ne8, ...Bf6 regrouping - the knight on e8 safely defends the pawn on d6 while the bishop on f6 opposes the one on b2 and also pins the knight, which makes the ...b5 push easier to achieve. }
5... a6
{ Again the most direct move. Black forces the exchange on c6, thus gaining the bishop pair and strengthening the centre. With the b-file open White's plan of queenside castling is out of the question, so what remains for White is the plan with the establishment of a Maroczy structure. }
6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. O-O
{ White can also start with 7. c4, which would lead to a transposition.  While the move   7.e5  an attempt to prevent Black's ...e5, is met by the strong move  f6 !  Take a look at the model game Ponomariov-Grischuk for the details how Black should play in this line. }
7... e5
{ With the compact pawn mass in the centre Black will comfortably develop behind it. }
8. Qd3 Qc7
{ It is more precise to start with the queen move in order to avoid the pin after 9. Bg5 which coupled with a quick Rd1 can lead to problems with the d6-pawn. }
9. c4
{ Going for the Maroczy structure is White's best strategical plan in this position.  It is important to know that the idea to attack the d6-pawn quickly by   9.Nbd2  is met by  Nf6  10.Nc4  Be6  11.Rd1  d5 !  and the complications after  12.exd5  e4  13.Qd4  cxd5  14.Nb6  Rd8  15.Qa4+  Nd7  16.Nxd5  Qb7  are favourable for Black. He wins material and is able to defend against White's initiative after  17.Bg5  Bxd5  18.Bxd8  exf3  as the important light-squared bishop can drop back to e6 to defend the king. }
9... Nf6 10. Nc3
{ White cannot capture the d6-pawn by going after it directly with   10.Bg5  Be7  11.Rd1  O-O  (now Black wants to play ...Rd8 next)  12.Bxf6  Bxf6  13.Qxd6 ?  as this loses to  Rd8  Also, the disruptive move   10.c5  is met by  d5 }
10... Be7 { Black continues with his development. } 11. b3
{ This move allows for possible development of the bishop to b2 or a3.  The alternative is to develop it on g5, though after   11.Bg5  O-O  12.Rfd1  Rd8  Black has a very solid position. Strategically he would like to exchange the dark-squared bishops and maneuver his knight to e6, from where it would target the weakened  (by the absence of White's dark-squared bishop)  squares f4, d4 and c5. How to achieve this is seen in the variation  13.Rac1  h6  14.Bh4  Bg4  (this development of the bishop is annoying for White as the queen is forced to defend the knight on f3)  15.b3  Nh7 !  and the knight will go to f8 and e6. }
11... O-O 12. h3
{ Since the development of the bishop on g4 is what Black would like to obtain, White is preventing it.  Allowing it by   12.Rd1  Bg4  is fine for Black, for example  13.h3  Bh5  14.Ba3  Rfd8  15.Qe3  Nd7  controlling the c5-square as the c5-push is White's main positional idea in this structure. Black may consider playing ...c5 himself, but this needs to be done carefully: first he must ensure that White has nothing from the weakening of the d5-square and second he must make sure that his knight is coming to d4  (in this case via b8 and c6)  . }
12... h6
{ Black also opens a luft for the king and prepares the development of the bishop on e6, thus not fearing Ng5. }
13. Rd1 Be6
{ Black is fully developed and is now ready for the middlegame. His main active idea is the ...f5 push and he can achieve this by either ...Nd7 or ...Nh5. }
14. Ba3
{ This puts more pressure on d6 but Black can easily defend the d6-pawn by putting a rook on d8.  The alternative   14.Be3  is met by  Nd7  (keeping control over the c5-square)  and then the pseudo-sacrifice  15.Nd5  leads to equality after  cxd5  16.cxd5  Bxd5  17.Qxd5  Nf6  18.Qd3  Qb7  As in the Najdorf, Black controls the d5-square and also attacks the e4-pawn, giving him good counterplay.  Black can use the other bishop development   14.Bb2  (which left the f4-square unattended)  by  Nh5  and after  15.Ne2  f5  he has excellent play. }
14... Rad8
{ Defending the pawn. The other rook stays on f8 in case the f-file is opened after ...f5. }
15. Qe3
{ The automatic   15.Rac1  is met by  15...Nh5  with the knight coming to f4 and ... f5 coming up. }
15... Qa5
{ An important move, chasing away the bishop from the a3-square and preventing the c5-push. }
16. Bb2 Nd7
{ Black has an excellent position - the c5 push has been prevented and he is ready for ...f5 to start his own activity on the kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.Qxd4"]
[Black "4.Qxd4 Variation 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ With this recapture White has two ideas, depending on Black's response - either to obtain a Maroczy bind by playing c4, or to obtain quick development by Nc3, Bg5 and O-O-O, aiming for a kingside attack. Obviously the drawback of the line is the exposed position of the queen, who often cannot find a comfortable spot, thus making White lose time. }
4... Nc6 { The most direct move, immediately attacking the queen. } 5. Qe3
{ With this move White aims for the Maroczy bind but without exchanging the light-squared bishop. His plan is to play c4, Nc3, Be2, O-O, Rd1, b3, Bb2 in various move-orders. Still, the queen on e3 is far from ideally placed in these structures and this gives Black good play. }
5... Bg4
{ With this move Black will aim for a hedgehog position, but with the bishop actively placed on g4. }
6. Be2 Nf6
{ Black develops normally and reaches the desired set-up without problems. } 7.
O-O e6 8. Rd1 Be7 9. c4 Qc7
{ The threat was c5, so the queen is removed from the d-file. } 10. Nc3 a6
{ The threat was Nb5, so the b5-square had to be controlled. } 11. b3 O-O
{ If } 12. Ba3 Rad8
{ then safely defending the pawn. The other rook can go to e8, similarly as in the Moscow Variation placing the rook on the same file as the opponent's queen. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.Qxd4"]
[Black "4.Qxd4 Variation 2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ With this recapture White has two ideas, depending on Black's response - either to obtain a Maroczy bind by playing c4, or to obtain quick development by Nc3, Bg5 and O-O-O, aiming for a kingside attack. Obviously the drawback of the line is the exposed position of the queen, who often cannot find a comfortable spot, thus making White lose time. }
4... Nc6 { The most direct move, immediately attacking the queen. } 5. Qe3
{ With this move White aims for the Maroczy bind but without exchanging the light-squared bishop. His plan is to play c4, Nc3, Be2, O-O, Rd1, b3, Bb2 in various move-orders. Still, the queen on e3 is far from ideally placed in these structures and this gives Black good play. }
5... Bg4
{ With this move Black will aim for a hedgehog position, but with the bishop actively placed on g4. }
6. Be2 Nf6
{ Black develops normally and reaches the desired set-up without problems. } 7.
O-O e6 8. Rd1 Be7 9. c4 Qc7
{ The threat was c5, so the queen is removed from the d-file. } 10. Nc3 a6
{ The threat was Nb5, so the b5-square had to be controlled. } 11. b3 O-O
{ Finishing development. } 12. Bb2 Ne5
{ A move that seeks an exchange of pieces. It is important to know that the exchange on e5 favours Black because after ...dxe5 he will obtain access to c5 for the bishop and eternal control over the weak d4-square that he can use for a light piece or a rook. }
13. Rac1 Rac8
{ Black is in no need to resolve the tension in the centre. It is a general rule that if one side cannot resolve a tension  (in this case White)  then the other side should keep it as long as possible in order to pose practical problems - the opponent has to think on every move whether the tension will be resolved or not. }
14. h3
{ White now forces Black to take on f3 as retreating with the bishop invites g4 and the bishop will be passive on g6. }
14... Bxf3 { Taking } 15. gxf3 { is double-edged. After } 15... Ng6
{ immediately going to the weakened f4-square } 16. f4 e5 17. f5 Nf4
{ Black has good counterplay thanks to the strong knight o f4. A constructive idea for Black in this position is ...Bd8-b6  (after moving the queen first)  in order to activate the bishop. }
*

