[Black "4.Qxd4 Variation 3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ With this recapture White has two ideas, depending on Black's response - either to obtain a Maroczy bind by playing c4, or to obtain quick development by Nc3, Bg5 and O-O-O, aiming for a kingside attack. Obviously the drawback of the line is the exposed position of the queen, who often cannot find a comfortable spot, thus making White lose time. }
4... Nc6 { The most direct move, immediately attacking the queen. } 5. Qe3
{ With this move White aims for the Maroczy bind but without exchanging the light-squared bishop. His plan is to play c4, Nc3, Be2, O-O, Rd1, b3, Bb2 in various move-orders. Still, the queen on e3 is far from ideally placed in these structures and this gives Black good play. }
5... Bg4
{ With this move Black will aim for a hedgehog position, but with the bishop actively placed on g4. }
6. Be2 Nf6
{ Black develops normally and reaches the desired set-up without problems. } 7.
O-O e6 8. Rd1 Be7 9. c4 Qc7
{ The threat was c5, so the queen is removed from the d-file. } 10. Nc3 a6
{ The threat was Nb5, so the b5-square had to be controlled. } 11. b3 O-O
{ Finishing development. } 12. Bb2 Ne5
{ A move that seeks an exchange of pieces. It is important to know that the exchange on e5 favours Black because after ...dxe5 he will obtain access to c5 for the bishop and eternal control over the weak d4-square that he can use for a light piece or a rook. }
13. Rac1 Rac8
{ Black is in no need to resolve the tension in the centre. It is a general rule that if one side cannot resolve a tension  (in this case White)  then the other side should keep it as long as possible in order to pose practical problems - the opponent has to think on every move whether the tension will be resolved or not. }
14. h3
{ White now forces Black to take on f3 as retreating with the bishop invites g4 and the bishop will be passive on g6. }
14... Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Nxf3+
{ Eliminating the bishop so as not to allow White to keep the bishop pair. }
16. Qxf3 Rfd8
{ Black is without problems here and the position is equal. As in a usual hedgehog Black will seek the liberating moves ...b5 or ...d5. An interesting idea is the ...Ne8, ...Bf6 regrouping - the knight on e8 safely defends the pawn on d6 while the bishop on f6 opposes the one on b2 and also pins the knight, which makes the ...b5 push easier to achieve. }
