[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ With this recapture White has two ideas, depending on Black's response - either to obtain a Maroczy bind by playing c4, or to obtain quick development by Nc3, Bg5 and O-O-O, aiming for a kingside attack. Obviously the drawback of the line is the exposed position of the queen, who often cannot find a comfortable spot, thus making White lose time. }
4... Nc6 { The most direct move, immediately attacking the queen. } 5. Bb5
{ This move is considered the main one, but the alternative is also decent and has gained some traction recently. }
5... a6
{ Again the most direct move. Black forces the exchange on c6, thus gaining the bishop pair and strengthening the centre. With the b-file open White's plan of queenside castling is out of the question, so what remains for White is the plan with the establishment of a Maroczy structure. }
6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. O-O
{ White can also start with 7. c4, which would lead to a transposition. } 7...
e5
{ With the compact pawn mass in the centre Black will comfortably develop behind it. }
8. Qd3 Qc7
{ It is important to know that the idea to attack the d6-pawn quickly by } 9.
Nbd2 { is met by } 9... Nf6 10. Nc4 Be6 11. Rd1 d5
{ and the complications after } 12. exd5 e4 13. Qd4 cxd5 14. Nb6 Rd8 15. Qa4+
Nd7 16. Nxd5 Qb7
{ are favourable for Black. He wins material and is able to defend against White's initiative after }
17. Bg5 Bxd5 18. Bxd8 exf3
{ as the important light-squared bishop can drop back to e6 to defend the king. }
