[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. f3
{ The idea of this move is to allow for the move c4 before putting the knight on c3, thus establishing a Maroczy bind. Black doesn't need to allow this and can quickly liberate his play by pushing ...d5.  The move   5.Bd3  is a harmless one, as Black can play  Nc6  immediately attacking the knight on d4. Then he can decide whether he would play ...g6 or ...e6 in order to complete his development as both options are good. }
5... e5 { The typical Najdorf move here is a preparation for ...d5. } 6. Nb3
{ Lately White's attempts were connected with this move.   6.Bb5+  This check was considered the main move many years ago, but Black can easily equalise.  Bd7  This is the simplest, by exchanging the bishops Black speeds up his development and uses this development advantage to push ...d5 and later recuperate the pawn on d5.  7.Bxd7+  Nbxd7  8.Nf5  If   8.Nb3  then after  Nb6  Black still pushes ...d5 on the next move.  8...d5  This is a temporary pawn sacrifice that liberates Black's play.  9.exd5  Nb6  Thanks to his lead in development Black will return the material.  10.Bg5  The move   10.d6  shouldn't worry Black as after  Qd7  the knight cannot stay on f5 for long and the d6-pawn will fall.  10...Qd7  Removing the queen from the pin and attacking the knight.  11.Bxf6  Qxf5  Winning tempo against the bishop and also eyeing c2.  12.Bh4  Rc8  With every move Black increases his initiative.  13.Nc3  After   13.c3  Bc5  White's king will find it difficult to find a safe haven while Black can continue with ...O-O and then there are ideas like ... Qg6, ...f5 and ...e4, aiming for a direct attack.  13...Bb4  Now Black returns the pawn and obtains excellent play  14.O-O  Bxc3  15.bxc3  Rxc3  With great play for Black who will castle next and will continue with a better pawn structure. }
6... d5 { Immediately liberating the position and not allowing c4. } 7. Bg5 Be6
{ Defending the centre. } 8. Bxf6 gxf6 9. exd5 Qxd5
{ With the pair of bishops Black is fine in the endgame. } 10. Qxd5 Bxd5 11.
Nc3 Be6
{ Black has the pair of bishops while White has the better structure and a slight lead in development. With some precise play Black can neutralise White's trumps. }
12. O-O-O
{ After   12.Nb5  Na6  13.O-O-O  Bh6+  14.Kb1  Ke7  Black is quite alright as he's ready to start active play by ...Nb4. }
12... Nc6
{ Developing normally and limiting the knight on b3 since its movement would allow ...Nd4. }
13. Bb5
{ White continues to develop too. The alternative   13.Ne4  is rather harmless in view of  Bh6+  14.Kb1  Ke7  and Black is fine. }
13... Rc8
{ Defending the knight against Na5 ideas and allowing for ...Rc7 in some lines in order to defend b7. }
14. Nd5
{ The alternative is   14.Ne4  but after the already familiar reaction  Bh6+  15.Kb1  Ke7  Black is fine as  16.Nec5  Rc7  defends everything. }
14... f5
{ The pawn was attacked so Black pushes it forward to activate his central majority. White's position may look very active, but Black is solid. He wants to give the check from h6 and play ...Kf8, thus untangling. White is actually hard-pressed to find something concrete before Black untangles and starts playing for a win with his pair of bishop and mobile central majority. }
15. Na5
{ Putting more pressure on Black's queenside, but it amounts to nothing.  The alternative   15.Rhe1  is met with the same  Bh6+  16.Kb1  Kf8  and Black has nothing to fear as he wants to play ...Kg7 connecting the rooks. }
15... Bh6+ 16. Kb1 Kf8 { The typical reaction to get the king out of the pin. }
17. Bxc6
{ If White goes back with   17.Nb3  then after  Kg7  Black slowly starts to take over, as shown in the model game Harikrishna-Giri. }
17... bxc6 18. Nb4 c5
{ The knights are not very stable and this move accentuates it. } 19. Nbc6 e4
{ With very sharp endgame where Black can look confidently ahead with the passed e-pawn and the pair of bishops. Note that the pawn on a7 is poisoned as after }
20. Nxa7 Ra8 21. N7c6 Rg8 { White's kingside crumbles. } *

