[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Larsen, Bent vs. Fischer, Robert"]
[Result "*"]

1. f4
{ Even though the game starts as the Bird's Opening, soon enough it transposes to a Sicilian. }
1... c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. e4
{ Here we are, a direct transposition to the variation arising after 1.e4 c5 2.f4 g6 3.Nf3. }
3... Bg7 4. Be2 Nc6 5. O-O d6 6. d3 e6
{ Fischer develops in the same way as suggested in the theoretical part. } 7.
Na3
{ Larsen determines the position of the knight early. In the theoretical part we examine Be3 first and then c3 followed by Nbd2. In this game we can explore how the game develops with the knight being developed on a3. }
7... Nge7 8. c3 O-O 9. Be3 a6
{ Fischer prefers to start queenside play.  The immediate   9...f5  was also possible. }
10. d4 cxd4
{ Fischer tries to transpose to an open Sicilian structure.  The immediate   10...f5  was possible, fighting for the light squares in the centre. }
11. Nxd4
{ After   11.cxd4  Black had two options at his disposal:  11...f5  to fight for the light-squares in the centre.  and   11...b5  to expand on the queenside. Both give Black satisfactory play. The latter line shows that Black can try to ignore White's centre and play on the queenside, similar to some lines in the Rossolimo. For all these reasons Larsen takes with the knight, but this Sicilian structure favours Black as White's knight on a3 is out of place. }
11... b5 { Black starts the usual queenside counterplay. } 12. Nxc6 Nxc6 13.
Qd2 { White opened the d-file and intends to put pressure on the d6-pawn. }
13... Qc7 { Fischer intends to defend the d6-pawn with the rook. } 14. Rad1 Rd8
15. Nc2
{ The knight comes back into play. The position is balanced, Black safely covers the d6-pawn and is active on the queenside while White will try to attack on the kingside. }
15... Rb8
{ Fischer is careful and keeps the bishop on c8, lending extra cover to the f5-square, thus discouraging f5. }
16. a3
{ White prevents ... b4 practically forever, but this weakens the light squares on the queenside. With his next move Fischer immediately takes advantage of that.  It was possible to avoid this and play   16.Bf2  with the idea of playing Bh4 and Ne3. }
16... Na5 17. e5
{ Larsen goes forward. This was the last game of the famous match that Fischer won 6-0 and this was Larsen's last attempt to score a win. But, unfortunately for him, Fischer was much better in the complications that Larsen himself kept instigating.  It was better to play   17.f5  as after  exf5  18.exf5  Bxf5  19.Nb4  White has compensation for the pawn. }
17... Bf8
{ Defending the pawn. White seems overstretched as his pieces cannot support the advanced pawn. }
18. b4
{ Continuing to go forward. White sacrifices a pawn in order to activate his pieces. }
18... Nc6 19. Nd4 dxe5 20. fxe5 Nxe5 21. Bg5 Rd5
{ The rook is active on the fifth rank, keeping an eye on the bishop on g5. }
22. Qf4 Bg7 23. h4
{ This looks slow, but White didn't have direct threats anyway. } 23... Rb7
{ It was possible to take on c3 immediately, but Fischer prefers to defend f7 one more time. This still keeps the advantage. }
24. Bf6 Bxf6 25. Qxf6 Qxc3
{ But now this is out of place!  Black should have brought the queen to the defence of the dark squares by   25...Qe7  and after  26.Qf4  The endgame is hopeless for White.  Rc7  White has no compensation for the pawn. }
26. h5
{ Now White has enough counterplay for a draw. But remember that a draw meant a loss of the match for Larsen. }
26... gxh5
{ Looks insane, but it's an instructive defensive idea based on activity - Black wants to put a knight either on g6 or g4 and the rook on d5 would control the fifth rank once the knight moves. }
27. Kh1
{ Threatening Nf5  (which wasn't possible in view of ... Nf3+, winning the queen)  . }
27... Ng4 { The only move. } 28. Bxg4 hxg4 29. Qh6
{ Preventing ...Rh5 and threatening Rc1. } 29... Bd7
{ Finally developing the bishop. } 30. Rf4
{ This allows White to force a draw by   30.Rxf7  but as we said, a draw in this game meant the match would be over, so Larsen tries his last chance to score a win and keep the match going. }
30... f5 31. Qf6
{ The final mistake.  He could still have drawn by   31.Qg5+  with a likely repetition after  Kf7  32.Qh6  Kg8  33.Qg5+ }
31... Bc8
{ The bishop undevelops and returns to its original square, but it's a winning move as it allows the b7-rook to cover the king. }
32. Rff1 { Threatening Rc1, but now Black is faster. } 32... Rf7 33. Qh6 Bb7
{ The bishop finally develops to the usual Sicilian diagonal, this time with devastating effect. }
34. Nxe6 Qf6
{ The queen returns to cover everything in the vicinity of the king. } 35. Qe3
Re7
{ This forces further simplifications which at the end lead to the trapping of the hapless knight that started its path in this game with the move Nb1-a3. }
36. Rde1 Rd6 37. Qg5+ Qxg5 38. Nxg5 Rxe1 39. Rxe1 Bd5 40. Re8+ Kg7 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Karjakin, Sergey vs. Carlsen, Magnus"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Bc4 Be7 5. d3 d6 6. Nd2 Nf6 7. Nf1 Nd7 8. a3
{ With this move Karjakin tries to preserve the light-squared bishop, but it allows Black time to quickly finish development.  In the theoretical part we examine the more direct move   8.Ne3 }
8... Nb6 9. Ba2 O-O 10. Ne3 Be6
{ Black finished the development. With his last move he controls d5 and would like to play ...Bg5 next, aiming to exchange his passive dark-squared bishop. }
11. Ncd5 Bg5 12. O-O Bxe3
{ An important moment - this exchange of the bishop for a knight is fine for Black in these structures as he gets rid of the only passive piece he has. The remaining pieces are all well-placed and he is looking to start kingside activity by playing ...f5. }
13. fxe3
{ With this move White takes control over the d4 and f4-squares, but he renders his own dark-squared bishop passive. }
13... Ne7 { Attacking the knight on d5. } 14. c4
{ Now White's other bishop is also passive.  Retreating the knight was possible, but Black would have been fine after   14.Nc3  Bxa2  15.Nxa2  f5  with easy play. }
14... f5
{ With the centre closed Black starts his kingside counterplay. White will try to achieve something on the queenside. }
15. Bd2 Bxd5
{ A curious and instructive decision. There was no need for this exchange  (and the engine doesn't like it)  , but from a human perspective it makes sense to leave the knights to play against the bishops in a closed position. }
16. exd5 Nd7
{ Black's play is simple - he will bring the knights to the kingside and will try to create an attack there. For White to achieve something on the queenside is not easy as there is nothing to attack there. }
17. b4 b6 18. Bb3
{ The bishop is activated via a4, but even getting to c6 leaves it completely cut off from the kingside. }
18... Ng6 19. Ba4 Qe7 20. Bc6
{ The engine suggests the instructive   20.Qh5  It is a common defensive strategy to put the queen on the flank where your opponent is attacking as the queen hinders the movement of the opponent's pieces thus slowing down  (or often even stopping completely)  the attack. Here it is also a very concrete move as the pawn on f5 is attacked and it's not easy to defend it. }
20... Rad8 21. Qa4
{ Karjakin had other ideas for the queen. This move shows that he doesn't believe in Black's attack and leaves the kingside without defence. As the game shows, this was a serious mis-evaluation. }
21... Nf6
{ Now Black's attack develops on its own. The threats are ...e4 and ...Ng4. }
22. bxc5 bxc5 23. Rxf5
{ This opens the f-file that Black can use, but at least it takes a pawn... }
23... e4 { One of the good moves.  The others were   23...Nh4  and   23...Ng4 }
24. Qc2
{ The queen returns but it's too late. She shouldn't have gone in the first place. }
24... Ng4 25. Raf1 Rxf5 26. Rxf5 Qh4
{ The attack flow naturally, Black's only difficulty consists of choosing from the many tempting options. }
27. h3 Nxe3 28. Bxe3 Qe1+ 29. Kh2 Qxe3 30. dxe4 Nf4
{ Carlsen had stronger options on the previous moves, but even here Black's pieces dominate. Just take a look at the stranded bishop on c6. }
31. Qb2
{ The final mistake.  It was more resilient to play   31.Qd1  with the idea of Qg4. Black is still on top after  Ne2  but at least White is not losing immediately. }
31... Qxe4 { Now it's over. Perhaps Karjakin was banking on } 32. Bd7
{ Finally using the bishop, but after } 32... g6 33. Rf6 Nd3
{ He is losing material - the queen cannot stay on b2, the only square that prevents ...Qe5 and threatens Qb8 when Black takes the bishop. }
34. Qc3 Rxd7 35. Re6 Qf4+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Svidler, Peter vs. Carlsen, Magnus"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Bc4 Be7 5. d3 d6 6. Nd2 Nf6 7. Nf1 Nd7 8. Nd5
{ Svidler deviates from the move   8.Ne3  that we examined in the theoretical part and immediately puts a knight on d5. }
8... Nb6 { Black continues with his plan. } 9. Nxb6 axb6
{ This move opens the a-file and also keeps the queen on d8 from where she can help the move ...Bg5. }
10. c3
{ For now White managed to keep control over the d5 and b5-squares and with his last move he limits the movement of the knight on c6. }
10... O-O { Black finishes development. } 11. Ne3 Bg5
{ Now Carlsen plays the typical move in these structures, activating his only passive piece. }
12. O-O Kh8
{ A characteristic moment.  Carlsen undoubtedly knew the game Leko-Kramnik from Dortmund 2003 where Black took on e3 and equalised:   12...Bxe3  13.Bxe3  Qe7  followed by ...Be6 gave Black a relatively easy draw. With his move he is in fact showing more aggressive intentions, aiming to push ...f5 and to play for more than just equality. }
13. a3 { A rather vague move, not interfering with Black's plans. } 13... f5
{ This is Carlsen's idea. He is temporarily sacrificing the f-pawn in order to remove the e4-pawn and achieve a full centre. }
14. Nxf5 Bxc1 15. Rxc1 Bxf5 16. exf5 d5
{ This is the important intermediate move ! } 17. Ba2 Rxf5
{ It appears that Black has everything he wanted, but in fact White can start attacking the centre. }
18. Qg4 Rf6 19. f4
{ This was Svidler's idea, but he missed  (or, rather, mis-evaluated)  Black's 20th move.  It was better to play   19.Rce1  with a solid position. }
19... exf4 20. Qg5
{ White cannot take on f4 in view of   20.Rxf4  Ne5  and the pawn on d3 drops. }
20... Qf8
{ A very strong move. Black keeps the advanced f4-pawn and gives away the useless d5-pawn. It may appear that with the disappearance of the d5-pawn White's bishop will become active, but in fact the bishop will have an empty diagonal to look down on while Black can prepare the kingside assault at his leisure. }
21. Qxd5 Rd8 22. Qf3
{ Defending the pawn on d3, but allowing the knight to enter the game with tempo.  It was more resilient to prevent ...Ne5 by playing   22.Qg5  but Black is better anyway after  Rxd3 }
22... Ne5 23. Qe4 Ng4
{ Of course, not   23...Nxd3 ?  24.Rcd1  which lets White activate his pieces. }
24. Rce1 Ne3
{ With the monster knight on e3 it is only a matter of time before Black delivers the final blow on the kingside. }
25. Rf2 Re8 26. Qxb7 g5
{ The b7-pawn is irrelevant, as is the beautiful bishop on a2. The pawns start rolling and the end is nigh. }
27. Rfe2 g4 28. Rf2 Qh6 29. Qc7 Ref8 30. h3
{ As is his wont, Svidler performs hara-kiri. } 30... gxh3 31. g3 fxg3 32. Rxf6
h2+ 33. Kh1 g2# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Nguyen Ngoc Truong Son vs. Anton Guijarro, David"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 7. O-O e6
{ In the theoretical part we examined   7...Rc8  but of course there is nothing wrong with 7... e6, especially as later Black could have played ...Rc8 with a transposition to the lines we examine. }
8. d4 cxd4 9. Qxd4
{ White could recapture with the knight as after   9.Nxd4  Rc8  he can play  10.Qe2  After  Qa5  (preventing b3 and Bb2)  11.Be3  Be7  we have a transposition to the lines we examined via the move-order 4. Bxd7+ Nxd7 5. O-O Ngf6 6. Qe2 e6 7. c4. }
9... Be7 10. b3 Qa5
{ With this move he introduces a very interesting, aggressive and unexpected concept of kingside attack.  Black could have played   10...Rc8  which is what we examine in the theoretical part. }
11. Bd2 Qh5
{ We have seen instances of this maneuver in the theoretical part, but here Black uses the fact that he hasn't castled yet to start aggressive kingside expansion. }
12. Qd3 Rg8
{ This is the idea ! The idea to push ...g5 in the hedgehog structure isn't new. It was first introduced by Fischer in the game Garcia Soruco-Fischer from the Havana Olympiad in 1966  (though there White didn't have a pawn on c4)  and then played it once again very successfully with White in a reversed Sicilian position  (where again Black didn't have a pawn on c5 so it wasn't a proper Maroczy structure)  against Ulf Andersson in an exhibition game played after the Siegen Olympiad in 1970.  Black could have played   12...O-O  with a normal position, but he wants to spice things up ! }
13. Bf4
{ White panics. He transfers the bishop to g3 in order to defend the kingside but the bishop only serves as a target there. He could have waited first for the g-pawn to come to g4 before putting a bishop on f4, from where it cannot easily be dislodged. }
13... g5 14. Bg3 g4 15. Nd4 Qg5
{ Now the threat is .. .Nh5, attacking the bishop. } 16. Rad1
{ The move   16.f4  doesn't help White as after  gxf3  17.Nxf3  Qg4  the bishop is pinned on the g-file and will be attacked by ...Nh5 next. }
16... Nh5
{ Unfortunately Black doesn't have time for ...h5-h4 in view of   16...h5  17.f4 !  as here Black is too slow to attack the bishop after  gxf3  18.Nxf3  Qg4  19.Qc2  with the threat of Bd6. }
17. e5
{ A desperate attempt to change the course of the game. Otherwise Black's attack is rolling after ...Nxg3, ... h5-h4. A triumph of Black's daring opening experiment and an idea that is well-worth remembering. }
17... Nxg3 18. hxg3 Nxe5 19. Qxh7 O-O-O
{ This is the reason Black kept the rook on a8, so that he can castle queenside whenever needed ! Black has a dominating position with a clear advantage. Unfortunately he didn't manage to convert it. }
20. Ne4 Qg6 21. Qxg6 Rxg6 22. Rfe1 Rh6 23. Kf1 Kc7
{ This is fine, but   23...d5 !  was stronger, with the idea of ...Bb4, disrupting White's rooks. }
24. Ke2 Rdh8 25. Nc3 Nc6 26. Nc2 f5 27. Ne3 Bf6 28. Rc1 Kd7 29. Red1 Bd4 30.
Ncd5 { Another desperate attempt by White in this game, but this one worked ! }
30... exd5
{ It was better to leave the knight with   30...Bb2  31.Rb1  Bg7  keeping all the advantages of Black's position. }
31. cxd5 Bxe3 32. dxc6+ bxc6 33. Kxe3
{ Reaching a rook endgame while at the same time destroying Black's central mass is a huge achievement for White ! He held the draw without problems. }
33... Re6+ 34. Kd3 Rhe8 35. Rh1 c5 36. Rh7+ Kc6 37. Ra7 Kb6 38. Rd7 Kc6 39. Ra7
Kb6 40. Rd7 a5 41. Rd1 Kc6 42. Ra7 Kb6 43. Rd7 Kc6 44. Ra7 Kb6 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
