[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Ponomariov, Ruslan vs. Grischuk, Alexander"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Bb5 a6 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. e5
{ This is a direct attempt to prevent Black from playing ...e5, but after Black's next strong retort it is White who needs to be careful not to be worse ! }
7... f6 { Black will achieve the ...e5 push after all ! } 8. exd6
{ Taking on f6 is worse, after   8.exf6  Nxf6  Black develops smoothly and has the central mass going after ...e5. }
8... e5 { Black expands in the centre before taking the pawn on d6. } 9. Qa4
Qxd6
{ Taking with the queen creates the threat of ... Qb4. An exchange of queens is hugely in Black's favour, with his central pawns and the bishop pair he would be better. }
10. O-O Ne7
{ Black defends the c6-pawn. The fight here is whether Black can consolidate and develop, when he would have an advantage because of the bishop pair and strong centre, or White can create enough threats to prevent that development. }
11. Nc3 a5
{ Again threatening ... Qb4. This idea is very important for Black in this line. }
12. Nd2
{ White could prevent ...Qb4 by   12.a3  but then the knight would come to the centre by  Nd5  with good play for Black. }
12... Qb4 13. Nde4 Bf5
{ With the exchange of queens guaranteed only Black can try to be better now. }
14. Rd1 Bxe4 15. Qxb4 axb4 16. Nxe4 Nd5 17. c4 bxc3
{ Draw was agreed here because it was a team match. While the rook endgame arising after }
18. Nxc3 Nxc3 19. bxc3 Ba3 20. Bxa3 Rxa3
{ should be a draw, it is Black who is trying for more in view of the weak pawns on a2 and c3. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Harikrishna, Pentala vs. Giri, Anish"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. f3 e5 6. Nb3 d5 7. Bg5 Be6 8. Bxf6
gxf6 9. exd5 Qxd5 10. Qxd5 Bxd5 11. Nc3 Be6 12. O-O-O Nc6 13. Bb5 Rc8 14. Nd5
f5 15. Na5 Bh6+
{ The typical way to escape from the pin was also present in some other lines that we examined in the theoretical part. }
16. Kb1 Kf8 17. Nb3
{ In the theoretical part we discuss   17.Bxc6  but that also gives Black good play. With the retreat of the knight White acknowledges that his initiative has come to a stop and now tries to limit the damage. }
17... Kg7 { Connecting the rooks. } 18. Rhe1 Rhd8 19. Nc3
{ Forcing exchanges down the d-file as the move   19.c4  would weaken the d4-square forever. }
19... Rxd1+ 20. Nxd1 Kf6
{ With the exchange of one pair of rooks the Black king can move more easily . The game is an excellent illustration of a good endgame technique. }
21. Bxc6
{ This is far from desired, but it is probably the lesser evil as the bishop didn't have a good square to go to. }
21... Rxc6 22. Nf2 Rc4 23. Re2
{ A good move, preventing in view of   23.Nd3  in view of  e4 } 23... b6
{ Limiting the knight on b6. Just like in the classical games, these positions are won by limiting the movement of the knights and play on domination on the whole board. }
24. Nc1 Bf8 { The bishop goes to d6 to defend the e5-pawn. } 25. Ncd3 Bd6 26.
b3 Rc8
{ The rook is transferred on the g-file, which coupled with the movement of the h-pawn will create weaknesses in White's kingside structure. }
27. g4
{ White doesn't want to wait so he moves the g-pawn before it is attacked. }
27... Bd5
{ But the movement of the g-pawn left the f3-pawn weak, which Black immediately attacks. }
28. Ne1 Bb4 29. gxf5 Kxf5 30. Ng2
{ Indirectly defending the f3-pawn in view of Nh4. } 30... Ba8
{ Getting away as far as possible, since the threat was Ne3. } 31. c4 f6
{ Black is in no hurry, he strengthens his position to the maximum. He can take time to move the king and start pushing the central pawns. }
32. Ne4 Ke6 33. Ne3 f5
{ The knights placed themselves in front of the pawns, inviting the advance. }
34. Ng5+ Kf6 35. Rg2 { Taking on h7 would lose the knight after ...Kg6. } 35...
Rc7
{ Defending the pawn on h7. White cannot hold his position anymore as he is overstretched - the pawn on f3 and the knight on g5 both need protection. }
36. Nc2 Bc5 37. b4
{ This only leads to more weakening, this time of the c4-pawn. } 37... Bf8 38.
Nh3 Bxf3 { Black won the weak pawn and the rest is trivial for Giri. } 39. Rg8
Bh6 40. c5 { A desperate attempt that leads to nothing. } 40... bxc5 41. b5 Rb7
42. a4 a6 43. Rc8 axb5 44. a5 Ra7 45. Rxc5 Rxa5
{ White is 3  (!)  pawns down and could have resigned here. } 46. Nf2 Bf8 47.
Rc7 Be7 48. Ne3 f4 49. Neg4+ Bxg4 50. Nxg4+ Ke6 51. Nf2
{ If   51.Nxe5  then  Bd6 } 51... Ra4 52. Rb7 Rb4+ 53. Kc2 f3 54. Nd3 Rc4+ 55.
Kd1 Rd4 56. Kc2 b4
{ This game is a highly instructive illustration how Black can win the endgames arising from the 5. f3 line. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Turovsky, Stephan vs. Dvoretzky, Mark"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The game starts as a French Defence, but soon enough it transposes to a Closed Sicilian structure. }
2. Qe2 c5 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O d6 7. Nc3 Nge7 8. d3 O-O 9. Be3
Rb8
{ Black developed in the optimal way. The plan is straight-forward: ...b5-b4. White's play in this game is not very good, but this game serves as an illustration of the best-case scenario for Black, what to strive for and how ideally things should work out.. }
10. Qd2 Re8
{ An instructive moment. The young Dvoretsky avoids the exchange of bishops with Bh6, but allows d4. The latter threat is much more important.  It was better to prevent d4 by   10...Nd4  and after  11.Bh6  to play the typical  e5 !  This repositioning of the pawns on dark squares after the exchange of the dark-squared bishop is an important positional theme in the Closed Sicilian. With the black pawns on dark squares and the white pawns on light squares Black will have the better light-squared bishop, not limited by its own pawns. The bishop will be developed on e6  (most likely with the support of ...f6, to cover the g5-square and defend against a possible f4-f5, which can then be met by the calm ...Bf7)  and Black will continue with the queenside expansion. }
11. Nd1
{ White plays in a typical Closed Sicilian manner, preparing c3, but the transposition to an open Sicilian structure by   11.d4 !  was preferable. The problem for Black then would be the d6-pawn, which lacks easy protection with the bishop being on g7 and not on e7. }
11... b5
{ Now Black's queenside play gets rolling. With the knight on b1 the d4-push is less effective, so White continues in a typical Closed Sicilian fashion - he plays c3 to control d4, to limit the bishop on g7 and prepare d4 so that he can recapture with a pawn. However, Black's play on the queenside is much faster. }
12. c3 b4
{ Black already established contact on the queenside. Soon his ideal set-up appears on the board. }
13. d4 bxc3 14. bxc3 Ba6
{ This is the best square for the bishop from where it is the most active. }
15. Re1 cxd4 16. cxd4 Qa5
{ And this is the best square for the queen, exerting maximim pressure on the queenside. Note how Black successfully circumvents White's pawn centre to create play on the queenside. We have seen this circumvention in several lines of the Rossolimo. }
17. Nc3
{ After the exchange of the queens after   17.Qxa5  Nxa5  the black knight will land on c4. }
17... Rec8 { The rook was useless on e8, so it takes the open c-file. } 18.
Rec1 Qa3
{ Grabbing more queenside space, taking control of the b2-square and liberating the a5-square for the ...Na5-c4 maneuver. }
19. Rab1 Na5 { Black is consistently increasing his queenside pressure. } 20.
Rxb8 Rxb8 21. Rb1
{ After Black's next move the knight on c3 is left without proper protection and Black still wants to play ...Nc4.  It was better to get rid of the queen by   21.Nb1 }
21... Rc8 22. Nd1
{ Going to b5 was better, though after   22.Nb5  Bxb5  23.Rxb5  Nc4  Black is clearly better. }
22... Nc4 { The move   22...Bd3  was winning faster, as the pawn on e4 falls. }
23. Qb4 Qxa2
{ Triumph of Black's queenside strategy. White's centre is still intact, but entirely useless. }
24. Nc3 Qa3 25. Bc1 Qxb4 26. Rxb4 Nb6 27. Bd2 Nc6
{ The rest is a matter of technique and White resigned. A game that illustrates an ideal scenario for Black in the Closed Sicilian. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Bronstein, David vs. Dvoretsky, Mark"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 e6 6. Be3 d6 7. f4 Nge7 8. Nf3
Nd4
{ Dvoretsky learned his lesson from the game with Turovsky and now prevents d4. }
9. O-O O-O 10. g4
{ In the theoretical part we looked at the most direct move 10 e5 and we also mentioned several others. With this move White openly states is intention to start kingside operations, but after Black's typical reaction these immediately come to a halt. }
10... f5
{ The typical reaction, stopping the threat of f5 in its tracks. As long as Black controls the f5-square with enough pieces so that a piece lands on it after all the exchanges, he is perfectly happy with this confrontation on the kingside. }
11. gxf5 exf5
{ The rule of thumb in practice: always take with the "other" pawn - if White takes with the g-pawn, recapture with the e-pawn; if White takes with the e-pawn, recapture with the g-pawn. }
12. Qd2 Bd7
{ The bishop wants to go to c6, as the long diagonal is the most important one it can occupy. }
13. Qf2
{ Attacking the d4-knight, so Black takes on f3 with tempo and continues with his plan. }
13... Nxf3+ 14. Bxf3 Bc6
{ Black has practically finished development. Generally speaking, in this structure he has two plans: 1. to push ...d5 and 2. to push ...b5-b4. As always the choice of plans depends on the concrete circumstances. }
15. Qg2 b6
{ Black decides to go for ...d5 by first defending the c5-pawn. The actual move ...d5 still isn't possible, but by putting the pawn on b6 Black abandons the plan of queenside expansion, which was a decent alternative. }
16. Rad1 Qc7
{ Removing the queen from the d-file, where White put his rook on, and plans to go ...Qb7, ...Rad8 and eventually, ...d5 }
17. Ne2 Rae8
{ The knight abandoned the control of d5, so now Black doesn't need a rook on d8 to support the ...d5 push. He uses this fact to put the rook on the e-file where two of White's light pieces are placed and from where it can exert pressure on the e4-pawn. Taking on b2 was possible, but very impractical - it would have distracted Black from a well-founded positional plan and it would have given White some compensation after c3 as the important dark-squared bishop would have been cut off from the kingside. }
18. Bc1
{ Removing an undefended piece from the e-file and defending the b2-pawn. }
18... Qb7 { Black proceeds with his plan. } 19. c4
{ A direct way to prevent ...d5, but one that opens up other possibilities for Black.  It was better to allow ... d5 and play   19.Ng3  d5  though   19...b5  may be better.  20.e5  d4  where Black has a more pleasant position, but White can certainly can play on. }
19... Qa6
{ A double attack - the pawn on a2 is hanging, but so is the pawn on c4, as Black threatens to take on e4 and remove the defender of the c4-pawn - the pawn on d3. }
20. Nc3
{ White didn't have much choice, but Black will manage to control his counterplay. }
20... fxe4 21. dxe4 Bd4+ { Closing the d-file. } 22. Kh1 Qxc4
{ Black won a pawn and kept control over the position. } 23. Rfe1 Kh8
{ Removing the king from the g-file just in case. } 24. Ne2 Bg7 25. b3 Qa6 26.
Ng3
{ Taking on d6 was met by taking on a2, both now and on the previous move. }
26... Qb7 27. Rg1
{ But now the same motif is even stronger.  Black consolidated and in case of   27.Rxd6  prepared  Nf5 !  with ...Nh4 to come. }
27... Nf5 28. Nxf5 Rxf5
{ Black is not only material up, he also has the initiative as White is under huge pressure to defend his central pawns. }
29. Rxd6 Bxe4 30. Bxe4 Qxe4 31. Qxe4 Rxe4
{ The endgame is winning for Black as White has no compensation for the pawn and also has the f4-pawn as an extra weakness. }
32. Rd8+ Rf8 33. Rxf8+ Bxf8 34. f5 Bg7 35. fxg6 Bd4 36. g7+ Kg8 37. Rf1 Kxg7
{ Black will play ...Re2 next with an easy win. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Timofeev, Artyom vs. Kasparov, Garry"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 Nc6 5. c3 g6 6. O-O Bg7 7. Bb3 O-O 8. Re1
b5 9. a3 a5 10. h3 Nd7
{ A constructive maneuver - the knight is removed from in front of the bishop and is transferred to b6, from where it will exert pressure on the queenside. }
11. Be3 a4 12. Bc2 Nb6 13. Nbd2 e5
{ Preventing d4. Without d4 White is left without a constructive plan and in such situations it is easy to to play something that only worsens your own position. }
14. b4
{ Even though the engine somewhat likes this, from a human perspective it is not very good: it weakens the a3-pawn and gives Black an easy plan of play against it. What White gets in return is not very clear as the activity of the bishop on b3 is far from being enough compensation. }
14... axb3 15. Bxb3 Bd7
{ Black's play is simple and straight-forward: to double on the a-file. } 16.
Qc2 Ra6 17. Reb1 Qa8 18. Qc1
{ White is completely tied down to the defence of the a3-pawn and has no counterplay whatsoever. Kasparov now continues to push forward and improve his position by including the rook from f8 in the game. }
18... Na5
{ First the knight liberates the c6-square for the queen. Then the queen will come to c6 to liberate the a8-square for the rook. }
19. Ba2 Qc6 20. d4
{ Desperation. White couldn't just sit and wait, but as usual in such cases the desperation hastens the end. }
20... c4
{ A typical reaction from the Spanish, but it was stronger to take on d4 first:   20...exd4  21.cxd4  Rc8  and the space advantage on the queenside plus the passed c-pawn will decide in Black's favour. }
21. dxe5 dxe5 22. Bxb6
{ The knight would have gone to a4 and c5, so White eliminates it, but now he will be weak on the dark squares. }
22... Rxb6 23. a4
{ White finally breaks the bind from the c4-pawn, but allows an outside passed a-pawn. }
23... bxa4 24. Rxb6 Qxb6 25. Nxc4 Nxc4 26. Bxc4 Qc5
{ Attacking the bishop and intending ...Ra8, ... a3 etc. } 27. Qd1 Qxc4
{ Kasparov goes for transformation of the advantage.  He could have played   27...Qc7  keeping the a-pawn, but instead decides to play for domination - the knight on f3 will lack good squares after ...e4 and the pawn on c3 will be weak. }
28. Qxd7 Qxe4 29. Qxa4 Qd3 30. c4
{ Trying to save the c-pawn, but Black's central domination is the decisive factor. }
30... e4 31. Rd1 Qe2 32. Nh2 Bc3 { Black's pieces dominate. } 33. Rf1
{ Defending against ...Be1. } 33... Bd4
{ It was better to limit the knight by ...h5 first. } 34. Qc6
{ White misses the chance to bring the knight back into the game by Ng4, as after   34.Ng4  h5  he has  35.c5 !  and the bishop must stay on the long diagonal to prevent Nf6+ but that would allow the knight to come back to e3. }
34... h5
{ Kasparov doesn't allow a second chance and controls the game until the end. }
35. Qd5 Qd3 36. g4
{ White was paralysed, so just as in the first half of the game, when he was paralysed on the queenside, this time he desperately tries to break up the grip on the kingside. }
36... hxg4 37. hxg4 Kg7 { Black will use the h-file to finish the game off. }
38. Kg2 Rh8 39. Qd6 Qh3+ 40. Kg1 Qd3 41. Kg2 Qh3+ 42. Kg1 Qc3
{ With the threat of ...Be5. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Aronian, Levon vs. Carlsen, Magnus"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Bc4 Be7 5. d3 d6 6. O-O Nf6 7. h3
{ Not a very ambitious move whose idea is to play in a similar manner to the Spanish. White wants to play Ne2-g3.  In the theoretical part we examined the more aggressive   7.Ng5  followed by f4. }
7... O-O 8. Ne2 a6
{ Carlsen decides to copy Aronian and treat the position as a Spanish. The threat is to play ...b5 and ...Na5, taking the light-squared bishop. Of course, Black could have played differently.  For example, there was nothing wrong with the immediate   8...Be6  which in case of an exchange on e6 would have saved a tempo for Black  (as in that case the move ...a6 isn't needed)  .  Another idea for Black is to play   8...d5  9.exd5  Nxd5  followed by ...Be6 and ...f6, with strong central control.  An interesting and more aggressive idea for Black is   8...Nh5  with the idea of  9.Ng3  Nf4  or otherwise ...Kh8 and ...f5. }
9. a3 { White makes sure he preserves the bishop. } 9... b5 10. Ba2 Be6
{ Black grabbed space in typical Spanish fashion and now neutralises the bishop on a2. }
11. Bxe6 { If White didn't take Black could take on a2 and push ...d5. } 11...
fxe6 12. Ng3 d5
{ The maneuver ...Nd7-b6 was possible here - it opens the f-file and also increases Black's queenside presence. With the game move Black increases his space advantage. }
13. Re1 d4
{ Black now has the natural plan to push ...c4 and play on the queenside. Note that the pawn on e6 is very useful in controlling the f5-square and the open f-file can be used by Black as we will soon see. }
14. c3 { This is a way to defend against ... c4 } 14... Kh8
{ Avoiding trouble along the a2-g8 diagonal after Qb3, but the more direct   14...Nd7  was possible, with the idea of  15.Qb3  c4 !  16.dxc4  a5 }
15. Qe2
{ This was a blitz game, so the players didn't always take their best chances.  This move simply develops, but White could have been more active with a move like   15.a4 }
15... Nd7 { Black continues now with his intended plan. } 16. Bd2 Na5
{ Even though 16.. .Nb6 was probably better, this move has an interesting tactical idea in mind. }
17. cxd4
{ Aronian falls for it.  It was better to play   17.b4  attacking the knight. }
17... Nb3 18. dxe5 Rxf3
{ This was probably missed by White. He would have liked to sacrifice the exchange on a1 for great central pawns, but in fact it is Black who sacrifices the exchange and starts to dominate the whole board with his knights ! }
19. gxf3
{ White decides to keep the material advantage.  In case of   19.Qxf3  Nxe5  20.Qe2  Nxa1  21.Rxa1  Nxd3  Black is clearly better - the knight on d3 is a beast that will be defended by ...c4. }
19... Nxd2
{ Spoiling it a bit.  The dominating   19...Nd4  20.Qd1  Nxe5  would have led to a picturesque position with the knights ruling the board. }
20. Qxd2 Nxe5 21. Qe3 Nxd3 22. Rad1 c4
{ Black has good compensation for the exchange, but White should be fine here. }
23. Rxd3
{ But not like this !  This is panic, there was no need to immediately return the material as he could have done that when the queen moved from the d-file, for example after   23.f4  Qc7  24.Rxd3 }
23... Qxd3 24. Qxd3 cxd3
{ The endgame is better for Black. The bishop is better than the knight in this open position and the pawn on d3 is dangerous and it cannot be captured. }
25. Rd1 Rd8 26. f4 b4
{ With the exchange of pawns Black gains access to the b4-square for the bishop from where it can defend the d-pawn once it arrives on d2. }
27. axb4 { The same would happen after   27.a4  b3 } 27... Bxb4 28. Kg2 d2
{ Black now wants to play . ..Rd3-b3, so White brings the king to the defence in order to control the d2-pawn. }
29. Kf3 Rd3+ 30. Ke2 Rb3 31. Rb1 Kg8
{ Black maximised the activity of his pieces and now only the king remains to be included in the game. }
32. Nf1
{ White finally manages to capture the pawn on d2, but Black manages to exchange it for another one and continues to press. }
32... d1=Q+
{ Taking on h3 was another option that gave Black an outside passed pawn on the h-file. }
33. Kxd1 Rf3 34. Ke2 Rxf4 35. Ng3 Bc5
{ We now see the transformation of the advantage - White has pawn weaknesses he needs to defend. Objectively White should be able to draw, but in practice  (and particularly against Carlsen !)  these positions are difficult to save. }
36. f3 Rh4 37. Rh1 Kf7
{ White is passive and Black keeps on improving his position. } 38. Nf1 Kf6 39.
Nd2 Ke5 40. Nb3 Bb6 41. Nc1 Kf6
{ Avoiding a check from d3. There is no clear breakthrough for Black, but he continues to play from a more comfortable position. }
42. Nd3 a5 43. f4
{ White cannot withstand the pressure and feels the need to do something active, but this just opens the game more after Black's next and exposes White's weaknesses. From a practical point of view it makes White's position more difficult to play than it was. }
43... g5 44. Kf3 gxf4 45. Nxf4 Bc7 { Now all White's pawns need protection. }
46. Nd3 Rh5 47. Rf1 Ke7 48. Kg4 Rb5
{ Carlsen switches the attack. Again, objectively this is a draw, but White isn't there yet. }
49. Rc1 h5+ 50. Kf3 Bd6 51. Rc3 Rg5
{ Carlsen again switches sides. This is a very instructive method of play in similar positions. }
52. Kf2 h4 53. Rb3
{ This allows Black to play ...Rg3, attacking the h3-pawn, as his intended defence fails. White allowed a bit too much  (it was better to stop ... h4 by playing h4 himself, but understandably he didn't want to put a pawn on a square with the same colour as the bishop)  . }
53... Rg3 54. Nc1 { This was White's defensive idea, but it doesn't suffice. }
54... Bc5+
{ It was also possible to take on b3 and play ...a4, fixing the pawn on b2. }
55. Ke2 Bd4 { White will lose a pawn now, as he cannot defend both b2 and h3. }
56. Rb7+ Kf6 57. Nb3 Bxb2 58. Nxa5 Rxh3
{ A nice tactic. The bishop is taboo in view of ...Rh2. The rest of the game was smooth sailing for Carlsen until he messed it up, but Aronian missed this accidental chance. }
59. Nc4 Bd4 60. Rd7 e5
{ Sooner or later White will also lose the e4-pawn as it cannot be defended. }
61. Nd2 Re3+ 62. Kf1 h3 63. Rh7 Kg5 64. Nc4 Rf3+ 65. Ke2 Rf2+ 66. Ke1 Rh2 67.
Nd6 Kf4 68. Rf7+ Ke3 69. Nf5+ Kxe4
{ This should have been over in a few moves, but for some reason Carlsen didn't wrap it up. }
70. Ng3+ Kd5 71. Ne2 Rh1+
{ It was faster to go   71...Rg2  with ...h2 to come. } 72. Kd2 Ra1 73. Rh7
Ra2+ 74. Kd1 Ra3 75. Rh5 Ke6 76. Kd2 Kf6 77. Rh8 Kg5 78. Rg8+ Kf5 79. Ng3+ Ke6
80. Ne2 h2 81. Rh8 Be3+ 82. Kc2 Ra2+ 83. Kd3 Bf4
{ Going   83...Bg1  or giving another check on a3 was still easily winning, while this curiously enough allows White to draw. }
84. Nxf4+ exf4 85. Ke4 Rf2 86. Rh3
{ But White misses his chance. Perhaps not surprising in a blitz game that was most likely played on increment time for quite some time up to here.  The saving resource was   86.Rh6+  pushing the king back and after  Kf7  87.Kf5  Black cannot make progress. }
86... Kf6 { Now the king joins the pawns and it's over. } 87. Rh8 Kg5 88. Rh7
Kg4 89. Rg7+ Kh3 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Laird, Craig vs. Azmaiparashvili, Zurab"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6
{ The game starts with a Pirc and for some time Black doesn't even play ...c5, but after 9 moves we do get a transposition to the Sicilian. }
2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c3 g6 4. Bd3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. Re1 Bg4 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 c5 9.
Bf1 Nc6
{ This position usually arises after 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. c3 Nf6 4. Be2 g6 5. O-O Bg7 6. Re1 O-O 7. Bf1 Bg4   in the theoretical section we analyse  7...Nc6  8.h3  e5  8. h3 Bf3 9. Qf3 Nc6. Even though we do not enter in this exact position in our repertoire, the reason being the move 8. Nbd2   instead of  8.h3  which would allow White to recapture on f3 with the knight, Black's queenside attack is very instructive and can be applied in similar positions, like the ones mentioned in the theoretical part   arising after  3.g3  . }
10. Na3 { The knight is transferred to c2 from where it will support d4. }
10... Qa5
{ Black activates the queen and intends ...b5 in case White goes 11 Nc2. } 11.
Nc4
{ So White changes plans and gains tempo by attacking the queen, but now the knight cannot support the d4-push. }
11... Qc7 12. a4 { Preventing ...b5, but not for long. } 12... a6 13. d3 b5 14.
Ne3 b4
{ Black plays simply and directly. His queenside play develops naturally. } 15.
Bd2 Rab8 { The b-file will be opened so Black prepares for it beforehand. } 16.
Nc4 Nd7
{ Another typical move in these structures. The knight opens the long diagonal for the bishop and can later go to e5 or b6. }
17. Qd1 Rb7 { Black wants to double on the b-file. } 18. Qc1 bxc3 19. bxc3 Rfb8
{ Now Black is ready to come to b3 with the rook. At some point he will look to exchange the knight on c4 as it is White's most active piece. }
20. Bh6 Bh8
{ Of course, the fianchettoed bishop is very important and should be preserved. It defends the king and exerts pressure on c3. }
21. Ra2
{ White is very passive, though his position is solid and he can play without making further concessions. }
21... Rb1 22. Qd2
{ White couldn't exchange the queen for two rooks because in that case the pawn on c3 would be lost. }
22... Qb7
{ Black is controlling the only open file. For now it doesn't bring him much, but it is already clear that his opening strategy has been a success. White didn't even manage to push d4, let alone create something more while Black pursues his own queenside play. }
23. f4
{ A typical mistake of a player who is suffering under pressure and without counterplay. Humans are not good at suffering patiently ! This only creates new weaknesses and allows Black to finally penetrate.  The patient move   23.Rc1  would have kept it tight. }
23... Rxe1 24. Qxe1 Qb1
{ The queen on b1 is much more effective than a rook ! } 25. Qd2 Nb6
{ Exchanging White's only active piece. } 26. Rb2
{ Maybe White was hoping for this, but it loses.  Though White is probably lost even after the best   26.Nxb6  Rxb6  as he can do nothing to defend the weaknesses on c3 and a4. }
26... Nxc4 27. Rxb8+ Nxb8 28. dxc4 Qxe4
{ Black won a pawn and has a winning position. He still has a very compact position while White's position is in ruins. }
29. Bd3 Qb7 30. f5 Nd7 31. fxg6 hxg6 32. Qc2 Ne5
{ Black's ideal structure and the untouchable knight coupled with White's wrecked structure  (in addition to the extra pawn)  make this position an easy technical win. }
33. Be2 Qd7 34. Bg5 Bf6
{ The bishop can be exchanged now as the exchanges favour Black. } 35. Bxf6
exf6 36. a5 Qc7 37. Qa4 Qb7 38. Qd1 Qe4 { Playing on domination. } 39. Bf1 Qe3+
40. Kh1 Qf2
{ There was nothing wrong with picking up more pawns after   40...Qxc3  but now it is all a matter of taste. }
41. Be2 Kg7 42. Bf1 Nc6 43. Bd3 Nxa5 44. Qa1 Nc6 45. Qxa6 Ne5 46. Qxd6 Qd2
{ Winning the hapless bishop. An excellent demonstration of Black's queenside play ! }
*

